orean boy bands]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2018]]\n[[Category:South Korean pop music groups]]\n[[Category:KQ Entertainment artists]]\n[[Category:MTV EMA winners]]\n", "name_user": "PeaceNT", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2020: Treasure Epilogue:fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ateez"}
{"title_page": "Anna Iwaszkiewicz", "text_new": " {{Completed}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Anna Iwaszkiewicz\n| image              = Anna Iwaszkiewicz with parrot - Stanis\u0142aw Wilhelm Lilpop.jpg\n| birth_name         = Anna Lilpop\n| birth_date         = 17 December 1897\n| birth_place        = [[Brwin\u00f3w]], [[Congress Poland|Poland]]\n| death_date         = 23 December 1979\n| death_place        = Stawisko, [[Polish People's Republic|Poland]]\n| resting_place      = Roman-Catholic Cemetery in Brwin\u00f3w\n| occupation         = Writer and translator\n| nationality        = Polish\n| parents            = Stanis\u0142aw Wilhelm Lilpop and Jadwiga nee Stankiewicz\n| spouse             = [[Jaros\u0142aw Iwaszkiewicz]]\n| children           = Maria and Teresa\n}}\n'''Anna Iwaszkiewicz''', born Lilpop, [[pen name]]: '''Adam Podkowi\u0144ski'''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://sprawiedliwi.org.pl/en/stories-of-rescue/story-rescue-iwaszkiewicz-family|title=Story of Rescue - The Iwaszkiewicz Family {{!}} Polscy Sprawiedliwi|website=sprawiedliwi.org.pl|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite book|title=Homobiografie|author=Tomasik, Krzysztof, 1978-|location=Warszawa|isbn=978-83-64682-22-3|oclc=915291354}}</ref> (born [[December 17]], [[1897]] in [[Brwin\u00f3w]], died [[December 23]], [[1979]] in Stawisko) \u2013 [[Polish People|Polish]] writer and translator, wife of the writer [[Jaros\u0142aw Iwaszkiewicz]].\n\n== Early years ==\nWhen Anna was four years old, her mother Jadwiga Stankiewicz left her and her father, a wealthy industrialist Stanis\u0142aw Wilhelm Lilpop, for the pianist [[J\u00f3zef \u015aliwi\u0144ski]]. From then on, her father and aunt Aniela Pilawitz brought her up, while her mother was denied any contact with Anna. From 1915 to 1918, she stayed with her father in [[Russia]], particularly in [[Moscow]] and [[Kiev]]. Her time in Russia contributed to the formation of her literary talent as she studied at the Moscow Polish University, learned foreign languages, and became interested in music and theater. In Russia, she acquired knowledge about the work of [[Alexander Scriabin|Scriabin]], who would later become her favorite composer and whose music she would promote in Poland by organizing his music concerts in [[Warsaw]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|title=Muzeum im. Anny i Jaros\u0142awa Iwaszkiewicz\u00f3w w Stawisku|url=http://www.stawisko.pl/index.php?anna_iwaszkiewicz|agency=www.stawisko.pl|accessdate=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n== Marriage ==\n[[File:Anna Iwaszkiewiczowa with daughter - Stanis\u0142aw Wilhelm Lilpop.jpg|thumb|left|Anna Iwaszkiewicz with a daughter (1924)]]\nOn September 12, 1922, after overcoming the initial resistance of her father, she married [[Jaros\u0142aw Iwaszkiewicz]] (back then a beginner poet). For Iwaszkiewicz, she broke off an engagement to Prince [[Krzysztof Radziwi\u0142\u0142]], arranged several years ago.<ref name=\":1\" /> Through her marriage she gained the opportunity to establish contacts with the artistic and literary community.\n\nShe gave birth to daughters: Maria and Teresa. \n\n== Literary activity ==\n\nAnna published mostly essays on the works of [[Marcel Proust]], [[Joseph Conrad]] and [[Thomas Mann]] (partly under a pseudonym). She translated mainly French literature (Marcel Proust, [[Michel Butor]], [[Alain-Fournier]], [[Jules Verne]]) and English-language literature (Thomas Marton and [[Alfred North Whitehead]]). At the end of her life, she published the book ''Nasze zwierz\u0119ta'' (''Our Animals'') (1978). Her most outstanding work is ''Dzienniki i wspomnienia'' (''Diaries and Memoirs'') (published in 2000), containing valuable descriptions of life in the interwar period and memories of, among others, [[Karol Szymanowski]] - a relative of Anna's husband.\n\n== Personality ==\n[[File:Brwinow, grob Jaroslawa i Anny Iwaszkiewiczow.jpg|thumb|left|Anna and Jaros\u0142aw's grave in Brwin\u00f3w]]\nAnna was a sensitive and difficult person.\n\nHer husband did not hide his orientation and having male lovers from her, while Anna herself was bisexual.<ref name=\":1\" /> Nonetheless, Iwaszkiewicz couple considered their marriage happy and successful.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nAnna had mental health issues, including [[Depression (mood)|depression]]. She coped with it by being a devoted Catholic. Anna hat written for journals for many years, showcasing her literary talent and personality.\n\nDuring the [[German occupation of Poland|German occupation]], she helped [[Polish Jews]] by organizing their escape from the [[Ghetto]] and hiding them in [[Stawisko]]. For this activity, on January 21, 1988, she and her husband were honored with the award of [[Righteous Among the Nations]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iwaszkiewicz, Anna}}\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1979 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish women writers\u200e]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Poland]]\n[[Category:Polish memoirists]]\n[[Category:Polish translators]]\n[[Category:Polish Righteous Among the Nations]]\n[[Category:Bisexual women]]\n", "text_old": " {{Completed}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Anna Iwaszkiewicz\n| image              = Anna Iwaszkiewicz with parrot - Stanis\u0142aw Wilhelm Lilpop.jpg\n| birth_name         = Anna Lilpop\n| birth_date         = 17 December 1897\n| birth_place        = [[Brwin\u00f3w]], [[Congress Poland|Poland]]\n| death_date         = 23 December 1979\n| death_place        = Stawisko, [[Polish People's Republic|Poland]]\n| resting_place      = Roman-Catholic Cemetery in Brwin\u00f3w\n| occupation         = Writer and translator\n| nationality        = Polish\n| parents            = Stanis\u0142aw Wilhelm Lilpop and Jadwiga nee Stankiewicz\n| spouse             = [[Jaros\u0142aw Iwaszkiewicz]]\n| children           = Maria and Teresa\n}}\n'''Anna Iwaszkiewicz''', born Lilpop, [[pen name]] '''Adam Podkowi\u0144ski'''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://sprawiedliwi.org.pl/en/stories-of-rescue/story-rescue-iwaszkiewicz-family|title=Story of Rescue - The Iwaszkiewicz Family {{!}} Polscy Sprawiedliwi|website=sprawiedliwi.org.pl|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite book|title=Homobiografie|author=Tomasik, Krzysztof, 1978-|location=Warszawa|isbn=978-83-64682-22-3|oclc=915291354}}</ref> (born [[December 17]], [[1897]] in [[Brwin\u00f3w]], died [[December 23]], [[1979]] in Stawisko) \u2013 [[Polish People|Polish]] writer and translator, wife of the writer [[Jaros\u0142aw Iwaszkiewicz]].\n\n== Early years ==\nWhen Anna was four years old, her mother Jadwiga Stankiewicz left her and her father, a wealthy industrialist Stanis\u0142aw Wilhelm Lilpop, for the pianist [[J\u00f3zef \u015aliwi\u0144ski]]. From then on, her father and aunt Aniela Pilawitz brought her up, while her mother was denied any contact with Anna. From 1915 to 1918, she stayed with her father in [[Russia]], particularly in [[Moscow]] and [[Kiev]]. Her time in Russia contributed to the formation of her literary talent as she studied at the Moscow Polish University, learned foreign languages, and became interested in music and theater. In Russia, she acquired knowledge about the work of [[Alexander Scriabin|Scriabin]], who would later become her favorite composer and whose music she would promote in Poland by organizing his music concerts in [[Warsaw]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|title=Muzeum im. Anny i Jaros\u0142awa Iwaszkiewicz\u00f3w w Stawisku|url=http://www.stawisko.pl/index.php?anna_iwaszkiewicz|agency=www.stawisko.pl|accessdate=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\n== Marriage ==\n[[File:Anna Iwaszkiewiczowa with daughter - Stanis\u0142aw Wilhelm Lilpop.jpg|thumb|left|Anna Iwaszkiewicz with a daughter (1924)]]\nOn September 12, 1922, after overcoming the initial resistance of her father, she married [[Jaros\u0142aw Iwaszkiewicz]] (back then a beginner poet). For Iwaszkiewicz, she broke off an engagement to Prince [[Krzysztof Radziwi\u0142\u0142]], arranged several years ago.<ref name=\":1\" /> Through her marriage she gained the opportunity to establish contacts with the artistic and literary community.\n\nShe gave birth to daughters: Maria and Teresa. \n\n== Literary activity ==\n\nAnna published mostly essays on the works of [[Marcel Proust]], [[Joseph Conrad]] and [[Thomas Mann]] (partly under a pseudonym). She translated mainly French literature (Marcel Proust, [[Michel Butor]], [[Alain-Fournier]], [[Jules Verne]]) and English-language literature (Thomas Marton and [[Alfred North Whitehead]]). At the end of her life, she published the book ''Nasze zwierz\u0119ta'' (''Our Animals'') (1978). Her most outstanding work is ''Dzienniki i wspomnienia'' (''Diaries and Memoirs'') (published in 2000), containing valuable descriptions of life in the interwar period and memories of, among others, [[Karol Szymanowski]] - a relative of Anna's husband.\n\n== Personality ==\n[[File:Brwinow, grob Jaroslawa i Anny Iwaszkiewiczow.jpg|thumb|left|Anna and Jaros\u0142aw's grave in Brwin\u00f3w]]\nAnna was a sensitive and difficult person.\n\nHer husband did not hide his orientation and having male lovers from her, while Anna herself was bisexual.<ref name=\":1\" /> Nonetheless, Iwaszkiewicz couple considered their marriage happy and successful.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nAnna had mental health issues, including [[Depression (mood)|depression]]. She coped with it by being a devoted Catholic. Anna hat written for journals for many years, showcasing her literary talent and personality.\n\nDuring the [[German occupation of Poland|German occupation]], she helped [[Polish Jews]] by organizing their escape from the [[Ghetto]] and hiding them in [[Stawisko]]. For this activity, on January 21, 1988, she and her husband were honored with the award of [[Righteous Among the Nations]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iwaszkiewicz, Anna}}\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1979 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish women writers\u200e]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Poland]]\n[[Category:Polish memoirists]]\n[[Category:Polish translators]]\n[[Category:Polish Righteous Among the Nations]]\n[[Category:Bisexual women]]\n", "name_user": "Visioncurve", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anna_Iwaszkiewicz"}
{"title_page": "Robbie Haines", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox sailor\n| name           = Robbie Haines\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = Robert Bentley Haines, Jr.\n| nickname       = \n| nationality    = \n| birth_date     = {{birth-date and age|March 27, 1954}}\n| birth_place    = [[San Diego, California]], U.S.\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| classes        = \n| club           = \n| collegeteam    = \n| coach          = \n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport| [[Sailing at the Summer Olympics|Sailing]] }}\n{{Medal|Country| the {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition| [[Olympic Games]] }}\n{{MedalGold| [[1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Los Angeles]] | [[Sailing at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling|Soling]] }}\n}}\n\n'''Robert Bentley Haines, Jr.''' (born March 27, 1954) is an American [[sailor]] and [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] champion. Born in [[San Diego, California]], he has won seven world championships in 4 different class of boats. He was associate producer and sailing team manager for the Walt Disney film [[Morning Light (film)|\"Morning Light\"]]. He was awarded the Congressional Gold Medal for being a member of the 1980 US Olympic Sailing Team, which did not compete in the Soviet Union (Estonia) due to the boycott of the Olympic Games that year by President [[Jimmy Carter]].\n\nHaines, skipper of the Haines-[[Edward Trevelyan|Trevelyan]]-[[Rod Davis (sailor)|Davis]] team, received a gold medal in the ''[[Soling]] class'' at the [[1984 Summer Olympics]] in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=sports-ref>{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ha/robbie-haines-1.html |title=Robbie Haines |accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref> Haines was inducted into the San Diego Sports Hall of Fame in 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.coronadonewsca.com/news/coronado_island_news/olympic-sailing-gold-medalist-robbie-haines-inducted-into-san-diego/article_723a03e6-1042-11e8-b30d-9b9d776557c6.html|newspaper=[[Coronado Eagle & Journal]]|title= Olympic Sailing Gold Medalist Robbie Haines Inducted Into San Diego Sports Hall Of Fame|first=David|last=Axelson|date=February 12, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n{{Footer American Championship Winners in Soling}}\n{{Footer North American Champions Soling}}\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Soling}}\n{{Footer World Champions Soling}}\n{{Authority control}}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{sports links}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haines, Robbie}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:North American Champions Soling]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for the United States in sailing]]\n[[Category:Olympic sailors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling]]\n[[Category:Soling class world champions]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from San Diego]]\n\n\n{{US-yachtracing-Olympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox sailor\n| name           = Robbie Haines\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = Robert Bentley Haines, Jr.\n| nickname       = \n| nationality    = \n| birth_date     = {{birth-date and age|March 27, 1954}}\n| birth_place    = [[San Diego, California]], U.S.\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| classes        = \n| club           = \n| collegeteam    = \n| coach          = \n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport| [[Sailing at the Summer Olympics|Sailing]] }}\n{{Medal|Country| the {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition| [[Olympic Games]] }}\n{{MedalGold| [[1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Los Angeles]] | [[Sailing at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling|Soling]] }}\n}}\n\n'''Robert Bentley Haines, Jr.''' (born March 27, 1954) is an American [[sailor]] and [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] champion. Born in [[San Diego, California]], he has won seven world championships in 4 different class of boats. He was associate producer and sailing team manager for the Walt Disney film [[Morning Light (film)|\"Morning Light\"]]. He was awarded the Congressional Gold Medal for being a member of the 1980 US Olympic Sailing Team, which did not compete in the Soviet Union (Estonia) due to the boycott of the Olympic Games that year by President [[Jimmy Carter]].\n\nHaines, skipper of the Haines-[[Edward Trevelyan|Trevelyan]]-[[Rod Davis (sailor)|Davis]] team, received a gold medal in the ''[[Soling]] class'' at the [[1984 Summer Olympics]] in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=sports-ref>{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ha/robbie-haines-1.html |title=Robbie Haines |accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref> Haines was inducted into the San Diego Sports Hall of Fame in 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.coronadonewsca.com/news/coronado_island_news/olympic-sailing-gold-medalist-robbie-haines-inducted-into-san-diego/article_723a03e6-1042-11e8-b30d-9b9d776557c6.html|newspaper=[[Coronado Eagle & Journal]]|title= Olympic Sailing Gold Medalist Robbie Haines Inducted Into San Diego Sports Hall Of Fame|first=David|last=Axelson|date=February 12, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{sports links}}\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Soling}}\n{{Footer World Champions Soling}}\n{{Footer North American Champions Soling}}\n{{Footer American Championship Winners in Soling}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haines, Robbie}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Olympic sailors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for the United States in sailing]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1984 Summer 