{"title_page": "Christopher Nolan", "text_new": "{{Other people|Christopher Nolan}}\n{{short description|British\u2013American filmmaker}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Christopher Nolan\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}}\n| image            = Christopher Nolan Cannes 2018.jpg\n| caption          = Nolan at the [[2018 Cannes Film Festival]]\n| birth_name       = Christopher Edward Nolan\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1970|7|30}}\n| birth_place      = [[Westminster]], [[London]], England\n| citizenship      = {{hlist|United Kingdom|United States}}\n| alma_mater       = [[University College London]]\n| occupation       = Filmmaker\n| years_active     = 1989\u2013present\n| works            = [[Christopher Nolan filmography|Full list]]\n| spouse           = {{marriage|[[Emma Thomas]]|1997}}\n| children         = 4\n| relatives        = [[Jonathan Nolan]] (brother)<br />[[John Nolan (British actor)|John Nolan]] (uncle)<br />[[Lisa Joy]] (sister-in-law)\n| awards           = [[List of awards and nominations received by Christopher Nolan|Full list]]\n}}\n\n'''Christopher Edward Nolan''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE}} ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|n|o\u028a|l|\u0259|n}}; born 30 July 1970) is a British-American filmmaker known for making personal, distinctive films within the [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]] mainstream. [[Christopher Nolan filmography|His ten films]] have grossed over US$4.7{{nbsp}}billion worldwide and garnered a total of 34 [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] nominations and ten wins.\n\nBorn and raised in [[London]], Nolan developed an interest in filmmaking from a young age. After studying English literature at [[University College London]], he made his feature debut with ''[[Following]]'' (1998). Nolan gained international recognition with his second film, ''[[Memento (film)|Memento]]'' (2000), for which he was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay]]. He transitioned from independent to studio filmmaking with ''[[Insomnia (2002 film)|Insomnia]]'' (2002), and found further critical and commercial success with ''[[The Dark Knight Trilogy]]'' (2005\u20132012), ''[[The Prestige (film)|The Prestige]]'' (2006), and ''[[Inception]]'' (2010), which received eight Oscar nominations, including for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] and Best Original Screenplay. This was followed by ''[[Interstellar (film)|Interstellar]]'' (2014) and ''[[Dunkirk (2017 film)|Dunkirk]]'' (2017), the latter of which earned him Academy Award nominations for Best Picture and [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]].\n\nNolan's films are typically rooted in [[Epistemology|epistemological]] and [[Metaphysics|metaphysical]] themes, exploring human morality, the construction of [[time]], and the malleable nature of [[memory]] and [[personal identity]]. [[Cinematic style of Christopher Nolan|His work]] is permeated by unconventional [[Nonlinear narrative|narrative structures]], [[practical special effects]], experimental soundscapes, [[70 mm film|large-format]] film photography, and [[Materialism|materialistic]] perspectives. He has co-written several of his films with his brother [[Jonathan Nolan|Jonathan]], and runs the production company [[Syncopy Inc.]] with his wife [[Emma Thomas]].\n\nNolan has received many [[List of awards and nominations received by Christopher Nolan|awards and honours]]. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine named him one of the [[Time 100|100 most influential people in the world]] in 2015, and in 2019, he was appointed Commander of the [[Order of the British Empire]] for his services to film. In addition to his filmmaking, Nolan is an advocate for [[film preservation]] and the [[film stock|analog medium]].\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Life and career ==\n=== 1970\u20131997: Early life and career beginnings ===\nNolan was born in [[Westminster]], [[London]], and grew up in [[Highgate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2bbfd6e83e|title=Christopher Nolan|publisher=British Film Institute (BFI)|accessdate=4 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311164847/http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2bbfd6e83e|archive-date=11 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=Fuv8tRfxQgrEic7cP%2Bx9Rg&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=8 March 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> His father, Brendan James Nolan, was a British advertising executive who worked as a creative director.<ref>Mooney, p. 3.</ref> His mother, Christina (n\u00e9e Jensen), was an American [[flight attendant]] who would later work as an English teacher.<ref>Mooney, p. 3.</ref><ref name=\"Shone2014\" /><ref name=\"Feinberg\">{{cite magazine|title=Christopher Nolan on 'Interstellar' Critics, Making Original Films and Shunning Cell Phones and Email (Q&A)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/christopher-nolan-interstellar-critics-making-760897|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|author=Feinberg, Scott|date=3 January 2015|accessdate=1 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117111636/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/christopher-nolan-interstellar-critics-making-760897|archive-date=17 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Nolan's childhood was split between London and [[Evanston, Illinois]], and he has both British and US citizenship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/ct-interstellar-christopher-nolan-20141030-column.html|title=Christopher Nolan injects his sci-fi with soul|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=7 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308133759/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/ct-interstellar-christopher-nolan-20141030-column.html|archive-date=8 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Boucher\">{{cite news|url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/2010/04/11/christopher-nolans-inception-hollywoods-first-existential-heist-film|title=Christopher Nolan's 'Inception'&nbsp;\u2014 Hollywood's first existential heist film|last=Boucher|first=Geoff|date=11 April 2010|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=28 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110204203937/http://herocomplex.latimes.com/2010/04/11/christopher-nolans-inception-hollywoods-first-existential-heist-film/|archive-date=4 February 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Itzkoff|first=Dave|title=The Man Behind the Dreamscape|work=The New York Times|date=30 June 2010|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/04/movies/04inception.html|accessdate=1 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114141507/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/04/movies/04inception.html|archive-date=14 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Christopher Nolan's Inception tops British box office|work=BBC|date=22 July 2010|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/threecounties/hi/front_page/newsid_8845000/8845715.stm|accessdate=5 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917015720/http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/threecounties/hi/front_page/newsid_8845000/8845715.stm|archive-date=17 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He has an older brother, Matthew Francis Nolan, a convicted criminal,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-07-07/news/ct-met-escape-sentencing-20100707_1_costa-rica-fake-british-passport-extradited|title=Nolan sentenced for escape attempt|work=Chicago Tribune|date=7 July 2010|accessdate=24 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821110202/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-07-07/news/ct-met-escape-sentencing-20100707_1_costa-rica-fake-british-passport-extradited|archive-date=21 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and a younger brother, [[Jonathan Nolan|Jonathan]].<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news|title=Christopher Nolan interview for Inception|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmmakersonfilm/7894376/Christopher-Nolan-interview-for-Inception.html|newspaper=The Telegraph|author=Lawrence, Will|date=19 July 2012|accessdate=3 January 2014|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131117141943/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmmakersonfilm/7894376/Christopher-Nolan-interview-for-Inception.html|archive-date=17 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Growing up, Nolan was particularly influenced by the work of [[Ridley Scott]], and the science fiction films ''[[2001: A Space Odyssey (film)|2001: A Space Odyssey]]'' (1968) and ''[[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]]'' (1977).<ref>Mooney, p. 4.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/hollywood/on-christopher-nolan-s-birthday-how-many-of-his-15-favourite-films-have-you-seen/story-Ol1qwIWL9hBUQTS9ZkqICO.html|title=On Christopher Nolan\u2019s birthday, how many of his 15 favourite films have you seen?|work=Hindustan Times|date=31 July 2019|accessdate=2 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190928034554/https://www.hindustantimes.com/hollywood/on-christopher-nolan-s-birthday-how-many-of-his-15-favourite-films-have-you-seen/story-Ol1qwIWL9hBUQTS9ZkqICO.html|archive-date=28 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He began making films at age seven, borrowing his father's [[Super 8 mm film|Super{{nbsp}}8 camera]] and shooting short films with his action figures.<ref name=\"Timberg\">{{cite web|url=http://cinefiles.bampfa.berkeley.edu/cinefiles/DocDetail?docId=49987|last=Timberg|first=Scott|title=Indie Angst|work=New Times Los Angeles|accessdate=4 June 2013|date=15 March 2001|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815135228/https://cinefiles.bampfa.berkeley.edu/cinefiles/DocDetail?docId=49987|archive-date=15 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/film/nolans-move-from-highgate-to-hollywood-7381904.html \"Nolan's move from Highgate to Hollywood\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826194400/https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/film/nolans-move-from-highgate-to-hollywood-7381904.html |date=26 August 2017 }}, ''Evening Standard'' (London); retrieved 10 April 2011.</ref> These films included a [[Stop motion|stop motion animation]] homage to ''Star Wars'' called ''Space Wars''. He cast his brother Jonathan and built sets from \"clay, flour, egg boxes and toilet rolls.\"<ref>Mooney, p. 4.</ref> His uncle, who worked at [[NASA]] building guidance systems for the [[Apollo program|Apollo]] rockets, sent him some launch footage: \"I re-filmed them off the screen and cut them in, thinking no-one would notice,\" Nolan later remarked.<ref name=\"Shone2014\">{{cite journal|last=Shone|first=Tom|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/nov/04/-sp-christopher-nolan-interstellar-rebooted-blockbuster|title=Christopher Nolan: the man who rebooted the blockbuster|journal=The Guardian|date=4 November 2014|accessdate=24 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122014558/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/nov/04/-sp-christopher-nolan-interstellar-rebooted-blockbuster|archive-date=22 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andrewpurcell.net/?p=2000|title=Christopher Nolan's final frontier|publisher=Andrew Purcell|accessdate=7 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518084035/http://www.andrewpurcell.net/?p=2000|archive-date=18 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Covert|first=Colin|url=http://blog.startribune.com/christopher-nolan-explains-his-cinematic-brain-at-walker-art-center/302854481|title=Christopher Nolan explains his 'cinematic brain' at Walker Art Center|journal=StarTribune|accessdate=6 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150510011838/http://blog.startribune.com/christopher-nolan-explains-his-cinematic-brain-at-walker-art-center/302854481/|archive-date=10 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> From the age of eleven, he aspired to be a professional filmmaker.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/> In his teenage years, Nolan started making films with Adrien and [[Roko Belic]]. Nolan and Roko co\u2013directed the [[surrealism|surreal]] [[Super 8 film|8{{nbsp}}mm]] ''Tarantella'' (1989), which was shown on ''Image Union'', an independent film and video showcase on the [[Public Broadcasting Service]].{{refn|group=note|Nolan has continued his collaboration with the brothers, receiving a credit for his editorial assistance on their Oscar-nominated documentary ''[[Genghis Blues]]'' (1999).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicdoc.se/genghis-blues|title=Genghis Blues|publisher=Musicdoc.se|accessdate=2 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815062817/http://www.musicdoc.se/genghis-blues/|archive-date=15 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Nolan also worked alongside Roko Belic on documenting a safari across four African countries, organised by the late photojournalist [[Dan Eldon]] in the early 1990s.<ref>O'Sullivan, Graydon (2013), p. 67.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/amy-eldon-turteltaub/dan-eldon_b_3582633.html|title=Remembering My Brother Dan Eldon: A Journalist Who Died To Tell the Story|publisher=Huffingtonpost|date=7 December 2013|accessdate=30 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812045120/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/amy-eldon-turteltaub/dan-eldon_b_3582633.html|archive-date=12 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>}}<ref>Mooney, p. 5.</ref>\n\n[[File:Flaxman Gallery, UCL.JPG|thumb|right|220x220px|Nolan attended [[University College London]], and used its Flaxman Gallery for a scene in ''[[Inception]]'' (2010).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://filmlondon.org.uk/news/2010/july/nolans_mind_games|title=Nolan's Mind Games|accessdate=11 August 2010|publisher=Film London|date=14 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101122213601/http://filmlondon.org.uk/news/2010/july/nolans_mind_games|archive-date=22 November 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>]]\n\nNolan was educated at [[Haileybury and Imperial Service College]], an independent school in [[Hertford Heath]], [[Hertfordshire]], and later read [[English literature]] at [[University College London]] (UCL). Opting out of a traditional film education, he pursued \"a degree in something unrelated ... because it gives a different take on things.\"<ref>Mooney, p. 6.</ref> He chose UCL specifically for its filmmaking facilities, which comprised a [[Steenbeck|Steenbeck editing suite]] and [[16 mm film#Cameras|16{{nbsp}}mm film cameras]].<ref name=\"Tempest\">Tempest, M. [https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2011/feb/24/inception-christopher-nolan-film-oscar-director \"I was there at the 'Inception' of Christopher Nolan's film career\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005100119/http://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2011/feb/24/inception-christopher-nolan-film-oscar-director |date=5 October 2013 }}, ''The Guardian'', 24 February 2011; retrieved 21 September 2011.</ref> Nolan was president of the Union's Film Society,<ref name=\"Tempest\"/> and with [[Emma Thomas]] (his girlfriend and future wife) he screened [[35mm movie film|35 mm]] feature films during the school year and used the money earned to produce [[16 mm]] films over the summers.<ref name=\"British Cinematographer pt2\">{{cite web|title=Wally Pfister ASC on Christopher Nolan's Inception|url=http://www.thecinematographer.info/articles/18-wally-pfister.html|work=thecinematographer.info|year=2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120411005825/http://www.thecinematographer.info/articles/18-wally-pfister.html|archivedate=11 April 2012|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter earning his bachelor's degree in English literature in 1993, Nolan worked as a [[Script analyst|script reader]], [[camera operator]], and director of [[corporate video]]s and [[Sponsored film|industrial films]].<ref name=\"Tempest\"/><ref name=\"Feinberg\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b81581f07|title=Fearville (1997)|publisher=BFI|accessdate=1 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107104214/http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b81581f07|archive-date=7 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1995, he began work on the short film ''Larceny'', which was filmed over a weekend in black and white with limited equipment and a small cast and crew.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/interviews/interview.asp?IID=1052|title=Christopher Nolan: The Movies. The Memories|work=Empire|accessdate=12 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924064331/http://www.empireonline.com/interviews/interview.asp?IID=1052|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>Mooney, p. 5.</ref> Funded by Nolan and shot with the society's equipment, it appeared at the [[Cambridge Film Festival]] in 1996 and is considered one of UCL's best shorts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/~uczxflm/productions/archive/9495|title=UCLU Film Society, London|publisher=Ucl.ac.uk|accessdate=12 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120810232748/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/~uczxflm/productions/archive/9495/|archive-date=10 August 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> He filmed a third short, ''[[Doodlebug (film)|Doodlebug]]'' (1997), about a man chasing an insect around a flat with a shoe, only to discover when killing it that it is a miniature of himself.<ref>Mooney, p. 6.</ref><ref name=\"independent\">{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/christopher-nolan-director-dunkirk-short-first-film-doodlebug-student-ucl-london-a7675861.html |title=Christopher Nolan's student short film Doodlebug shows the Dunkirk director's humble beginnings |last=Hooton |first=Christopher |website=The Independent |date=10 April 2017 |accessdate=22 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722194629/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/christopher-nolan-director-dunkirk-short-first-film-doodlebug-student-ucl-london-a7675861.html |archive-date=22 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Nolan and Thomas made their first attempt at a feature in the mid-90s, an \"arty\" student angst film called ''Larry Mahoney'', which was scrapped and never released.<ref name=\"Mahoney\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nerdly.co.uk/2017/12/27/horror-on-sea-2018-interview-brian-barnes-discusses-the-redeeming/|title=Horror-On-Sea 2018 Interview: Brian Barnes discusses 'The Redeeming'|accessdate=5 April 2020|publisher=Nerdly|date=27 December 2017}}</ref> During this period in his career, Nolan had little or no success getting his projects off the ground; he later recalled the \"stack of rejection letters\" that greeted his early forays into making films, adding \"there's a very limited pool of finance in the UK. To be honest, it's a very clubby kind of place&nbsp;... Never had any support whatsoever from the British film industry.\"<ref name=\"AndrewPulver05\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2005/jun/15/features.features11|title=He's not a god \u2013 he's human|last=Pulver|first=Andrew|date=15 June 2005|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=23 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224110327/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2005/jun/15/features.features11|archive-date=24 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== 1998\u20132003: Breakthrough ===\nIn 1998, Nolan released his first feature, ''[[Following]]''. He wrote, directed, photographed and edited the film, which depicts an unemployed young writer ([[Jeremy Theobald]]) who trails strangers through London, hoping they will provide material for his first novel, but is drawn into a criminal underworld when he fails to keep his distance. The film was inspired by Nolan's experience of living in London and having his apartment burgled: \"There is an interesting connection between a stranger going through your possessions and the concept of following people at random through a crowd{{snd}}both take you beyond the boundaries of ordinary social relations\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wiki.ucl.ac.uk/display/SLAISFAlumni/Christopher+Nolan|title=The Man behind the Mask|publisher=UCL|date=8 December 2008|accessdate=12 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303180241/https://wiki.ucl.ac.uk/display/SLAISFAlumni/Christopher+Nolan|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Co-produced by Nolan with Emma Thomas and Jeremy Theobald,<ref name=\"nolandotnet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.christophernolan.net/following_making.php |title=The Making of Following |last=Duncker |first=Johannes |date=6 June 2002 |publisher=christophernolan.net |url-status=dead |accessdate=12 February 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513200348/http://www.christophernolan.net/following_making.php |archivedate=13 May 2008 |df= }}</ref> it was funded by him and made on a modest budget of \u00a33,000.<ref>[http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/interviews/39-christopher-nolan \"Interview with Christopher Nolan\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100505141213/http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/interviews/39-christopher-nolan |date=5 May 2010 }}. ''Metro''; retrieved 10 April 2011.</ref><ref name=\"Ressner\">{{cite web|last=Ressner|first=Jeffrey|title=The Traditionalist|url=http://www.dga.org/Craft/DGAQ/All-Articles/1202-Spring-2012/DGA-Interview-Christopher-Nolan.aspx|work=DGA Quarterly|accessdate=22 August 2012|date=Spring 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171125235745/https://www.dga.org/Craft/DGAQ/All-Articles/1202-Spring-2012/DGA-Interview-Christopher-Nolan.aspx|archive-date=25 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Most of the cast and crew were Nolan's friends, and shooting took place on weekends over the course of a year.<ref name=\"Ressner\"/>  To conserve [[film stock]], each scene in the film was rehearsed extensively to ensure that the first or second take could be used in the final edit.<ref>Mooney, p. 6.</ref><ref name=\"Tobias\">Tobias, S. [http://www.avclub.com/articles/christopher-nolan,13769 Interview: Christopher Nolan] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018024630/http://www.avclub.com/articles/christopher-nolan,13769/ |date=18 October 2013 }}, avclub.com, 5 June 2002; retrieved 13 September 2011.</ref> ''Following'' won several awards during its festival run<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmfestivalrotterdam.com/en/about/awards-and-jury/tiger-awards/previous-winners|title=Tiger Awards Competition: previous winners|publisher=International Film Festival Rotterdam|accessdate=12 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121013119/http://www.filmfestivalrotterdam.com/en/about/awards-and-jury/tiger-awards/previous-winners/|archive-date=21 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0154506/awards \"Awards for Following\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827194725/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0154506/awards |date=27 August 2017 }}. ''[[IMDb]]''; retrieved 25 June 2013.</ref> and was well received by critics; ''The New Yorker'' wrote that it \"echoed [[Alfred Hitchcock|Hitchcock]] classics\", but was \"leaner and meaner\".<ref name=\"Timberg\"/> [[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' was impressed with its \"spare look\" and agile hand-held camerawork, saying, \"As a result, the actors convincingly carry off the before, during and after modes that the film eventually, and artfully, weaves together.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Hero With No Memory Turns 'Memento' Into Unforgettable Trip|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C0CE1D71439F931A35757C0A96F958260|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=3 February 2017|first=Janet|last=Maslin|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204011800/http://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C0CE1D71439F931A35757C0A96F958260|archive-date=4 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On 11{{nbsp}}December 2012 it was released on DVD and [[Blu-ray]] as part of [[The Criterion Collection]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.criterion.com/films/28030-following|title=Criterion \u2013 Following|publisher=Criterion|accessdate=12 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107060854/https://www.criterion.com/films/28030-following|archive-date=7 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|align=left|width=246px|quote=[The] difference between shooting ''[[Following]]'' with a group of friends wearing our own clothes and my mum making sandwiches to spending $4&nbsp;million of somebody else's money on ''[[Memento (film)|Memento]]'' and having a crew of a hundred people is, to this day, by far the biggest leap I've ever made.|source= \u2014Nolan (in 2012) on the jump from his first film to his second.<ref name=\"Ressner\"/>}}\n\n''Following''{{'}}s success led to Nolan being afforded the opportunity to make ''[[Memento (film)|Memento]]'' (2000), which became his breakthrough film. The synopsis came from his brother Jonathan, who pitched the idea  to Nolan during a road trip about a man with [[anterograde amnesia]] who uses notes and tattoos to hunt for his wife's murderer. Jonathan worked the idea into a short story, \"[[Memento Mori (short story)|Memento Mori]]\" (2001), while Nolan developed it into a screenplay that told the story in reverse. Aaron Ryder, an executive for [[Newmarket Films]], said it was \"perhaps the most innovative script I had ever seen\".<ref>Mottram, p. 176.</ref> The film was optioned and given a budget of $4.5{{nbsp}}million, with [[Guy Pearce]] and [[Carrie-Anne Moss]] in the starring roles.<ref>Mottram, p. 177.</ref>  ''Memento'' premiered at the [[Venice International Film Festival]] in September 2000 to critical acclaim.<ref>Mottram, p. 62\u201364.</ref> [[Joe Morgenstern]] of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' wrote in his review, \"I can't remember when a movie has seemed so clever, strangely affecting and slyly funny at the very same time.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Hero With No Memory Turns 'Memento' Into Unforgettable Trip|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB9846986937127287|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=21 January 2014|first=Joe|last=Morgenstern|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326002730/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB9846986937127287|archive-date=26 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Basil Smith, in the book ''The Philosophy of Neo-Noir'', draws a comparison with [[John Locke]]'s ''[[An Essay Concerning Human Understanding]]'', which argues that conscious memories constitute our identities, a theme that Nolan explores in the film.<ref>Conard (2007) p.35.</ref> The film was a box-office success<ref>{{cite web|title=Memento|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=memento.htm|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6I5CaqAw2?url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=memento.htm|archive-date=13 July 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> and received a number of accolades, including [[Academy Award for Best Writing (Original Screenplay)|Academy Award]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay|Golden Globe Award]] nominations for its screenplay, [[Independent Spirit Award]]s for [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Director|Best Director]] and [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]], and a [[Directors Guild of America]] (DGA) Award nomination.<ref name=\"nytimesawards\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/240025/Christopher-Nolan/awards|title=Christopher Nolan awards|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=26 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024065520/http://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/240025/Christopher-Nolan/awards|archive-date=24 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp;jsessionid=85089250F8C40E42B36D0F921E3F7860?curTime=1295947194337 Session Timeout \u2013 Academy Awards\u00ae Database] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105194451/http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp%3Bjsessionid%3D85089250F8C40E42B36D0F921E3F7860?curTime=1295947194337 |date=5 November 2013 }} (29 January 2010); retrieved 26 November 2011.</ref> ''Memento'' was considered by numerous critics to be one of the best films of the [[2000s in film|2000s]].<ref name=\"Metadecade\">{{cite web|title=Film Critics Pick the Best Movies of the Decade|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critics-pick-the-best-movies-of-the-decade|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=3 January 2010|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6pBuFqa6Q?url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critics-pick-the-best-movies-of-the-decade|archive-date=24 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2017, the film was selected by the [[Library of Congress]] for preservation in the United States [[National Film Registry]], being deemed \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/the-goonies-titanic-field-of-dreams-die-hard-national-film-registry-1202638298/ |title='Titanic,' 'The Goonies,' 'Field of Dreams,' 'Memento' Added to National Film Registry |magazine=Variety |date=13 December 2017 |accessdate=13 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213101146/http://variety.com/2017/film/news/the-goonies-titanic-field-of-dreams-die-hard-national-film-registry-1202638298/ |archive-date=13 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n[[File:Steven Soderbergh 66\u00e8me Festival de Venise (Mostra).jpg|thumb|right|220x220px| Oscar-winning film director [[Steven Soderbergh]] ''(pictured)'' supported Nolan in his transition to studio filmmaking.]]\n\nImpressed by his work on ''Memento'', [[Steven Soderbergh]] recruited Nolan to direct the [[psychological thriller]] ''[[Insomnia (2002 film)|Insomnia]]'' (2002), starring Academy Award winners [[Al Pacino]], [[Robin Williams]], and [[Hilary Swank]].<ref name=\"insomnia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/interview/cnolan|title='Memento' recognition landed Christopher Nolan in the director's chair for big-budget 'Insomnia'|accessdate=5 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618002152/http://www.contactmusic.com/interview/cnolan|archive-date=18 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Warner Bros.]] initially wanted a more seasoned director, but Soderbergh and his [[Section Eight Productions]] fought for Nolan, as well as his choice of cinematographer ([[Wally Pfister]]) and editor ([[Dody Dorn]]).<ref>deWaard, Tait (2013), p. 49.</ref> With a $46{{nbsp}}million budget, it was described as \"a much more conventional Hollywood film than anything [Nolan had] done before\".<ref name=\"insomnia\"/> A remake of the 1997 [[Insomnia (1997 film)|Norwegian film of the same name]], ''Insomnia'' is about two Los Angeles detectives sent to a northern Alaskan town to investigate the murder of a local teenager. It received positive reviews from critics and performed well at the box office, earning $113{{nbsp}}million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Insomnia|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1114154-insomnia/|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100802163407/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1114154-insomnia/|archive-date=2 August 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Insomnia|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=insomnia.htm|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808004401/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=insomnia.htm|archive-date=8 August 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> Film critic [[Roger Ebert]] praised the film for introducing new perspectives and ideas on the issues of morality and guilt, stating that \"Unlike most remakes, the Nolan ''Insomnia'' is not a pale retread, but a re-examination of the material, like a new production of a good play.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ebert|first=Roger|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/insomnia-2002|title=Insomnia review|journal=Rogerebert.com|date=24 May 2002|accessdate=18 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213010524/http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/insomnia-2002|archive-date=13 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Erik Skjoldbj\u00e6rg]], the director of the original film, was satisfied with Nolan's version, calling it a \"well crafted, smart film ... with a really good director handling it\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Paul Weedon|title=Erik Skjoldb\u00e6rg on 'Pioneer'|url=http://grolschfilmworks.com/ca/features/erik-skjoldbjaerg-on-pioneer|work=Grolsch Filmworks|accessdate=30 October 2013}}</ref> [[Richard Schickel]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' deemed ''Insomnia'' a \"worthy successor\" to ''Memento'', and \"a triumph of atmosphere over a none-too-mysterious mystery\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Schickel|first=Richard|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,238623,00.html|title=Sleepless in Alaska|journal=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=19 May 2002|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113065714/http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,238623,00.html|archive-date=13 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter ''Insomnia'', Nolan planned a [[Howard Hughes]] biographical film starring [[Jim Carrey]]. He wrote a screenplay, which he said was \"the best script I've ever written\", but when he learned that [[Martin Scorsese]] was making a Hughes biopic (2004's ''[[The Aviator (2004 film)|The Aviator]]''), he reluctantly tabled his script and moved on to other projects.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2014/11/christopher-nolan-talks-howard-hughes-project-interstellar-more-in-interviews-plus-featurettes-new-pics-more-270480/|title=Christopher Nolan Talks Howard Hughes Project, 'Interstellar' & More In Interviews, Plus Featurettes, New Pics & More|work=Indiewire|date=10 November 2014|accessdate=7 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308045123/http://www.indiewire.com/2014/11/christopher-nolan-talks-howard-hughes-project-interstellar-more-in-interviews-plus-featurettes-new-pics-more-270480/|archive-date=8 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/christopher-nolan-says-his-howard-hughes-film-is-dead-but-hed-still-like-to-do-a-bond-film-at-some-point-20120604|title=Christopher Nolan Says His Howard Hughes Film Is Dead, But He'd Still Like To Do A Bond Film at Some Point|work=Indiewire|accessdate=9 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527153400/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/christopher-nolan-says-his-howard-hughes-film-is-dead-but-hed-still-like-to-do-a-bond-film-at-some-point-20120604|archive-date=27 May 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> After turning down an offer to direct the historical epic ''[[Troy (film)|Troy]]'' (2004),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/trivia-when-christopher-nolan-first-came-to-warner-bros-he-was-offered-troy-to-direct-20130621|title=Trivia: When Christopher Nolan First Came To Warner Bros., He Was Offered 'Troy' To Direct|publisher=The Playlist|accessdate=12 August 2014|first=Kevin|last=Jagernauth|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140813021758/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/trivia-when-christopher-nolan-first-came-to-warner-bros-he-was-offered-troy-to-direct-20130621|archive-date=13 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Nolan worked on adapting [[Ruth Rendell]]'s crime novel ''[[The Keys to the Street]]'' into a screenplay that he planned to direct for [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]], but eventually left the project, citing the similarities to his previous films.<ref name=\"blogspot\">[http://theplaylist.net/gemma-arterton-to-star-in-christopher-20100906/ Gemma Arterton to star in Christopher Nolan-penned thriller 'The Keys to the Street', Meeting with Ridley Scott for 'Alien' prequels'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925015835/http://theplaylist.net/gemma-arterton-to-star-in-christopher-20100906/ |date=25 September 2016 }} ''The Playlist'', 9 June 2011.</ref> Nolan was also adapting a film version of ''[[The Prisoner]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Child|first=Ben|title=Nolan signs to take Inception from script to screen|work=The Guardian|date=12 February 2009|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/feb/12/christopher-nolan-inception|location=London}}</ref> but later dropped out of the project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/batman/news/nolan-drops-the-prisoner_1113280 |title=Nolan Drops The Prisoner |publisher=Contact Music |date = 13 August 2009|accessdate=5 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\n=== 2003\u20132013: Hollywood success ===\nIn early 2003, Nolan approached Warner Bros. with the idea of making a new [[Batman]] film.<ref name=\"bb-latimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2005-may-08-ca-batman8-story.html|title=Rescuing Batman|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref> Fascinated by the character and story, he wanted to make a film grounded in a \"relatable\" world more reminiscent of a classical drama than a comic-book fantasy.<ref name=\"bb\">{{cite web|url=http://filmcomment.com/article/cinematic-faith-christopher-nolan-scott-foundas|title=Christopher Nolan looks back over the Dark Knight trilogy in this extended interview|publisher=Filmcomment|accessdate=27 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820002832/https://www.filmcomment.com/article/cinematic-faith-christopher-nolan-scott-foundas/|archive-date=20 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Filming took place in 2004, and Nolan relied heavily on traditional [[stunt]]s and [[miniature effect]]s, with [[computer-generated imagery]] being used in a minimal capacity.<ref name=\"bb-latimes\"/> ''[[Batman Begins]]'', the biggest project Nolan had undertaken to that point,<ref name=\"bb\"/> premiered in June 2005 to critical acclaim and commercial success.<ref>{{cite web|title=Insomnia|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/batman_begins/|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115152611/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/batman_begins/|archive-date=15 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Starring [[Christian Bale]] in the [[Bruce Wayne (The Dark Knight trilogy)|title role]], along with [[Michael Caine]], [[Gary Oldman]], [[Morgan Freeman]], and [[Liam Neeson]], the film revived the franchise, heralding a trend towards darker films that [[reboot (fiction)|rebooted]] (or retold) backstories.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/06/the-complicated-legacy-of-batman-begins/395477/|title=The Complicated Legacy of Batman Begins|magazine=The Atlantic|accessdate=10 June 2015|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611041139/http://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/06/the-complicated-legacy-of-batman-begins/395477/|archive-date=11 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Shawn Adler|title=He-Man' Movie Will Go Realistic: 'We're Not Talking About Putting Nipples On The Trapjaw Suit|url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2008/08/14/he-man-movie-will-go-realistic-were-not-talking-about-putting-nipples-on-the-trapjaw-suit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080902155525/http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2008/08/14/he-man-movie-will-go-realistic-were-not-talking-about-putting-nipples-on-the-trapjaw-suit|archivedate=2 September 2008|date=14 August 2008|accessdate=8 April 2013}}</ref> Praised for its psychological depth and contemporary relevance,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/sites/bfi.org.uk/files/downloads/bfi-press-release-christopher-nolan-season-at-bfi-southbank-in-july-2012-06-06.pdf|title=Christopher Nolan Season at BFI Southbank in July 2012|publisher=British Film Institute|accessdate=31 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304093423/http://www.bfi.org.uk/sites/bfi.org.uk/files/downloads/bfi-press-release-christopher-nolan-season-at-bfi-southbank-in-july-2012-06-06.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Kyle Smith]] of ''[[The New York Post]]'' called it \"a wake-up call to the people who keep giving us cute capers about men in tights. It wipes the smirk off the face of the superhero movie.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Review: Batman Begins|url=http://kylesmithonline.com/?p=349|newspaper=The New York Post|accessdate=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201172556/http://kylesmithonline.com/?p=349|archive-date=1 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''Batman Begins'' was the eighth-highest-grossing film of 2005 in the United States and the year's ninth-highest-grossing film worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=batmanbegins.htm|title=Batman Begins (2005)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=19 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724205014/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=batmanbegins.htm|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography]] and three [[BAFTA]] awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0372784/awards|title=Batman Begins|publisher=IMDb|access-date=30 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180409044611/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0372784/awards|archive-date=9 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/awards-database.html?sq=batman+begins|title=Batman Begins|publisher=BAFTA-Awards Database|accessdate=23 October 2012}}</ref> On the film's 10th anniversary, ''[[Forbes]]'' published an article describing its lasting influence: \"Reboot became part of our modern vocabulary, and superhero origin stories became increasingly en{{nbsp}}vogue for the genre. The phrase \"dark and gritty\" likewise joined the cinematic lexicon, influencing our perception of different approaches to storytelling not only in the comic book film genre but in all sorts of other genres as well.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/markhughes/2015/07/30/exclusive-christopher-nolan-talks-batman-begins-10th-anniversary/#797eaf2329a0|title=Exclusive: Christopher Nolan Talks 'Batman Begins' 10th Anniversary|magazine=Forbes|accessdate=28 February 2016|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003225206/https://www.forbes.com/sites/markhughes/2015/07/30/exclusive-christopher-nolan-talks-batman-begins-10th-anniversary/#797eaf2329a0|archive-date=3 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBefore returning to the Batman franchise for a sequel, Nolan directed, co-wrote, and produced ''[[The Prestige (film)|The Prestige]]'' (2006), an adaptation of the [[Christopher Priest (novelist)|Christopher Priest]] [[The Prestige|novel]] about two rival 19th-century magicians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christopher-priest.co.uk/books/the-prestige/interview-abou-the-prestige|title=Interview about The Prestige|publisher=Christopher-priest.co.uk|accessdate=15 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120728180958/http://www.christopher-priest.co.uk/books/the-prestige/interview-abou-the-prestige/|archive-date=28 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The screenplay was the result of an intermittent, five-year collaboration between him and his brother Jonathan, who had begun writing it already in 2001.<ref>{{cite podcast|url=http://cdn2.libsyn.com/creativescreenwritingmag/ThePrestigeQandA.mp3?nvb=20090804012227&nva=20090805013227&t=0177c850fb5969f409276|title=The Prestige Q&A: Interview with Jonathan Nolan|website=Creative Screenwriting Magazine Podcast|publisher=Creative Screenwriting|host=Jeff Goldsmith|date=28 October 2006|accessdate=24 July 2007}}</ref> Nolan initially intended to make the film as early as 2003, but had postponed the project after agreeing to make ''Batman Begins''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2003/film/news/nolan-wants-prestige-1117884751|title=Nolan wants 'Prestige'|work=Variety|accessdate=9 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005094256/http://variety.com/2003/film/news/nolan-wants-prestige-1117884751/|archive-date=5 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Starring [[Hugh Jackman]] and Christian Bale in the lead roles, ''The Prestige'' received critical acclaim and earned over $109{{nbsp}}million worldwide.<ref>[http://www.bo/Volumes/Untitled/PSP/Photo/Photo10/xofficemojo.com/movies/?id=prestige.htm \"The Prestige (2006)\"], ''[[Box Office Mojo]]''; retrieved 10 April 2011.</ref><ref>Murray, Noel. (3 December 2009) [http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-best-films-of-the-00s,35931 The best films of the '00s|Best of the Decade] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527155440/http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-best-films-of-the-00s,35931/ |date=27 May 2013 }}. The A.V. Club; retrieved 26 January 2011.</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] described it as \"quite a movie{{snd}}atmospheric, obsessive, almost satanic\",<ref>{{cite web|title=The Prestige|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-prestige-2007|publisher=Roger Ebert|accessdate=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203004736/http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-prestige-2007|archive-date=3 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Kenneth Turan]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called it an \"ambitious, unnerving melodrama\".<ref>{{cite news|title=They've got something up their sleeves|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/oct/20/entertainment/et-prestige20|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=23 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814051743/http://articles.latimes.com/2006/oct/20/entertainment/et-prestige20|archive-date=14 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Philip French]] wrote in his review for ''[[The Guardian]]'': \"In addition to the intellectual or philosophical excitement it engenders, ''The Prestige'' is gripping, suspenseful, mysterious, moving and often darkly funny.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=The Prestige|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2006/nov/12/drama.sciencefictionandfantasy|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=27 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221084521/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2006/nov/12/drama.sciencefictionandfantasy|archive-date=21 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Prestige'' also received Academy Award nominations for [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]] and [[Academy Award for Best Art Direction|Best Art Direction]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2007/feb/26/awardsandprizes.oscars2007|title=The Prestige|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815183501/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2007/feb/26/awardsandprizes.oscars2007|archive-date=15 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n | align     = left\n | direction = vertical\n | width     =\n | image1    = The Dark Knight European Premier - Leicester square2.jpg\n | width1    = 220\n | caption1  = Nolan (left) with the cast and crew of ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'' at the 2008 European premiere in London.\n | image2    = InceptionCastPremiereJuly10.jpg\n | width2    = 220\n | caption2  = The cast of ''[[Inception]]'' at the premiere in July 2010.\n}}\n\nIn 2006, Nolan announced that the follow-up to ''Batman Begins'' would be called ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.darkhorizons.com/news06/060731n.php|title=It's Official: \"Batman 2\" Gets A Title|author=Garth Franklin|date=31 July 2006|publisher=DarkHorizons|accessdate=9 March 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070125200104/http://www.darkhorizons.com/news06/060731n.php|archive-date=25 January 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> Approaching the sequel, Nolan wanted to expand on the [[Film noir|noirish]] quality of the first film by broadening the canvas and taking on \"the dynamic of a story of the city, a large crime story{{nbsp}}... where you're looking at the police, the justice system, the vigilante, the poor people, the rich people, the criminals\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.empireonline.com/features/dark-knight|title=The Dark Knight: The Original Feature|magazine=Empire|accessdate=23 December 2013|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120713133553/http://www.empireonline.com/features/dark-knight|archive-date=13 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Released in July 2008 to great critical acclaim, ''The Dark Knight'' has been cited as one of the best films of the 2000s and one of the [[List of films considered the best#Comic book/superhero|best superhero films ever made]].<ref name=\"Metadecade\"/><ref name=\"Paste\">{{cite web|title=The 50 Best Movies of the Decade (2000\u20132009)|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2009/11/50-best-movies-of-the-decade-2000-2009.html?p=4|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|accessdate=14 December 2011|date=3 November 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017223108/https://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2009/11/50-best-movies-of-the-decade-2000-2009.html?p=4|archive-date=17 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Empiredecade\">{{cite web|title=Review of the Decade \u2013 Year-By-Year: Empire's Films Of The Decade|url=http://www.empireonline.com/features/reviewofthedecade/films-of-the-decade/9.asp|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|accessdate=4 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924063908/http://www.empireonline.com/features/reviewofthedecade/films-of-the-decade/9.asp|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>  [[Manohla Dargis]] of ''The New York Times'' found the film to be of higher artistic merit than many Hollywood blockbusters: \"Pitched at the divide between art and industry, poetry and entertainment, it goes darker and deeper than any Hollywood movie of its comic-book kind.\"<ref name=\"Dargis\">{{cite news|author=Manohla Dargis|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/18/movies/18knig.html|title=The Dark Knight-Showdown in Gotham Town|work=The New York Times|date=18 July 2008|accessdate=21 January 2014|author-link=Manohla Dargis|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810124137/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/18/movies/18knig.html|archive-date=10 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Ebert expressed a similar point of view, describing it as a \"haunted film that leaps beyond its origins and becomes an engrossing tragedy.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080716/REVIEWS/55996637|title=The Dark Knight|author=Roger Ebert|date=16 July 2008|newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=21 January 2014|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/64yviafso?url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?aid=%2F20080716%2Freviews%2F55996637|archive-date=26 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Dark Knight'' set a number of box-office records during its theatrical run,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/28/movies/28box.html|title=Dark Knight Wins Again at Box Office|author=Brooks Barnes|date=28 July 2008|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=21 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090411150617/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/28/movies/28box.html|archive-date=11 April 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> earning $534,858,444 in North America and $469,700,000 abroad, for a worldwide total of $1,004,558,444.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=darkknight.htm|title=The Dark Knight (2008)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=17 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221104243/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=darkknight.htm|archive-date=21 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[81st Academy Awards]], the film was nominated for eight Oscars, winning two: the [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing]] and a posthumous [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for [[Heath Ledger]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/oscars/7842438.stm \"The Oscars 2009\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221215438/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/oscars/7842438.stm |date=21 February 2009 }}. BBC News.</ref> Nolan received many [[List of accolades received by The Dark Knight|awards and nominations]] for his work on the film.<ref name=\"nytimesawards\"/> In 2018, [[Bilge Ebiri]] of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' wrote, \"Its politics have been discussed ad infinitum. Its stylistic influence has become ubiquitous, then pass\u00e9, then somehow aspirational ... ''The Dark Knight'' is perhaps the most powerful exploration of guilt the modern American blockbuster has given us.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2018/07/18/10-years-later-the-dark-knight-and-its-vision-of-guilt-still-resonate/|title=Ten Years Later, \"The Dark Knight\" and Its Vision of Guilt Still Resonate|accessdate=23 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823174256/https://www.villagevoice.com/2018/07/18/10-years-later-the-dark-knight-and-its-vision-of-guilt-still-resonate/|archive-date=23 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter ''The Dark Knight''{{'}}s success, Warner Bros. signed Nolan to direct ''[[Inception]]'' (2010). Nolan also wrote and co-produced the film, described as \"a contemporary sci-fi actioner set within the architecture of the mind\".<ref name=\"Tackles\">{{cite journal|last=Fleming|first=Michael|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117999988.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|title=Nolan tackles 'Inception' for WB|journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=11 February 2009|accessdate=2 April 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414183155/http://variety.com/article/VR1117999988.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|archive-date=14 April 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> Starring a large ensemble cast led by [[Leonardo DiCaprio]], the film became a critical and commercial success upon its release in July 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://collider.com/inception-oscar-featurette|title=Warner Bros. Keeping INCEPTION in Oscar-voters' Minds with \"New\" Behind-the-Scenes Featurette|year=2010|work=Collider.com|accessdate=15 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822054454/http://collider.com/inception-oscar-featurette/|archive-date=22 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' awarded the film a perfect score of \"A+\" and called it \"one of the best movies of the [21st] century\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richardroeper.com/reviews/inception.aspx|title=''Inception'' Review|last=Roeper|first=Richard|authorlink=Richard Roeper|work=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=21 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100718103707/http://www.richardroeper.com/reviews/inception.aspx|archive-date=18 July 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mark Kermode]] named it the best film of 2010, stating \"''Inception'' is proof that people are not stupid, that cinema is not trash, and that it is possible for blockbusters and art to be the same thing.\"<ref name=\"Kermode\">{{cite video|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/markkermode/2010/12/my_top_five_films_of_the_year.html|accessdate=21 January 2014|date=24 December 2010|first=Mark|last=Kermode|authorlink=Mark Kermode|title=Kermode Uncut: My Top Five Films of the Year|publisher=BBC|time=5:05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130106172155/http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/markkermode/2010/12/my_top_five_films_of_the_year.html|archive-date=6 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Schuker\">{{cite news|last=Schuker|first=Lauren|title=Studios Root for 'Inception'|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703722804575369390235794102|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=10 January 2013|date=16 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150514092432/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703722804575369390235794102|archive-date=14 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The film ended up grossing over $820{{nbsp}}million worldwide<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=inception.htm|title=Inception (2010)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=2 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030220255/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=inception.htm|archive-date=30 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> and was nominated for eight Academy Awards, including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] and [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]; it won the award for [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound|Best Sound Mixing]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Best Sound Editing]] and [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]].<ref name=\"Academy Awards 2010 (83rd)\">{{cite web |url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2011/I?qt-honorees=1#block-quicktabs-honorees |title=2011 Academy Awards Nominations and Winners |access-date=26 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802040831/http://oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2011/I?qt-honorees=1#block-quicktabs-honorees |archive-date=2 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Nolan was also nominated for [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]] and Golden Globe awards, [[List of accolades received by Inception|among other accolades]].<ref name=\"nytimesawards\"/>\n\nIn 2012, Nolan directed his third and final Batman film, ''[[The Dark Knight Rises]]'', with Christian Bale reprising the title role. Although Nolan was initially hesitant about returning to the series, he agreed to come back after developing a story with his brother and [[David S. Goyer]] that he felt would end the series on a high note.<ref name=\"Bettinger\">{{cite news|first=Brendan|last=Bettinger|title=Christopher Nolan Speaks! Updates on Dark Knight Sequel and Superman Man of Steel|website=Collider.com|date=10 March 2010|url=http://www.collider.com/2010/03/10/christopher-nolan-speaks-updates-on-dark-knight-sequel-and-superman-man-of-steel|accessdate=10 March 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100313061209/http://www.collider.com/2010/03/10/christopher-nolan-speaks-updates-on-dark-knight-sequel-and-superman-man-of-steel/|archive-date=13 March 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/2010/10/27/christopher-nolan-reveals-title-of-third-batman-film-and-that-it-wont-be-the-riddler|title=Christopher Nolan reveals title of third Batman film and that 'it won't be the Riddler'|last=Boucher|first=Geoff|date=27 October 2010|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=27 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101029042813/http://herocomplex.latimes.com/2010/10/27/christopher-nolan-reveals-title-of-third-batman-film-and-that-it-wont-be-the-riddler/|archive-date=29 October 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> The film was released in July 2012 to positive reviews; Andrew O'Hehir of ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'' called it \"arguably the biggest, darkest, most thrilling and disturbing and utterly balls-out spectacle ever created for the screen\", further describing the work as \"auteurist spectacle on a scale never before possible and never before attempted\".<ref name=\"Hehir\">{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/2012/07/18/the_dark_knight_rises_christopher_nolans_evil_masterpiece|title=\"The Dark Knight Rises\": Christopher Nolan's evil masterpiece|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|date=18 July 2012|accessdate=4 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602051223/http://www.salon.com/2012/07/18/the_dark_knight_rises_christopher_nolans_evil_masterpiece/|archive-date=2 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/filmandtv/news/the-dark-knight-rises-receives-overwhelmingly-positive/275513|title='The Dark Knight Rises' receives overwhelmingly positive early reviews|author=NME.com|work=NME.com}}</ref> [[Christy Lemire]] of ''[[The Associated Press]]'' wrote in her review that Nolan concluded his trilogy in a \"typically spectacular, ambitious fashion\", but disliked the \"overloaded\" story and excessive grimness.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/16/batman-review-dark-knight-rises-letdown_n_1677247.html|title=Batman Review: Is 'The Dark Knight Rises' An Epic Letdown?|last=Lemire|first=Christy|date=16 July 2012|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=16 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317011538/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/16/batman-review-dark-knight-rises-letdown_n_1677247.html|archive-date=17 March 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Like its predecessor, the film was a box office success, becoming the thirteenth film to reach the billion-dollar mark.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-milestone-dark-knight-rises-warner-bros-christopher-nolan-christian-bale-367476|title=Box Office Milestone: 'Dark Knight Rises' Crosses $1 Billion Worldwide|accessdate=17 November 2012|work=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|date=2 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109092114/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-milestone-dark-knight-rises-warner-bros-christopher-nolan-christian-bale-367476|archive-date=9 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> During a midnight showing of the film at the Century{{nbsp}}16 cinema in [[Aurora, Colorado]], [[2012 Aurora, Colorado shooting|a gunman opened fire inside the theatre]], killing 12 people and injuring 58 others.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_21124893/12-shot-dead-58-wounded-aurora-movie-theater|title=12 shot dead, 58 wounded in Aurora movie theater during Batman premier|accessdate=13 January 2012|work=Denver Post|first=Jennifer|last=Brown|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722234007/http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_21124893/12-shot-dead-58-wounded-aurora-movie-theater|archive-date=22 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Nolan released a statement to the press expressing his condolences for the victims of what he described as a senseless tragedy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2012/07/20/christopher-nolan-dark-knight-rises-shooting-statement|title=Christopher Nolan on Theater Shooting: 'I Would Like to Express Our Profound Sorrow'|accessdate=13 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120721130638/http://insidemovies.ew.com/2012/07/20/christopher-nolan-dark-knight-rises-shooting-statement/|archive-date=21 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Christopher Nolan, London, 2013 (crop).jpg|thumb|upright|Nolan at the 2013 premiere of ''[[Man of Steel (film)|Man of Steel]]'' in London.]]\n\nDuring story discussions for ''The Dark Knight Rises'' in 2010, Goyer told Nolan of his idea to present [[Superman]] in a modern context.<ref name=\"GoyStory\">{{cite news|url=http://www.superherohype.com/news/articles/102090-christopher-nolan-on-batman-and-superman|title=Christopher Nolan on Batman and Superman|publisher=[[Superhero Hype!]]|date=4 June 2010|accessdate=2 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110105182212/http://www.superherohype.com/news/articles/102090-christopher-nolan-on-batman-and-superman|archive-date=5 January 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Impressed with Goyer's [[First contact (science fiction)|first contact]] concept, Nolan pitched the idea for ''[[Man of Steel (film)|Man of Steel]]'' (2013) to Warner Bros, who hired Nolan to produce and [[Zack Snyder]] to direct.<ref>{{cite news|title=Alien, Yet Familiar|work=The New York Times|date=22 May 2013|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/26/movies/man-of-steel-aims-to-make-superman-relevant-again.html|accessdate=22 May 2013|first=Dave|last=Itzkoff|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523184437/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/26/movies/man-of-steel-aims-to-make-superman-relevant-again.html|archive-date=23 May 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"GoyStory\"/> Starring [[Henry Cavill]], [[Amy Adams]], [[Kevin Costner]], [[Russell Crowe]], and [[Michael Shannon]], ''Man of Steel'' grossed more than $660{{nbsp}}million at the worldwide box office, but received a divided critical reaction.<ref>{{cite web|title=Man of Steel Reviews \u2013 Metacritic|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/man-of-steel|work=Metacritic|accessdate=12 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140706192545/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/man-of-steel|archive-date=6 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite the mixed reviews, Nolan was thoroughly impressed by Snyder's work, saying that the director \"knocked it out of the park\", and that he believed the film would have the same potential to excite audiences as when he himself saw the [[Superman (1978 film)|Christopher Reeve version]] in 1978.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/videos/christopher-nolan-talks-producing-man-of-steel-39948/|title=Christopher Nolan talks producing Man of Steel \u2013 Access Hollywood|accessdate=22 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822174604/http://www.accesshollywood.com/videos/christopher-nolan-talks-producing-man-of-steel-39948/|archive-date=22 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== 2014\u2013present: Established blockbuster auteur ===\n[[File:Jonathan Nolan by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Nolan's younger brother, [[Jonathan Nolan|Jonathan]], co-wrote the screenplay for ''Interstellar''.]]\n\nNolan next directed, wrote, and produced the science-fiction film ''[[Interstellar (film)|Interstellar]]'' (2014). The first drafts of the script were written by Jonathan Nolan, and it was originally to be directed by [[Steven Spielberg]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/09/christopher-nolan-interstellar_n_2444314.html|title=Christopher Nolan's 'Interstellar': 'Dark Knight Rises' Director Lines Up Next Project|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=13 January 2013|date=9 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130113030432/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/09/christopher-nolan-interstellar_n_2444314.html|archive-date=13 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Based on the scientific theories of [[theoretical physicist]] [[Kip Thorne]], the film follows a group of [[astronaut]]s who travel through a [[wormhole]] in search of a new home for humanity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/christopher-nolans-merging-an-original-idea-with-jonah-nolans-old-screenplay-for-interstellar-20130110|title=Christopher Nolan's Merging An Original Idea With Jonah Nolan's Old Screenplay For 'Interstellar'|publisher=The Playlist|author=Jagernauth, Kevin|date=10 January 2013|accessdate=13 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112010928/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/christopher-nolans-merging-an-original-idea-with-jonah-nolans-old-screenplay-for-interstellar-20130110|archive-date=12 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''Interstellar'' starred [[Matthew McConaughey]], [[Anne Hathaway]], [[Jessica Chastain]], [[Bill Irwin]], [[Michael Caine]], and [[Ellen Burstyn]], and was Nolan's first collaboration with cinematographer [[Hoyte van Hoytema]]. ''Interstellar'' was released in November 2014 to largely positive reviews and strong box office results, grossing over $670{{nbsp}}million worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/03/christopher-nolans-interstellar-to-be-paramount-warner-bros-co-production-and-joint-distribution/ |title=Christopher Nolan's 'Interstellar' To Be Paramount\u2013Warner Bros Co-Production And Joint Distribution |access-date=8 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140624041858/http://www.deadline.com/2013/03/christopher-nolans-interstellar-to-be-paramount-warner-bros-co-production-and-joint-distribution/ |archive-date=24 June 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/interstellar|title=Interstellar Reviews|work=metacritic.com|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=13 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804225550/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/interstellar|archive-date=4 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=interstellar.htm|title=Interstellar (2014)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=12 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316082328/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=interstellar.htm|archive-date=16 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> [[A. O. Scott]] wrote, in his review for ''The New York Times'', \"''Interstellar'', full of visual dazzle, thematic ambition{{nbsp}}... is a sweeping, futuristic adventure driven by grief, dread and regret.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/05/movies/interstellar-christopher-nolans-search-for-a-new-planet.html | title=Off to the Stars, With Grief, Dread and Regret | newspaper=The New York Times | accessdate=16 July 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828121417/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/05/movies/interstellar-christopher-nolans-search-for-a-new-planet.html | archive-date=28 August 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Documentary filmmaker [[Toni Myers]] said of the film, \"I loved it because it tackled the most difficult part of human exploration, which is that it's a multi-generational journey. It was a real work of art.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cnet.com/news/space-station-film-school-how-astronauts-shot-this-glorious-imax-documentary/ | title=Space station film school: How astronauts shot this glorious IMAX movie | website=CNET | accessdate=27 January 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610145325/http://www.cnet.com/news/space-station-film-school-how-astronauts-shot-this-glorious-imax-documentary/ | archive-date=10 June 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''Interstellar'' was particularly praised for its scientific accuracy, which led to the publication of two [[scientific papers]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=James|first=Oliver|last2=Tunzelmann|first2=Eug\u00e9nie von|last3=Franklin|first3=Paul|last4=Thorne|first4=Kip S.|date=February 2015|title=Gravitational lensing by spinning black holes in astrophysics, and in the movieInterstellar|journal=Classical and Quantum Gravity|language=en|volume=32|issue=6|pages=065001|doi=10.1088/0264-9381/32/6/065001|issn=0264-9381|arxiv=1502.03808}}</ref> and the [[American Journal of Physics]] calling for it to be shown in school science lessons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-33173197|title=Interstellar 'should be shown in school lessons'|work=BBC|accessdate=23 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150624075813/http://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-33173197|archive-date=24 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Visualizing Interstellar's Wormhole|journal = American Journal of Physics|volume = 83|issue = 6|pages = 486\u2013499|last=James|first=Oliver|last2=von Tunzelmann|first2=Eug\u00e9nie|doi=10.1119/1.4916949|last3=Franklin|first3=Paul|last4=Thorne|first4=Kip S.|year = 2015|bibcode = 2015AmJPh..83..486J|arxiv = 1502.03809}}</ref> It was named one of the best films of the year by The [[American Film Institute]] (AFI).<ref>{{cite news|last=Kilday|first=Gregg|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/afi-list-top-10-films-754933|title=AFI List of Top 10 Films Expands to Include 11|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=9 December 2014|accessdate=22 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150112100116/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/afi-list-top-10-films-754933|archive-date=12 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[87th Academy Awards]], the film won [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]] and received four other nominations{{snd}}[[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound Mixing]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Best Sound Editing]] and [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/3668006/oscars-2015-nominations/|title=Oscars 2015: See the Full List of Nominees|magazine=Time|date=15 January 2015|accessdate=16 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115180510/http://time.com/3668006/oscars-2015-nominations/|archive-date=15 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2014, Nolan and Emma Thomas also served as [[executive producer]]s on ''[[Transcendence (2014 film)|Transcendence]]'' (2014), the directorial debut of Nolan's longtime cinematographer Wally Pfister.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/christopher-nolan-wally-pfister-dark-knight-rises-337015|title=Christopher Nolan to Exec Produce Wally Pfister's Directorial Debut|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=23 October 2012|first=Borys|last=Kit|date=13 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120922192453/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/christopher-nolan-wally-pfister-dark-knight-rises-337015|archive-date=22 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The film was released to mostly unfavorable reviews and disappointing box office results.<ref name=\"Transcendence14\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/apr/18/transcendence-johnny-depp-2014s-most-unexpected-turkey-film|title=The Johnny Depp Problem|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=18 April 2014|accessdate=3 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703162416/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/apr/18/transcendence-johnny-depp-2014s-most-unexpected-turkey-film|archive-date=3 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the mid-2010s, Nolan took part in several ventures for film preservation and distribution of the films of lesser-known filmmakers. His production company, Syncopy, formed a joint venture with [[Zeitgeist Films]] to release [[Blu-ray]] editions of Zeitgeist's prestige titles.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/christopher-nolans-syncopy-teaming-with-zeitgeist-on-blu-ray-releases-exclusive-1201437195/|title=Christopher Nolan's Syncopy Teaming With Zeitgeist on Blu-ray Releases (EXCLUSIVE)|magazine=Variety|author=McNary, Dave|date=19 February 2015|accessdate=23 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224023820/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/christopher-nolans-syncopy-teaming-with-zeitgeist-on-blu-ray-releases-exclusive-1201437195/|archive-date=24 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> As part of the Blu-ray release of the animation films of the [[Brothers Quay]], Nolan directed the documentary short ''[[Quay (film)|Quay]]'' (2015). He also initiated a theatrical tour, showcasing the Quays' ''[[In Absentia (film)|In Absentia]]'', ''The Comb'', and ''[[Street of Crocodiles]]''. The program and Nolan's short received critical acclaim, with ''[[Indiewire]]'' writing in their review that the brothers \"will undoubtedly have hundreds, if not thousands more fans because of Nolan, and for that ''The Quay Brothers in 35mm'' will always be one of latter's most important contributions to cinema\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/why-the-quay-brothers-in-35mm-is-one-of-christopher-nolans-greatest-accomplishments-20150820|title=Why 'The Quay Brothers in 35mm' is One of Christopher Nolan's Greatest Accomplishments|work=Indiewire|accessdate=21 August 2015|date=20 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150821010112/http://www.indiewire.com/article/why-the-quay-brothers-in-35mm-is-one-of-christopher-nolans-greatest-accomplishments-20150820|archive-date=21 August 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/07/27/christopher-nolan-short-film-quay?|title=Christopher Nolan's next movie is a documentary short|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=28 July 2015|date=27 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150729031620/http://www.ew.com/article/2015/07/27/christopher-nolan-short-film-quay|archive-date=29 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> An advocate for the survival of the analogue medium, Nolan and visual artist [[Tacita Dean]] invited representatives from leading American film archives, laboratories, and presenting institutions to participate in an informal summit entitled ''Reframing the Future of Film'' at the [[J. Paul Getty Museum|Getty Museum]] in March 2015.<ref name=\"filmvsdigital 2\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/columns/christopher-nolan-rallies-the-troops-to-save-celluloid-film-1201450536/ |title=Christopher Nolan Rallies the Troops to Save Celluloid Film |work=Variety |date=11 March 2015 |accessdate=12 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150313152211/http://variety.com/2015/film/columns/christopher-nolan-rallies-the-troops-to-save-celluloid-film-1201450536/ |archive-date=13 March 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jul/31/quentin-tarantino-christopher-nolan-kodak-film|title=Tarantino and Nolan share a Kodak moment as studios fund film processing|work=The Guardian|accessdate=27 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227150531/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jul/31/quentin-tarantino-christopher-nolan-kodak-film|archive-date=27 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Subsequent events were held at [[Tate Modern]] in London, [[Museo Rufino Tamayo, Mexico City|Museo Tamayo]] in [[Mexico City]], and [[Tata Theatre]] in [[Mumbai]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://filmheritagefoundation.co.in/reframing-future-film/|title=Reframing The Future Of Film|date=14 March 2018|accessdate=14 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315070645/http://filmheritagefoundation.co.in/reframing-future-film/|archive-date=15 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2015, Nolan also joined the board of directors of [[The Film Foundation]], a US-based non-profitable organisation dedicated to [[film preservation]],<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://deadline.com/2015/04/christopher-nolan-joins-film-foundation-board-1201414195/|title=Christopher Nolan Joins Film Foundation Board|magazine=Deadline|date=22 April 2015|accessdate=22 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424184303/http://deadline.com/2015/04/christopher-nolan-joins-film-foundation-board-1201414195/|archive-date=24 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and was appointed, along with [[Martin Scorsese]], by the [[Library of Congress]] to serve on the [[National Film Preservation Board]] (NFPB) as DGA representatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dga.org/News/PressReleases/2015/150507-DGA-Congratulates-Martin-Scorsese-and-Christopher-Nolan-for-NFPB-appointments.aspx|title=DGA Congratulates Martin Scorsese and Christopher Nolan on Appointments to National Film Preservation Board|publisher=The Directors Guild of America|date=7 May 2015|accessdate=19 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150521043452/http://www.dga.org/News/PressReleases/2015/150507-DGA-Congratulates-Martin-Scorsese-and-Christopher-Nolan-for-NFPB-appointments.aspx|archive-date=21 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter serving as an executive producer alongside Thomas on Zack Snyder's ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]'' (2016) and ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]'' (2017), the sequels to ''Man of Steel'',<ref name=\"BSExec\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ben-affleck-first-choice-batman-740292|title=Charles Roven: Ben Affleck \"Was the First Guy We Went to\" for Batman Role|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=13 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014094819/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ben-affleck-first-choice-batman-740292|archive-date=14 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://collider.com/christopher-nolan-ben-affleck-batman-v-superman/|title=Christopher Nolan Discusses Ben Affleck's Casting in Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice|last=Nemiroff|first=Perri|work=Collider|date=10 November 2014|accessdate=23 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314192011/http://collider.com/christopher-nolan-ben-affleck-batman-v-superman/|archive-date=14 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Nolan returned to directing with ''[[Dunkirk (2017 film)|Dunkirk]]'' (2017). Based on his own original screenplay and co-produced with Thomas, the story is set amid [[World War II]] and the [[Dunkirk evacuation|evacuation]] of [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] soldiers from the beaches of [[Dunkirk]], [[France]], in 1940. Describing the film as a survival tale with a [[triptych]] structure, Nolan wanted to make a \"sensory, almost experimental movie\" with minimal dialogue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.premiere.fr/Cinema/News-Cinema/EXCLU-Christopher-Nolan-et-ses-collaborateurs-revelent-7-infos-sur-Dunkerque|title=Christopher Nolan et ses collaborateurs r\u00e9v\u00e8lent 7 infos sur Dunkerque|work=Premi\u00e8re|accessdate=28 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228144316/http://www.premiere.fr/Cinema/News-Cinema/EXCLU-Christopher-Nolan-et-ses-collaborateurs-revelent-7-infos-sur-Dunkerque/|archive-date=28 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He said he waited to make ''Dunkirk'' until he had earned the trust of a major studio to let him make it as a British film, but with an American budget.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2017/07/08/spitfires-flotillas-boats-rough-seas-1000-extras-christopher/|title=Spitfires, flotillas of boats, rough seas and 1,000 extras: Christopher Nolan on the making of Dunkirk, his most challenging film to date|last=Nolan|first=Christopher|work=The Telegraph|date=8 July 2017|accessdate=8 July 2017|archive-url=https://archive.is/20170710035754/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2017/07/08/spitfires-flotillas-boats-rough-seas-1000-extras-christopher/|archive-date=10 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Before filming, Nolan sought advice from Spielberg, who later said in an interview with ''Variety'', \"knowing and respecting that Chris [Nolan] is one of the world's most imaginative filmmakers, my advice to him was to leave his imagination, as I did on [[Saving Private Ryan|''Ryan'']], in second position to the research he was doing to authentically acquit this historical drama.\"<ref name=\"LangVariety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/christopher-nolan-dunkirk-oscars-movies-tv-spielberg-1202607836/|title=Christopher Nolan Gets Candid on the State of Movies, Rise of TV and Spielberg's Influence|last=Lang|first=Brent|date=8 November 2017|work=Variety|accessdate=9 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108202018/http://variety.com/2017/film/news/christopher-nolan-dunkirk-oscars-movies-tv-spielberg-1202607836/|archive-date=8 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Starring [[Fionn Whitehead]], [[Jack Lowden]], [[Aneurin Barnard]], [[Harry Styles]], [[Tom Hardy]], [[Mark Rylance]], [[Cillian Murphy]], and [[Kenneth Branagh]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/harry-styles-one-direction-christopher-nolan-dunkirk-1201728153|title=Harry Styles, Fionn Whitehead to Star in Christopher Nolan WW2 Action-Thriller 'Dunkirk'|last=McNary|first=Dave|work=Variety|date=11 March 2016|accessdate=7 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504152927/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/harry-styles-one-direction-christopher-nolan-dunkirk-1201728153/|archive-date=4 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Dunkirk'' was released in theatres in July 2017 to widespread critical acclaim and strong box office results.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/dunkirk-review-roundup-what-critics-are-saying-1021889|title='Dunkirk': What the Critics Are Saying|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=17 July 2017|accessdate=19 July 2017|archive-url=https://archive.is/20170720161842/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/dunkirk-review-roundup-what-critics-are-saying-1021889|archive-date=20 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dunkirk Reviews \u2013 Metacritic|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/dunkirk/critic-reviews|accessdate=21 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170722182106/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/dunkirk/critic-reviews|archive-date=22 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/07/dunkirk-success-christopher-nolan|title=How Dunkirk, Summer's Boldest Box-Office Gamble, Paid Off|magazine=Vanity Fair|date=24 July 2017|accessdate=1 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727032810/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/07/dunkirk-success-christopher-nolan|archive-date=27 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It grossed over $525{{nbsp}}million worldwide, which made it the highest-grossing World War{{nbsp}}II film of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/dunkirk-highest-grossing-world-war-2-movie/|title=Dunkirk Becomes Highest Grossing WWII Film at Global Box Office|work=Screen Rant|date=15 September 2017|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref> In his review, [[Mick LaSalle]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' wrote: \"It's one of the best [[war film]]s ever made, distinct in its look, in its approach and in the effect it has on viewers. There are movies\u2014they are rare\u2014that lift you out of your present circumstances and immerse you so fully in another experience that you watch in a state of jaw-dropped awe. ''Dunkirk'' is that kind of movie.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Dunkirk-is-Christopher-Nolan-s-masterpiece-11297495.php | title=Not a victory, but a triumph in 'Dunkirk' | newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle | accessdate=28 May 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190528083008/https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Dunkirk-is-Christopher-Nolan-s-masterpiece-11297495.php | archive-date=28 May 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The film received [[List of accolades received by Dunkirk|many accolades]], including Nolan's first Oscar nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]].<ref name=\"Oscars-18\">{{cite web|url=http://oscar.go.com/nominees|title=Oscar Nominations 2018: The Complete List \u2013 90th Academy Awards|publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]|date=23 January 2018|accessdate=23 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219195852/http://oscar.go.com/nominees|archive-date=19 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cannes 2018 4.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Nolan (right) with [[Keir Dullea]], Katharina Kubrick, Ron Sanders and [[Jan Harlan]] at the [[2018 Cannes Film Festival]].]]\n\nIn the months following the 2017\u201318 [[Oscar season]], Nolan began supervising a new 70mm print of [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s ''2001: A Space Odyssey'' (1968), made from the [[original camera negative]]; he presented it at the [[2018 Cannes Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-ca-mn-christopher-nolan-2001-20180503-story.html|title=Christopher Nolan restores Kubrick sci-fi masterpiece '2001: A Space Odyssey' the old-fashioned way|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=3 May 2018|accessdate=3 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510210339/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-ca-mn-christopher-nolan-2001-20180503-story.html|archive-date=10 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/christopher-nolan-cannes-stanley-kubrick-space-odyssey-2001-1202354670/|title=Cannes: Christopher Nolan To Present 70mm Print Of Stanley Kubrick's '2001: A Space Odyssey'|magazine=Deadline|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=3 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180328172210/http://deadline.com/2018/03/christopher-nolan-cannes-stanley-kubrick-space-odyssey-2001-1202354670/|archive-date=28 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> While in Cannes, the director also held a two-hour masterclass at the [[Palais des Festivals et des Congr\u00e8s|Palais des Festivals]]. ''[[USA Today]]'' observed that he was greeted \"like a rock star\", and with a prolonged standing ovation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2018/05/13/cannes-festival-christopher-nolan-inspires-crazed-crowd-talks-batman/605699002/|title=Christopher Nolan inspires crazed Cannes crowd, talks 'Batman' trilogy|newspaper=USA Today|date=13 May 2018|accessdate=14 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180513200908/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2018/05/13/cannes-festival-christopher-nolan-inspires-crazed-crowd-talks-batman/605699002/|archive-date=13 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, Nolan served as executive producer on ''The Doll's Breath'', an animated short directed by the Quay brothers.<ref name=\"Quay-Doll\">{{cite web|url=https://www.illuminationsmedia.co.uk/the-dolls-breath/|title=The Doll's Breath|publisher=illuminationsmedia|accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Upcoming projects ====\nNolan's eleventh feature, ''[[Tenet (film)|Tenet]]'', is scheduled to be released by Warner Bros. on 17 July 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20190522005664/en/Filming-Underway-%E2%80%9CTenet%E2%80%9D-New-Film-Christopher-Nolan|title=Filming is Underway on \"Tenet,\" a New Film from Christopher Nolan|website=Business Wire|date=22 May 2019|accessdate=22 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190523184738/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20190522005664/en/Filming-Underway-%25E2%2580%259CTenet%25E2%2580%259D-New-Film-Christopher-Nolan|archive-date=23 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Nolan wrote the screenplay and is producing with Emma Thomas. The film stars [[John David Washington]], [[Robert Pattinson]], [[Elizabeth Debicki]], [[Aaron Taylor-Johnson]], [[Dimple Kapadia]], [[Cl\u00e9mence Po\u00e9sy]], Kenneth Branagh and Michael Caine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/christopher-nolan-casts-pattinson-debicki/|title=Christopher Nolan's Next Film Adds Twilight, Guardians of the Galaxy Stars|website=[[CBR.com]]|last=Zachary|first=Brandon|date=21 March 2019|accessdate=22 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322122238/https://www.cbr.com/christopher-nolan-casts-pattinson-debicki/|archive-date=22 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Filmmaking ==\n{{Main|Cinematic style of Christopher Nolan}}\n\nNolan's films are often grounded in [[Existentialism|existential]] and [[Epistemology|epistemological]] themes, exploring the concepts of time, memory, and identity.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.grin.com/en/e-book/205383/time-memory-identity-the-films-of-christopher-nolan|title=Time, Memory & Identity: The Films of Christopher Nolan|year=2009|work=Grin \u2013 Master's Thesis written by Stuart Joy|accessdate=17 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201194745/http://www.grin.com/en/e-book/205383/time-memory-identity-the-films-of-christopher-nolan|archive-date=1 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Parks\">{{cite web|url=http://widescreenjournal.org/index.php/journal/article/viewFile/96/146|title=Identity Construction and Ambiguity in Christopher Nolan's Films|last=Parks|first=Erin Hill|date=June 2011|work=Widescreenjournal|accessdate=11 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425051550/http://widescreenjournal.org/index.php/journal/article/viewFile/96/146|archive-date=25 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://utpress.utexas.edu/index.php/books/mcgfic|title=The Fictional Christopher Nolan|publisher=University of Texas Press|accessdate=5 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005200914/http://utpress.utexas.edu/index.php/books/mcgfic|archive-date=5 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> His work is characterised by unconventional [[nonlinear narrative|narrative structures]], richly textured [[imagery]], and evocative use of music and sound.<ref name=\"Shone2014\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/nov/17/interstellar-sound-christopher-nolan|title=Interstellar's sound 'right for an experimental film', says Nolan|work=The Guardian|accessdate=29 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141117151023/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/nov/17/interstellar-sound-christopher-nolan|archive-date=17 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Film theory|Film theorist]] [[David Bordwell]] opined that Nolan has been able to blend his \"experimental impulses\" with the demands of mainstream entertainment, further describing his oeuvre as, \"experiments with cinematic time by means of techniques of subjective viewpoint and crosscutting.\"<ref name=\"Bordwell2019\">{{cite web|url=http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2019/01/28/nolan-book-2-0-cerebral-blockbusters-meet-blunt-force-cinephilia/|title=Nolan book 2.0: Cerebral blockbusters meet blunt-force cinephilia|last=Bordwell|first=David|date=28 January 2019|work=Observations on film art|accessdate=11 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190909104313/http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2019/01/28/nolan-book-2-0-cerebral-blockbusters-meet-blunt-force-cinephilia/|archive-date=9 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Nolan's use of practical, in-camera effects, miniatures and models, as well as shooting on celluloid film, has been highly influential in early [[Hollywood cinema in 21st century|21st century cinema]].<ref name=\"IndieW-19\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/influencers-team-christopher-nolan-1202192592/|title=Influencers: Christopher Nolan's Team Is the Big-Budget, Practical-Filmmaking Alternative|publisher=Indiewire|accessdate=12 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191203181719/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/influencers-team-christopher-nolan-1202192592/|archive-date=3 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''IndieWire'' wrote in 2019 that the director \"kept a viable alternate model of big-budget filmmaking alive\" in an era where blockbuster filmmaking has become \"a largely computer-generated art form.\"<ref name=\"IndieW-19\"/>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Christopher Nolan and Emma Thomas.jpg|thumb|Nolan and his wife [[Emma Thomas]] in January 2011]]\nNolan is married to [[Emma Thomas]], whom he met at University College London when he was 19.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/><ref name=\"British Cinematographer pt2\"/> She has worked as a producer on all of his films, and together they founded the production company [[Syncopy Inc.]]<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.empireonline.com/features/a-z/christopher-nolan/7.asp|accessdate=18 January 2014|magazine=Empire|title=The Z To A Of Christopher Nolan|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924051944/http://www.empireonline.com/features/a-z/christopher-nolan/7.asp|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The couple have four children and reside in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Christopher Nolan biography |publisher=Entertainment Scene 360 |url=http://www.entertainmentscene360.com/index.php/christopher-nolan-biography-252/ |accessdate=18 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202143859/http://www.entertainmentscene360.com/index.php/christopher-nolan-biography-252/ |archivedate=2 February 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/christopher-nolan|title=Christopher Nolan profile|magazine=Forbes|accessdate=18 January 2014|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140120171246/http://www.forbes.com/profile/christopher-nolan/|archive-date=20 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Protective of his privacy, he rarely discusses his personal life in interviews.<ref name=\"Lewis-Kraus\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/02/magazine/the-exacting-expansive-mind-of-christopher-nolan.html|last=Lewis-Kraus|first=Gideon|title=The Exacting, Expansive Mind of Christopher Nolan|work=The New York Times|accessdate=6 March 2016|date=30 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516070132/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/02/magazine/the-exacting-expansive-mind-of-christopher-nolan.html|archive-date=16 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> However, he has publicly shared some of his sociopolitical concerns for the future, such as the current conditions of nuclear weapons and environmental issues that he says need to be addressed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/christopher-nolan-uncut-on-interstellar-ben-afflecks-batman-and-the-future-of-mankind|accessdate=15 August 2017|website=The Daily Beast|title=Christopher Nolan Uncut: On 'Interstellar,' Ben Affleck's Batman, and the Future of Mankind|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730050522/http://www.thedailybeast.com/christopher-nolan-uncut-on-interstellar-ben-afflecks-batman-and-the-future-of-mankind|archive-date=30 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He has also expressed an admiration for [[scientific objectivity]], wishing it were applied \"in every aspect of our civilization.\"<ref name=\"ThorneNolan\">{{cite web|title=Watch Christopher Nolan and Kip Thorne Discuss the Physics of Interstellar|url=http://time.com/3602525/christopher-nolan-physics-interstellar-kip-thorne/|work=Time|accessdate=15 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160214175028/http://time.com/3602525/christopher-nolan-physics-interstellar-kip-thorne/|archive-date=14 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He is [[Red-Green color blindness|red-green colour blind]].<ref name=\"BAFTA-Pictures\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bafta.org/media-centre/transcripts/christopher-nolan-a-life-in-pictures | title=A Life in Pictures: Christopher Nolan | work=BAFTA | date=2 December 2017 | accessdate=21 April 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421091746/http://www.bafta.org/media-centre/transcripts/christopher-nolan-a-life-in-pictures | archive-date=21 April 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nNolan prefers not to use a mobile phone or an email address,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/dark-knight-rises-christopher-nolan-batman-352120 | title='Dark Knight Rises' Director Christopher Nolan's Shocking Admission: No Cell Phone, Email Address | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=19 July 2012 | accessdate=20 May 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803201801/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/dark-knight-rises-christopher-nolan-batman-352120 | archive-date=3 August 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> saying, \"It's not that I'm a [[Luddite]] and don't like technology; I've just never been interested ... When I moved to Los Angeles in 1997, nobody really had cell phones, and I just never went down that path.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.backstage.com/news/christopher-nolan-embraces-film-tech-but-doesnt-own-a-cell-phone/ | title=Christopher Nolan Embraces Film Tech But Doesn't Own a Cell Phone | work=Backstage | date=18 July 2012 | accessdate=6 January 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306082838/http://www.backstage.com/news/christopher-nolan-embraces-film-tech-but-doesnt-own-a-cell-phone/ | archive-date=6 March 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> He also prohibits use of phones on set.<ref name=\"cell phones on set\">{{cite web | url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/list-directors-interviewed-sam-mendes/ | title=A-List Directors, interviewed by Sam Mendes | work=Empire | date=21 October 2015 | accessdate=29 January 2015 | last=Mendes | first=Sam | authorlink=Sam Mendes | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029225147/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/list-directors-interviewed-sam-mendes/ | archive-date=29 October 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Recognition ==\nHaving made some of the most influential and popular films of his time,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/06/30/a-man-and-his-dream-christopher-nolan-and-inception/?|title=A Man and His Dream: Christopher Nolan and Inception|date=30 June 2010|work=The New York Times|accessdate=20 December 2013|first=Dave|last=Itzkoff|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140105012419/http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/06/30/a-man-and-his-dream-christopher-nolan-and-inception/|archive-date=5 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/tv-movie-creatives-that-defined-the-2010s/christopher-nolan|title=The Creatives That Defined the 2010s|publisher=Complex|accessdate=23 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/christopher-nolan-was-the-most-influential-filmmaker-of-00s/|title=Why Christopher Nolan Was the Quintessential Filmmaker of the 2000s|date=28 July 2017|work=Slashfilm|accessdate=11 January 2020|first=Joshua|last=Meyer}}</ref> Nolan's work has been as \"intensely embraced, analyzed and debated by ordinary film fans as by critics and film academics\".<ref name=\"Lewis-Kraus\"/><ref name=\"Descriptions\">{{cite web|title=An Evening with Christopher Nolan |url=http://www.ifccenter.com/films/an-evening-with-christopher-nolan |publisher=The Film Society of Lincoln Center \u2013 descriptions courtesy of The Criterion Collection and Film Society of Lincoln Center |accessdate=6 July 2013 |date=27 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130724221708/http://www.ifccenter.com/films/an-evening-with-christopher-nolan/ |archivedate=24 July 2013 }}</ref> Several of his films have been regarded by critics as among the best of their respective decades,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critics-pick-the-best-movies-of-the-decade|title=Film Critics Pick the Best Movies of the Decade|website=Metacritic.com |date=3 January 2010|accessdate=23 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-movies-of-the-decade-2010s|title=Best Movies of the Decade (2010-19)|website=Metacritic.com |date=18 December 2019|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://film.avclub.com/the-best-films-of-the-00s-1798222348|title=The best films of the '00s|accessdate=27 November 2019|newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]]| date=3 December 2009 |first1=Keith |last1=Phipps |first2=Tasha |last2=Robinson |first3=Nathan |last3=Rabin |first4=Scott |last4=Tobias |first5=Noel |last5=Murray}}</ref> and according to ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', his \"ability to combine box-office success with artistic ambition has given him an extraordinary amount of clout in the industry.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://online.wsj.com/articles/why-hollywood-loves-interstellar-director-christopher-nolan-1414677657|title=Why Hollywood Loves 'Interstellar' Director Christopher Nolan|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=30 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102063958/http://online.wsj.com/articles/why-hollywood-loves-interstellar-director-christopher-nolan-1414677657|archive-date=2 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, ''Memento'', ''The Dark Knight'', and ''Inception'' appeared in [[BBC's 100 Greatest Films of the 21st Century]] list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20160819-the-21st-centurys-100-greatest-films |title=The 21st Century's 100 greatest films |publisher=BBC |date=23 August 2016 |accessdate=21 January 2017}}</ref> In the following year, five of his (then nine) films featured in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine's poll of \"The 100 Greatest Movies\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/best-movies/|title=The 100 Greatest Movies|website=Empireonline.com |date=23 June 2017|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' categorised Nolan as a \"brand-name director\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/23/business/media/in-blockbuster-era-no-room-at-the-box-office-for-the-middlebrow.html|title=In Blockbuster Era, No Room at the Box Office for the Middlebrow|date=23 November 2019|work=The New York Times|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> while ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' described him as \"a Hollywood franchise unto himself.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/thr-100-hollywood-reporters-powerful-people-entertainment-1142979/item/thr-100-2018-randy-freer-1143892|title=The Hollywood Reporter 100: The Most Powerful People in Entertainment 2018|date=20 September 2018|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Geoff Andrew]] of the [[British Film Institute]] and ''[[Sight & Sound]]'' magazine, called Nolan \"a persuasively inventive storyteller\", singling him out as one of the few contemporary filmmakers producing highly personal films within the Hollywood mainstream. He also pointed out that his films are as notable for their \"considerable technical virtuosity and visual flair\" as for their \"brilliant narrative ingenuity and their unusually adult interest in complex philosophical questions\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://whatson.bfi.org.uk/Online/default.asp?doWork::WScontent::loadArticle=Load&BOparam::WScontent::loadArticle::article_id=92EC9074-583B-4953-AAFA-52B5F705731C|title=Christopher Nolan|year=2012|work=British Film Institute|accessdate=17 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620180635/https://whatson.bfi.org.uk/Online/default.asp?doWork::WScontent::loadArticle=Load&BOparam::WScontent::loadArticle::article_id=92EC9074-583B-4953-AAFA-52B5F705731C|archive-date=20 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/arts-and-books/widescreen-hollywoods-big-ideas|title=Widescreen: Hollywood's big ideas|publisher=Prospect|accessdate=30 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816232932/http://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/arts-and-books/widescreen-hollywoods-big-ideas|archive-date=16 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> David Bordwell observed that Nolan is \"considered one of the most accomplished living filmmakers,\" citing his ability to turn genre movies into both art and event films, as well as his box office numbers, critical acclaim, and popularity among cinemagoers.<ref name=\"Bordwell2019\">{{cite web|url=http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2019/01/28/nolan-book-2-0-cerebral-blockbusters-meet-blunt-force-cinephilia/|title=Nolan book 2.0: Cerebral blockbusters meet blunt-force cinephilia|last=Bordwell|first=David|date=28 January 2019|work=Observations on film art|accessdate=11 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190909104313/http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2019/01/28/nolan-book-2-0-cerebral-blockbusters-meet-blunt-force-cinephilia/|archive-date=9 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BordwellDunkirk\">{{cite web|title=DUNKIRK Part 2: The art film as event movie|url=http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2017/08/09/dunkirk-part-2-the-art-film-as-event-movie/|work=Observations on film art|accessdate=10 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810170522/http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2017/08/09/dunkirk-part-2-the-art-film-as-event-movie/|archive-date=10 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2008, film critic [[Philip French]] deemed Nolan \"The first major talent to emerge this [21st] century\",<ref name=\"French-50\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/apr/13/features.culture2|title=The top 50|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=21 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227024901/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/apr/13/features.culture2|archive-date=27 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> while ''[[Forbes]]'' called him \"one of the most successful and acclaimed filmmakers of our time\" in 2015.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/markhughes/2015/09/11/why-akira-could-be-christopher-nolans-next-film/#5d198de21474|title=Why 'Akira' Could Be Christopher Nolan's Next Film|magazine=Forbes|accessdate=30 June 2019|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630115858/https://www.forbes.com/sites/markhughes/2015/09/11/why-akira-could-be-christopher-nolans-next-film/#5d198de21474|archive-date=30 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Film critic [[Mark Kermode]] complimented the director for bringing \"the discipline and ethics of art-house independent moviemaking\" to Hollywood blockbusters, calling him \"living proof that you don't have to appeal to the lowest common denominator to be profitable\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenational.ae/lifestyle/newsmaker-christopher-nolan-is-a-different-kind-of-storyteller#page2|title=Newsmaker: Christopher Nolan is a different kind of storyteller|date=14 June 2013|publisher=The National|accessdate=21 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223144206/http://www.thenational.ae/lifestyle/newsmaker-christopher-nolan-is-a-different-kind-of-storyteller#page2|archive-date=23 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Observer]]'' described Nolan as a \"skilful, stylish storyteller, capable of combining the spectacle of Spielberg with the intellectual intricacy of [[Nicolas Roeg]] or [[Alain Resnais]]\".<ref name=\"Observer17\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/jul/22/christopher-nolan-dunkirk-batman-observer-profile-profile|last=Gilbey|first=Ryan|title=Christopher Nolan: from superheroes to Dunkirk's small tales of heroism|accessdate=30 June 2019|date=23 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630131849/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/jul/22/christopher-nolan-dunkirk-batman-observer-profile-profile|archive-date=30 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mark Cousins (film critic)|Mark Cousins]] applauded the director for embracing big ideas, \"Hollywood filmmakers generally shy away from ideas \u2014 but not Christopher Nolan\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/magazine/widescreen-hollywoods-big-ideas|title=Widescreen: Hollywood's big ideas|publisher=Prospect Magazine|accessdate=5 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720171750/https://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/magazine/widescreen-hollywoods-big-ideas|archive-date=20 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Scott Foundas of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' declared Nolan \"the premier big-canvas storyteller of his generation\",<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/film-review-interstellar-1201338475/|title=Film Review: 'Interstellar'|magazine=Variety|accessdate=30 October 2014|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141029234605/http://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/film-review-interstellar-1201338475/|archive-date=29 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> while [[Justin Chang]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called him \"the great [[proceduralist]] of 21st century blockbuster filmmaking, a lover of nuts-and-bolts minutiae.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-ca-mn-dark-knight-10th-anniversary-20180822-story.html|title=Ten years after it changed Hollywood, 'The Dark Knight' is back in theaters. Accept no substitutes|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=23 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822230952/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-ca-mn-dark-knight-10th-anniversary-20180822-story.html|archive-date=22 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe filmmaker has been praised by many of his contemporaries, and some have cited his work as influencing their own.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2016/06/duncan-jones-warcraft-christopher-nolan-moon-mute-interview-1201682897/|title=Duncan Jones on How He Models His Career After Christopher Nolan \u2013 Q&A|date=2 June 2017|work=Indiewire|accessdate=11 April 2019|first=Kate|last=Erbland|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411124616/https://www.indiewire.com/2016/06/duncan-jones-warcraft-christopher-nolan-moon-mute-interview-1201682897/|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/sam-mendes-says-he-was-not-at-all-interested-in-bond-at-first-took-direct-inspiration-from-christopher-nolans-dark-knight-films-20121018|title=Sam Mendes Says He Was \"Not at All\" Interested in Bond at First, Took Direct Inspiration From Nolan's 'Dark Knight' Films|date=18 October 2012|publisher=The Playlist|accessdate=26 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130110082142/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/sam-mendes-says-he-was-not-at-all-interested-in-bond-at-first-took-direct-inspiration-from-christopher-nolans-dark-knight-films-20121018|archive-date=10 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.empireonline.com/features/the-dark-knight-effect|title=The Dark Knight Effect \u2013 How Hollywood fell for \u2013 and learned from \u2013 the greatest superhero sequel ever made|date=23 July 2012|magazine=Empire|accessdate=26 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113083236/http://www.empireonline.com/features/the-dark-knight-effect|archive-date=13 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Rupert Wyatt]] said in an interview that he thinks of Nolan as a \"trailblazer{{nbsp}}... he is to be hugely admired as a master filmmaker, but also someone who has given others behind him a stick to beat back the naysayers who never thought a modern mass audience would be willing to embrace story and character as much as spectacle\".<ref name=\"Harding\">{{cite web|url=http://whatculture.com/film/exclusive-interview-rupert-wyatt-on-birdsong-why-he-quit-planet-of-the-apes.php#|last=Harding|first=Oscar|title=Exclusive Interview: Rupert Wyatt On Birdsong & Why He Quit Planet Of The Apes|work=Whatculture!|accessdate=4 June 2013|date=15 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605074302/http://whatculture.com/film/exclusive-interview-rupert-wyatt-on-birdsong-why-he-quit-planet-of-the-apes.php|archive-date=5 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Kenneth Branagh called Nolan's approach to large-scale filmmaking \"unique in modern cinema\", adding \"regardless of how popular his movies become, he remains an artist and an [[auteur]]. I think for that reason he has become a heroic figure for both the audience and the people working behind the camera.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://roadshow.com.au/articles/2017/6/kenneth-branagh-on-dunkirk |title=Kenneth Branagh on Dunkirk and The Nolan Experience |publisher=Roadshow |date=29 June 2017 |accessdate=25 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180325232650/https://roadshow.com.au/articles/2017/6/kenneth-branagh-on-dunkirk |archive-date=25 March 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Michael Mann (director)|Michael Mann]] complimented Nolan for his \"singular vision\" and called him \"a complete auteur\".<ref name=ShoneBlogspot>{{cite web|first=Tom|last=Shone|url=http://tomshone.blogspot.no/2014/11/christopher-nolan-directors-cut.html|title=Christopher Nolan: The Director's Cut|publisher=These Violent Delights, Tom Shone|date=4 November 2014|accessdate=23 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105014410/http://tomshone.blogspot.no/2014/11/christopher-nolan-directors-cut.html|archive-date=5 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Nicolas Roeg said of Nolan, \"[His] films have a magic to them{{nbsp}}... People talk about 'commercial art' and the term is usually self-negating; Nolan works in the commercial arena and yet there's something very poetic about his work.\"<ref name=\"ShoneBlogspot\"/> Martin Scorsese identified Nolan as a filmmaker creating \"beautifully made films on a big scale\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://filmtalk.org/2015/10/26/martin-scorsese-theres-always-the-budget-but-i-am-more-concerned-about-the-creative-freedom/|title=Martin Scorsese: There's always the budget, but I am more concerned about the creative freedom|date=26 October 2015|publisher=Filmtalk|accessdate=13 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025044907/https://filmtalk.org/2015/10/26/martin-scorsese-theres-always-the-budget-but-i-am-more-concerned-about-the-creative-freedom/|archive-date=25 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\nand [[Luca Guadagnino]] called him \"one of the ultimate auteurs.\"<ref name=Guadagnino>{{cite news|url=http://the-talks.com/interview/luca-guadagnino|title=Luca Guadagnino: \"I Try To Surrender To My Evidences\"|author=Kaleem Aftab|date=21 March 2018|work=The Talks|accessdate=21 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723190031/https://the-talks.com/interview/luca-guadagnino/|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Damien Chazelle]] said of Nolan, \"This is a filmmaker who has managed, time and again, to make the most seemingly impersonal projects \u2014 superhero epics, deep-space mind-benders \u2014 feel deeply personal\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/gallery/directors-on-directors-get-out-lady-bird/#!2/dunkirk-13|title=Damien Chazelle on ''Dunkirk''|magazine=Variety|accessdate=6 December 2017|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206041800/http://variety.com/gallery/directors-on-directors-get-out-lady-bird/#!2/dunkirk-13|archive-date=6 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Olivier Assayas]] said he admired Nolan for \"making movies that are really unlike anything else. The way I see it, he has a really authentic voice.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://filmtalk.org/2016/10/13/olivier-assayas-kristens-stewart-approach-to-acting-is-very-honest-very-human-and-very-pure/|title=Olivier Assayas: Kristen Stewart's approach to acting is very honest, very human and very pure|publisher=Film Talk|accessdate=14 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116165102/https://filmtalk.org/2016/10/13/olivier-assayas-kristens-stewart-approach-to-acting-is-very-honest-very-human-and-very-pure/|archive-date=16 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Discussing the difference between [[art film]]s and big studio blockbusters, [[Steven Spielberg]] referred to Nolan's ''Dark Knight'' series as an example of both;<ref>{{cite web|url=//www.youtube.com/watch?v=r69N56plrDE|title=In conversation with Steven Spielberg and Stacey Snider on The Front Row|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=16 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130728072836/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r69N56plrDE|archive-date=28 July 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> he has described ''Memento'' and ''Inception'' as \"masterworks\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.azcentral.com/thingstodo/movies/articles/2011/12/09/20111209steven-spielbergs-interview-goodykoontz-tintin-warhorse.html|title=Interview: Steven Spielberg talks movies 'Tintin,' 'War Horse'|date=19 December 2011|publisher=AzCentral|accessdate=26 January 2013}}</ref> [[Denis Villeneuve]] said of Nolan, \"[He] is a very impressive filmmaker, because he is able to keep his identity and create his own universe in that large scope ... To bring intellectual concepts and to bring them in that scope to the screen right now \u2014 it's very rare. Every movie that he comes out with, I have more admiration for his work.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/12/denis-villenueve-influences-christopher-nolan-steven-spielberg-ingmar-bergman-1201904623/|title=Denis Villenueve Aspires to Be Like Christopher Nolan, and Why He Wants to Make 'Dune'|date=22 December 2017|work=Indiewire|accessdate=23 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223192347/https://www.indiewire.com/2017/12/denis-villenueve-influences-christopher-nolan-steven-spielberg-ingmar-bergman-1201904623/|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSome of his films have been referenced extensively in popular culture,<ref>Eberl, Dunn, p. 1.</ref> and in 2013 a survey of seventeen film academics showed that Nolan was among the most studied directors in Britain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a529084/quentin-tarantino-is-most-studied-director-in-the-uk.html|title=Quentin Tarantino is most-studied director in the UK|date=6 November 2013|website=Digital Spy|accessdate=6 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131108105528/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a529084/quentin-tarantino-is-most-studied-director-in-the-uk.html|archive-date=8 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Nolan appeared in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'s}} [[Time 100|100 most influential people in the world]] in 2015 and in the [[Forbes Celebrity 100|''Forbes'' Celebrity 100]] in 2011 and 2013.<ref>[http://time.com/3822892/christopher-nolan-2015-time-100 \"Christopher Nolan\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417010758/http://time.com/3822892/christopher-nolan-2015-time-100/ |date=17 April 2015 }}, ''Time'', 16 April 2015; retrieved 16 April 2015.</ref><ref name=\"forbes-2011\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2012/celebrities/celebrity-100_2011.html|title=The World's Most Powerful Celebrities|magazine=Forbes|accessdate=29 January 2018|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160905004028/http://www.forbes.com/lists/2012/celebrities/celebrity-100_2011.html|archive-date=5 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography and awards ==\n{{Main|Christopher Nolan filmography|List of awards and nominations received by Christopher Nolan|l2=awards and nominations}}\n[[File:Christopher Nolan TCL.jpg|thumb|right|Nolan's hand and shoeprints in front of the [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]] in Hollywood]]\n\nNolan was named an Honorary Fellow of UCL in 2006, and conferred an [[Honorary degree|honorary doctorate]] in literature (DLit) in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/about-ucl/who-we-are/honorary-fellows|title=Honorary Fellows of UCL|publisher=UCL|year=2006|accessdate=11 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923115521/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/about-ucl/who-we-are/honorary-fellows|archive-date=23 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/campaign/campaign-news/christopher_nolan_honorary_doctorate|title=Back to where it all began: Christopher Nolan awarded honorary doctorate at UCL|publisher=UCL|year=2017|accessdate=15 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170916074807/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/campaign/campaign-news/christopher_nolan_honorary_doctorate|archive-date=16 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2012, he became the youngest director to receive a hand-and-footprint ceremony at [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2012/07/07/christopher-nolan-hand-and-footprint-ceremony/ |title=Christopher Nolan Hand and Footprint Ceremony, EW Magazine |access-date=28 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120808193929/http://insidemovies.ew.com/2012/07/07/christopher-nolan-hand-and-footprint-ceremony/ |archive-date=8 August 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Nolan was appointed Commander of the [[Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the [[2019 New Year Honours]] for his services to film.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/767769/DSO_NY19_CH___BE_HMTQ.pdf|title=OFFICIAL SENSITIVE \u2013 HONOURS|date=29 December 2018|accessdate=29 December 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190114225012/https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/767769/DSO_NY19_CH___BE_HMTQ.pdf|archive-date=14 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''Directed features:'''\n* ''[[Following]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Memento (film)|Memento]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Insomnia (2002 film)|Insomnia]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Batman Begins]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Prestige (film)|The Prestige]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Inception]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[The Dark Knight Rises]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Interstellar (film)|Interstellar]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Dunkirk (2017 film)|Dunkirk]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Tenet (film)|Tenet]]'' (2020)\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-ua}}\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Gouda|first=Soman|title=Yogi in Suits:Christopher Nolan and Vedanta|url=https://g.co/kgs/VthdpH |date=24 March 2018|publisher=SomeKranthi|isbn=978-1-9806-1543-9}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Conard|first=Mark|title=The Philosophy of Neo-Noir|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6J5uLqU8y58C&pg=PA35|date=5 January 2007|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=978-0-8131-7230-9}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Kellner|first=Douglas M|title=Cinema Wars: Hollywood Film and Politics in the Bush-Cheney Era|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GrQnyVqWBzYC&pg=PA2011 |date=21 December 2009|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell; 1 edition|isbn=978-1405198240}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Duncan Jesser |first1=Jody |first2=Janine |last2=Pourroy |title=The Art and Making of The Dark Knight Trilogy |publisher=Abrams |year=2012 |isbn=978-1-4197-0369-0}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Fischer |first=Mark |title=The Lost Unconscious: Delusions and Dreams in Inception. |publisher=Film Quarterly, Volume 64 (3) University of California Press |year=2011}}\n* {{Cite book |last=McGowan |first=Todd |title=The Fictional Christopher Nolan |location=Texas |publisher=the University of Texas Press |year=2012 |isbn=978-0-292-73782-2 }}\n* {{Cite book |last=Mottram |first=James |title=The Making of Memento |location=New York |publisher=Faber |year=2002 |isbn=0-571-21488-6 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/makingofmemento00mott }}\n* {{Cite book |last1=deWaard |first1=Andrew |first2=R. Colin |last2=Tait |title=The Cinema of Steven Soderbergh: Indie Sex, Corporate Lies, and Digital Videotape |publisher=Columbia University Press |year=2013 |isbn=978-0-231-16551-8}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Rabiger |first1=Michael |first2=Mick |last2=Hurbis-Cherrier |title=Directing: Film Techniques and Aesthetics |publisher=CRC Press |year=2013 |isbn=978-1-135-09921-3}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=O'Sullivan |first1=Natalia |first2=Nicola |last2=Graydon |title=The Ancestral Continuum: Unlock the Secrets of Who You Really Are |publisher=Simon and Schuster |year=2013 |isbn=978-1-451-67454-5}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Furby |first1=Jacqueline |first2=Stuart |last2=Joy |title=The Cinema of Christopher Nolan: Imagining the Impossible |publisher=Columbia University Press |year=2015 |isbn=978-0-231-85076-6}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Eberl |first1=Jason T. |first2=George A. |last2=Dunn |title=The Philosophy of Christopher Nolan |publisher=Lexington Books |year=2017 |isbn=978-1-498-51352-4}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Abad |first=Jos\u00e9 |title=Christopher Nolan |location=Madrid |publisher=C\u00e1tedra |year=2018 |isbn=978-84-376-3772-3}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Mooney |first=Darren |title=Christopher Nolan: A Critical Study of the Films |publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc. |year=2018 |isbn=978-14-766-7480-3}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Cameron |first=James |title=James Cameron's Story of Science Fiction |publisher=Simon and Schuster |year=2018 |isbn=978-16-838-3590-5}}\n\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q25191|c=category:Christopher Nolan|b=no|v=no|voy=no|s=no|wikt=no|n=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no}}\n* {{IMDb name|634240}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes person|christopher_nolan|Christopher Nolan}}\n* {{Allmovie name|240025|Christopher Nolan}}\n* [http://www.tribute.ca/people/christopher-nolan/6453/35045/ Christopher Nolan Biography] at [http://www.tribute.ca Tribute.ca]\n* [http://www.indiefilmhustle.com/christopher-nolan/ Christopher Nolan \u2013 How to Direct Your First Feature Film]\n{{Christopher Nolan|state=expanded}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Christopher Nolan|Awards for Christopher Nolan]]\n|list  =\n{{AACTA International Award for Best Direction}}\n{{BAFTA Los Angeles Britannia Awards}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Screenplay}}\n{{Empire Award for Best Director}}\n{{IndependentAwardforBestDirector}}\n{{Independent Spirit Award for Best Screenplay}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best New Filmmaker}}\n{{Nebula Award for Best Script/Bradbury Award 2001\u20132020}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Director}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Writing 1991\u20132010}}\n{{Writers Guild of America Award for Best Original Screenplay}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nolan, Christopher}}\n[[Category:Christopher Nolan| ]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Action film directors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College London]]\n[[Category:American cinematographers]]\n[[Category:American film editors]]\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:American film producers]]\n[[Category:American film production company founders]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Best Director AACTA International Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Director Empire Award winners]]\n[[Category:British film production company founders]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:David di Donatello winners]]\n[[Category:Edgar Award winners]]\n[[Category:Empire Inspiration Award winners]]\n[[Category:English cinematographers]]\n[[Category:English film directors]]\n[[Category:English film editors]]\n[[Category:English film producers]]\n[[Category:English male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:English people of American descent]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Film directors from London]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Film producers from California]]\n[[Category:Film producers from London]]\n[[Category:Hugo Award-winning writers]]\n[[Category:Independent Spirit Award for Best Director winners]]\n[[Category:People educated at Haileybury and Imperial Service College]]\n[[Category:People from Westminster]]\n[[Category:Science fiction film directors]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from California]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Sundance Film Festival award winners]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Writers from Evanston, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n[[Category:Writers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Writers Guild of America Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Christopher Nolan}}\n{{short description|British\u2013American filmmaker}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Christopher Nolan\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}}\n| image            = Christopher Nolan Cannes 2018.jpg\n| caption          = Nolan at the [[2018 Cannes Film Festival]]\n| birth_name       = Christopher Edward Nolan\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1970|7|30}}\n| birth_place      = [[Westminster]], [[London]], England\n| citizenship      = {{hlist|United Kingdom|United States}}\n| alma_mater       = [[University College London]]\n| occupation       = Filmmaker\n| years_active     = 1989\u2013present\n| works            = [[Christopher Nolan filmography|Full list]]\n| spouse           = {{marriage|[[Emma Thomas]]|1997}}\n| children         = 4\n| relatives        = [[Jonathan Nolan]] (brother)<br />[[John Nolan (British actor)|John Nolan]] (uncle)<br />[[Lisa Joy]] (sister-in-law)\n| awards           = [[List of awards and nominations received by Christopher Nolan|Full list]]\n}}\n\n'''Christopher Edward Nolan''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE}} ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|n|o\u028a|l|\u0259|n}}; born 30 July 1970) is a British-American filmmaker known for making personal, distinctive films within the [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]] mainstream. [[Christopher Nolan filmography|His ten films]] have grossed over US$4.7{{nbsp}}billion worldwide and garnered a total of 34 [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] nominations and ten wins.\n\nBorn and raised in [[London]], Nolan developed an interest in filmmaking from a young age. After studying English literature at [[University College London]], he made his feature debut with ''[[Following]]'' (1998). Nolan gained international recognition with his second film, ''[[Memento (film)|Memento]]'' (2000), for which he was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay]]. He transitioned from independent to studio filmmaking with ''[[Insomnia (2002 film)|Insomnia]]'' (2002), and found further critical and commercial success with ''[[The Dark Knight Trilogy]]'' (2005\u20132012), ''[[The Prestige (film)|The Prestige]]'' (2006), and ''[[Inception]]'' (2010), which received eight Oscar nominations, including for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] and Best Original Screenplay. This was followed by ''[[Interstellar (film)|Interstellar]]'' (2014) and ''[[Dunkirk (2017 film)|Dunkirk]]'' (2017), the latter of which earned him Academy Award nominations for Best Picture and [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]].\n\nNolan's films are typically rooted in [[Epistemology|epistemological]] and [[Metaphysics|metaphysical]] themes, exploring human morality, the construction of [[time]], and the malleable nature of [[memory]] and [[personal identity]]. [[Cinematic style of Christopher Nolan|His work]] is permeated by unconventional [[Nonlinear narrative|narrative structures]], [[practical special effects]], experimental soundscapes, [[70 mm film|large-format]] film photography, and [[Materialism|materialistic]] perspectives. He has co-written several of his films with his brother [[Jonathan Nolan|Jonathan]], and runs the production company [[Syncopy Inc.]] with his wife [[Emma Thomas]].\n\nNolan has received many [[List of awards and nominations received by Christopher Nolan|awards and honours]]. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine named him one of the [[Time 100|100 most influential people in the world]] in 2015, and in 2019, he was appointed Commander of the [[Order of the British Empire]] for his services to film. In addition to his filmmaking, Nolan is an advocate for [[film preservation]] and the [[film stock|analog medium]].\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Life and career ==\n=== 1970\u20131997: Early life and career beginnings ===\nNolan was born in [[Westminster]], [[London]], and grew up in [[Highgate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2bbfd6e83e|title=Christopher Nolan|publisher=British Film Institute (BFI)|accessdate=4 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311164847/http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2bbfd6e83e|archive-date=11 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=Fuv8tRfxQgrEic7cP%2Bx9Rg&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=8 March 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> His father, Brendan James Nolan, was a British advertising executive who worked as a creative director.<ref>Mooney, p. 3.</ref> His mother, Christina (n\u00e9e Jensen), was an American [[flight attendant]] who would later work as an English teacher.<ref>Mooney, p. 3.</ref><ref name=\"Shone2014\" /><ref name=\"Feinberg\">{{cite magazine|title=Christopher Nolan on 'Interstellar' Critics, Making Original Films and Shunning Cell Phones and Email (Q&A)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/christopher-nolan-interstellar-critics-making-760897|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|author=Feinberg, Scott|date=3 January 2015|accessdate=1 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117111636/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/christopher-nolan-interstellar-critics-making-760897|archive-date=17 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Nolan's childhood was split between London and [[Evanston, Illinois]], and he has both British and US citizenship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/ct-interstellar-christopher-nolan-20141030-column.html|title=Christopher Nolan injects his sci-fi with soul|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=7 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308133759/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/ct-interstellar-christopher-nolan-20141030-column.html|archive-date=8 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Boucher\">{{cite news|url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/2010/04/11/christopher-nolans-inception-hollywoods-first-existential-heist-film|title=Christopher Nolan's 'Inception'&nbsp;\u2014 Hollywood's first existential heist film|last=Boucher|first=Geoff|date=11 April 2010|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=28 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110204203937/http://herocomplex.latimes.com/2010/04/11/christopher-nolans-inception-hollywoods-first-existential-heist-film/|archive-date=4 February 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Itzkoff|first=Dave|title=The Man Behind the Dreamscape|work=The New York Times|date=30 June 2010|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/04/movies/04inception.html|accessdate=1 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114141507/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/04/movies/04inception.html|archive-date=14 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Christopher Nolan's Inception tops British box office|work=BBC|date=22 July 2010|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/threecounties/hi/front_page/newsid_8845000/8845715.stm|accessdate=5 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917015720/http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/threecounties/hi/front_page/newsid_8845000/8845715.stm|archive-date=17 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He has an older brother, Matthew Francis Nolan, a convicted criminal,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-07-07/news/ct-met-escape-sentencing-20100707_1_costa-rica-fake-british-passport-extradited|title=Nolan sentenced for escape attempt|work=Chicago Tribune|date=7 July 2010|accessdate=24 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821110202/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-07-07/news/ct-met-escape-sentencing-20100707_1_costa-rica-fake-british-passport-extradited|archive-date=21 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and a younger brother, [[Jonathan Nolan|Jonathan]].<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news|title=Christopher Nolan interview for Inception|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmmakersonfilm/7894376/Christopher-Nolan-interview-for-Inception.html|newspaper=The Telegraph|author=Lawrence, Will|date=19 July 2012|accessdate=3 January 2014|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131117141943/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmmakersonfilm/7894376/Christopher-Nolan-interview-for-Inception.html|archive-date=17 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Growing up, Nolan was particularly influenced by the work of [[Ridley Scott]], and the science fiction films ''[[2001: A Space Odyssey (film)|2001: A Space Odyssey]]'' (1968) and ''[[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]]'' (1977).<ref>Mooney, p. 4.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/hollywood/on-christopher-nolan-s-birthday-how-many-of-his-15-favourite-films-have-you-seen/story-Ol1qwIWL9hBUQTS9ZkqICO.html|title=On Christopher Nolan\u2019s birthday, how many of his 15 favourite films have you seen?|work=Hindustan Times|date=31 July 2019|accessdate=2 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190928034554/https://www.hindustantimes.com/hollywood/on-christopher-nolan-s-birthday-how-many-of-his-15-favourite-films-have-you-seen/story-Ol1qwIWL9hBUQTS9ZkqICO.html|archive-date=28 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He began making films at age seven, borrowing his father's [[Super 8 mm film|Super{{nbsp}}8 camera]] and shooting short films with his action figures.<ref name=\"Timberg\">{{cite web|url=http://cinefiles.bampfa.berkeley.edu/cinefiles/DocDetail?docId=49987|last=Timberg|first=Scott|title=Indie Angst|work=New Times Los Angeles|accessdate=4 June 2013|date=15 March 2001|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815135228/https://cinefiles.bampfa.berkeley.edu/cinefiles/DocDetail?docId=49987|archive-date=15 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/film/nolans-move-from-highgate-to-hollywood-7381904.html \"Nolan's move from Highgate to Hollywood\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826194400/https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/film/nolans-move-from-highgate-to-hollywood-7381904.html |date=26 August 2017 }}, ''Evening Standard'' (London); retrieved 10 April 2011.</ref> These films included a [[Stop motion|stop motion animation]] homage to ''Star Wars'' called ''Space Wars''. He cast his brother Jonathan and built sets from \"clay, flour, egg boxes and toilet rolls.\"<ref>Mooney, p. 4.</ref> His uncle, who worked at [[NASA]] building guidance systems for the [[Apollo program|Apollo]] rockets, sent him some launch footage: \"I re-filmed them off the screen and cut them in, thinking no-one would notice,\" Nolan later remarked.<ref name=\"Shone2014\">{{cite journal|last=Shone|first=Tom|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/nov/04/-sp-christopher-nolan-interstellar-rebooted-blockbuster|title=Christopher Nolan: the man who rebooted the blockbuster|journal=The Guardian|date=4 November 2014|accessdate=24 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122014558/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/nov/04/-sp-christopher-nolan-interstellar-rebooted-blockbuster|archive-date=22 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andrewpurcell.net/?p=2000|title=Christopher Nolan's final frontier|publisher=Andrew Purcell|accessdate=7 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518084035/http://www.andrewpurcell.net/?p=2000|archive-date=18 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Covert|first=Colin|url=http://blog.startribune.com/christopher-nolan-explains-his-cinematic-brain-at-walker-art-center/302854481|title=Christopher Nolan explains his 'cinematic brain' at Walker Art Center|journal=StarTribune|accessdate=6 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150510011838/http://blog.startribune.com/christopher-nolan-explains-his-cinematic-brain-at-walker-art-center/302854481/|archive-date=10 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> From the age of eleven, he aspired to be a professional filmmaker.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/> In his teenage years, Nolan started making films with Adrien and [[Roko Belic]]. Nolan and Roko co\u2013directed the [[surrealism|surreal]] [[Super 8 film|8{{nbsp}}mm]] ''Tarantella'' (1989), which was shown on ''Image Union'', an independent film and video showcase on the [[Public Broadcasting Service]].{{refn|group=note|Nolan has continued his collaboration with the brothers, receiving a credit for his editorial assistance on their Oscar-nominated documentary ''[[Genghis Blues]]'' (1999).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicdoc.se/genghis-blues|title=Genghis Blues|publisher=Musicdoc.se|accessdate=2 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815062817/http://www.musicdoc.se/genghis-blues/|archive-date=15 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Nolan also worked alongside Roko Belic on documenting a safari across four African countries, organised by the late photojournalist [[Dan Eldon]] in the early 1990s.<ref>O'Sullivan, Graydon (2013), p. 67.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/amy-eldon-turteltaub/dan-eldon_b_3582633.html|title=Remembering My Brother Dan Eldon: A Journalist Who Died To Tell the Story|publisher=Huffingtonpost|date=7 December 2013|accessdate=30 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812045120/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/amy-eldon-turteltaub/dan-eldon_b_3582633.html|archive-date=12 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>}}<ref>Mooney, p. 5.</ref>\n\n[[File:Flaxman Gallery, UCL.JPG|thumb|right|220x220px|Nolan attended [[University College London]], and used its Flaxman Gallery for a scene in ''[[Inception]]'' (2010).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://filmlondon.org.uk/news/2010/july/nolans_mind_games|title=Nolan's Mind Games|accessdate=11 August 2010|publisher=Film London|date=14 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101122213601/http://filmlondon.org.uk/news/2010/july/nolans_mind_games|archive-date=22 November 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>]]\n\nNolan was educated at [[Haileybury and Imperial Service College]], an independent school in [[Hertford Heath]], [[Hertfordshire]], and later read [[English literature]] at [[University College London]] (UCL). Opting out of a traditional film education, he pursued \"a degree in something unrelated ... because it gives a different take on things.\"<ref>Mooney, p. 6.</ref> He chose UCL specifically for its filmmaking facilities, which comprised a [[Steenbeck|Steenbeck editing suite]] and [[16 mm film#Cameras|16{{nbsp}}mm film cameras]].<ref name=\"Tempest\">Tempest, M. [https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2011/feb/24/inception-christopher-nolan-film-oscar-director \"I was there at the 'Inception' of Christopher Nolan's film career\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005100119/http://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2011/feb/24/inception-christopher-nolan-film-oscar-director |date=5 October 2013 }}, ''The Guardian'', 24 February 2011; retrieved 21 September 2011.</ref> Nolan was president of the Union's Film Society,<ref name=\"Tempest\"/> and with [[Emma Thomas]] (his girlfriend and future wife) he screened [[35mm movie film|35 mm]] feature films during the school year and used the money earned to produce [[16 mm]] films over the summers.<ref name=\"British Cinematographer pt2\">{{cite web|title=Wally Pfister ASC on Christopher Nolan's Inception|url=http://www.thecinematographer.info/articles/18-wally-pfister.html|work=thecinematographer.info|year=2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120411005825/http://www.thecinematographer.info/articles/18-wally-pfister.html|archivedate=11 April 2012|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter earning his bachelor's degree in English literature in 1993, Nolan worked as a [[Script analyst|script reader]], [[camera operator]], and director of [[corporate video]]s and [[Sponsored film|industrial films]].<ref name=\"Tempest\"/><ref name=\"Feinberg\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b81581f07|title=Fearville (1997)|publisher=BFI|accessdate=1 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107104214/http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b81581f07|archive-date=7 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1995, he began work on the short film ''Larceny'', which was filmed over a weekend in black and white with limited equipment and a small cast and crew.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/interviews/interview.asp?IID=1052|title=Christopher Nolan: The Movies. The Memories|work=Empire|accessdate=12 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924064331/http://www.empireonline.com/interviews/interview.asp?IID=1052|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>Mooney, p. 5.</ref> Funded by Nolan and shot with the society's equipment, it appeared at the [[Cambridge Film Festival]] in 1996 and is considered one of UCL's best shorts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/~uczxflm/productions/archive/9495|title=UCLU Film Society, London|publisher=Ucl.ac.uk|accessdate=12 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120810232748/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/~uczxflm/productions/archive/9495/|archive-date=10 August 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> He filmed a third short, ''[[Doodlebug (film)|Doodlebug]]'' (1997), about a man chasing an insect around a flat with a shoe, only to discover when killing it that it is a miniature of himself.<ref>Mooney, p. 6.</ref><ref name=\"independent\">{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/christopher-nolan-director-dunkirk-short-first-film-doodlebug-student-ucl-london-a7675861.html |title=Christopher Nolan's student short film Doodlebug shows the Dunkirk director's humble beginnings |last=Hooton |first=Christopher |website=The Independent |date=10 April 2017 |accessdate=22 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722194629/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/christopher-nolan-director-dunkirk-short-first-film-doodlebug-student-ucl-london-a7675861.html |archive-date=22 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Nolan and Thomas made their first attempt at a feature in the mid-90s, an \"arty\" student angst film called ''Larry Mahoney'', which was scrapped and never released.<ref name=\"Mahoney\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nerdly.co.uk/2017/12/27/horror-on-sea-2018-interview-brian-barnes-discusses-the-redeeming/|title=Horror-On-Sea 2018 Interview: Brian Barnes discusses 'The Redeeming'|accessdate=5 April 2020|publisher=Nerdly|date=27 December 2017}}</ref> During this period in his career, Nolan had little or no success getting his projects off the ground; he later recalled the \"stack of rejection letters\" that greeted his early forays into making films, adding \"there's a very limited pool of finance in the UK. To be honest, it's a very clubby kind of place&nbsp;... Never had any support whatsoever from the British film industry.\"<ref name=\"AndrewPulver05\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2005/jun/15/features.features11|title=He's not a god \u2013 he's human|last=Pulver|first=Andrew|date=15 June 2005|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=23 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224110327/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2005/jun/15/features.features11|archive-date=24 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== 1998\u20132003: Breakthrough ===\nIn 1998, Nolan released his first feature, ''[[Following]]''. He wrote, directed, photographed and edited the film, which depicts an unemployed young writer ([[Jeremy Theobald]]) who trails strangers through London, hoping they will provide material for his first novel, but is drawn into a criminal underworld when he fails to keep his distance. The film was inspired by Nolan's experience of living in London and having his apartment burgled: \"There is an interesting connection between a stranger going through your possessions and the concept of following people at random through a crowd{{snd}}both take you beyond the boundaries of ordinary social relations\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wiki.ucl.ac.uk/display/SLAISFAlumni/Christopher+Nolan|title=The Man behind the Mask|publisher=UCL|date=8 December 2008|accessdate=12 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303180241/https://wiki.ucl.ac.uk/display/SLAISFAlumni/Christopher+Nolan|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Co-produced by Nolan with Emma Thomas and Jeremy Theobald,<ref name=\"nolandotnet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.christophernolan.net/following_making.php |title=The Making of Following |last=Duncker |first=Johannes |date=6 June 2002 |publisher=christophernolan.net |url-status=dead |accessdate=12 February 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513200348/http://www.christophernolan.net/following_making.php |archivedate=13 May 2008 |df= }}</ref> it was funded by him and made on a modest budget of \u00a33,000.<ref>[http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/interviews/39-christopher-nolan \"Interview with Christopher Nolan\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100505141213/http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/interviews/39-christopher-nolan |date=5 May 2010 }}. ''Metro''; retrieved 10 April 2011.</ref><ref name=\"Ressner\">{{cite web|last=Ressner|first=Jeffrey|title=The Traditionalist|url=http://www.dga.org/Craft/DGAQ/All-Articles/1202-Spring-2012/DGA-Interview-Christopher-Nolan.aspx|work=DGA Quarterly|accessdate=22 August 2012|date=Spring 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171125235745/https://www.dga.org/Craft/DGAQ/All-Articles/1202-Spring-2012/DGA-Interview-Christopher-Nolan.aspx|archive-date=25 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Most of the cast and crew were Nolan's friends, and shooting took place on weekends over the course of a year.<ref name=\"Ressner\"/>  To conserve [[film stock]], each scene in the film was rehearsed extensively to ensure that the first or second take could be used in the final edit.<ref>Mooney, p. 6.</ref><ref name=\"Tobias\">Tobias, S. [http://www.avclub.com/articles/christopher-nolan,13769 Interview: Christopher Nolan] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018024630/http://www.avclub.com/articles/christopher-nolan,13769/ |date=18 October 2013 }}, avclub.com, 5 June 2002; retrieved 13 September 2011.</ref> ''Following'' won several awards during its festival run<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmfestivalrotterdam.com/en/about/awards-and-jury/tiger-awards/previous-winners|title=Tiger Awards Competition: previous winners|publisher=International Film Festival Rotterdam|accessdate=12 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121013119/http://www.filmfestivalrotterdam.com/en/about/awards-and-jury/tiger-awards/previous-winners/|archive-date=21 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0154506/awards \"Awards for Following\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827194725/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0154506/awards |date=27 August 2017 }}. ''[[IMDb]]''; retrieved 25 June 2013.</ref> and was well received by critics; ''The New Yorker'' wrote that it \"echoed [[Alfred Hitchcock|Hitchcock]] classics\", but was \"leaner and meaner\".<ref name=\"Timberg\"/> [[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' was impressed with its \"spare look\" and agile hand-held camerawork, saying, \"As a result, the actors convincingly carry off the before, during and after modes that the film eventually, and artfully, weaves together.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Hero With No Memory Turns 'Memento' Into Unforgettable Trip|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C0CE1D71439F931A35757C0A96F958260|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=3 February 2017|first=Janet|last=Maslin|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204011800/http://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C0CE1D71439F931A35757C0A96F958260|archive-date=4 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On 11{{nbsp}}December 2012 it was released on DVD and [[Blu-ray]] as part of [[The Criterion Collection]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.criterion.com/films/28030-following|title=Criterion \u2013 Following|publisher=Criterion|accessdate=12 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107060854/https://www.criterion.com/films/28030-following|archive-date=7 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|align=left|width=246px|quote=[The] difference between shooting ''[[Following]]'' with a group of friends wearing our own clothes and my mum making sandwiches to spending $4&nbsp;million of somebody else's money on ''[[Memento (film)|Memento]]'' and having a crew of a hundred people is, to this day, by far the biggest leap I've ever made.|source= \u2014Nolan (in 2012) on the jump from his first film to his second.<ref name=\"Ressner\"/>}}\n\n''Following''{{'}}s success led to Nolan being afforded the opportunity to make ''[[Memento (film)|Memento]]'' (2000), which became his breakthrough film. The synopsis came from his brother Jonathan, who pitched the idea  to Nolan during a road trip about a man with [[anterograde amnesia]] who uses notes and tattoos to hunt for his wife's murderer. Jonathan worked the idea into a short story, \"[[Memento Mori (short story)|Memento Mori]]\" (2001), while Nolan developed it into a screenplay that told the story in reverse. Aaron Ryder, an executive for [[Newmarket Films]], said it was \"perhaps the most innovative script I had ever seen\".<ref>Mottram, p. 176.</ref> The film was optioned and given a budget of $4.5{{nbsp}}million, with [[Guy Pearce]] and [[Carrie-Anne Moss]] in the starring roles.<ref>Mottram, p. 177.</ref>  ''Memento'' premiered at the [[Venice International Film Festival]] in September 2000 to critical acclaim.<ref>Mottram, p. 62\u201364.</ref> [[Joe Morgenstern]] of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' wrote in his review, \"I can't remember when a movie has seemed so clever, strangely affecting and slyly funny at the very same time.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Hero With No Memory Turns 'Memento' Into Unforgettable Trip|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB9846986937127287|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=21 January 2014|first=Joe|last=Morgenstern|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326002730/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB9846986937127287|archive-date=26 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Basil Smith, in the book ''The Philosophy of Neo-Noir'', draws a comparison with [[John Locke]]'s ''[[An Essay Concerning Human Understanding]]'', which argues that conscious memories constitute our identities, a theme that Nolan explores in the film.<ref>Conard (2007) p.35.</ref> The film was a box-office success<ref>{{cite web|title=Memento|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=memento.htm|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6I5CaqAw2?url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=memento.htm|archive-date=13 July 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> and received a number of accolades, including [[Academy Award for Best Writing (Original Screenplay)|Academy Award]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay|Golden Globe Award]] nominations for its screenplay, [[Independent Spirit Award]]s for [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Director|Best Director]] and [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]], and a [[Directors Guild of America]] (DGA) Award nomination.<ref name=\"nytimesawards\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/240025/Christopher-Nolan/awards|title=Christopher Nolan awards|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=26 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024065520/http://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/240025/Christopher-Nolan/awards|archive-date=24 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp;jsessionid=85089250F8C40E42B36D0F921E3F7860?curTime=1295947194337 Session Timeout \u2013 Academy Awards\u00ae Database] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105194451/http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp%3Bjsessionid%3D85089250F8C40E42B36D0F921E3F7860?curTime=1295947194337 |date=5 November 2013 }} (29 January 2010); retrieved 26 November 2011.</ref> ''Memento'' was considered by numerous critics to be one of the best films of the [[2000s in film|2000s]].<ref name=\"Metadecade\">{{cite web|title=Film Critics Pick the Best Movies of the Decade|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critics-pick-the-best-movies-of-the-decade|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=3 January 2010|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6pBuFqa6Q?url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critics-pick-the-best-movies-of-the-decade|archive-date=24 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2017, the film was selected by the [[Library of Congress]] for preservation in the United States [[National Film Registry]], being deemed \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/the-goonies-titanic-field-of-dreams-die-hard-national-film-registry-1202638298/ |title='Titanic,' 'The Goonies,' 'Field of Dreams,' 'Memento' Added to National Film Registry |magazine=Variety |date=13 December 2017 |accessdate=13 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213101146/http://variety.com/2017/film/news/the-goonies-titanic-field-of-dreams-die-hard-national-film-registry-1202638298/ |archive-date=13 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n[[File:Steven Soderbergh 66\u00e8me Festival de Venise (Mostra).jpg|thumb|right|220x220px| Oscar-winning film director [[Steven Soderbergh]] ''(pictured)'' supported Nolan in his transition to studio filmmaking.]]\n\nImpressed by his work on ''Memento'', [[Steven Soderbergh]] recruited Nolan to direct the [[psychological thriller]] ''[[Insomnia (2002 film)|Insomnia]]'' (2002), starring Academy Award winners [[Al Pacino]], [[Robin Williams]], and [[Hilary Swank]].<ref name=\"insomnia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/interview/cnolan|title='Memento' recognition landed Christopher Nolan in the director's chair for big-budget 'Insomnia'|accessdate=5 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618002152/http://www.contactmusic.com/interview/cnolan|archive-date=18 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Warner Bros.]] initially wanted a more seasoned director, but Soderbergh and his [[Section Eight Productions]] fought for Nolan, as well as his choice of cinematographer ([[Wally Pfister]]) and editor ([[Dody Dorn]]).<ref>deWaard, Tait (2013), p. 49.</ref> With a $46{{nbsp}}million budget, it was described as \"a much more conventional Hollywood film than anything [Nolan had] done before\".<ref name=\"insomnia\"/> A remake of the 1997 [[Insomnia (1997 film)|Norwegian film of the same name]], ''Insomnia'' is about two Los Angeles detectives sent to a northern Alaskan town to investigate the murder of a local teenager. It received positive reviews from critics and performed well at the box office, earning $113{{nbsp}}million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Insomnia|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1114154-insomnia/|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100802163407/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1114154-insomnia/|archive-date=2 August 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Insomnia|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=insomnia.htm|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808004401/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=insomnia.htm|archive-date=8 August 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> Film critic [[Roger Ebert]] praised the film for introducing new perspectives and ideas on the issues of morality and guilt, stating that \"Unlike most remakes, the Nolan ''Insomnia'' is not a pale retread, but a re-examination of the material, like a new production of a good play.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ebert|first=Roger|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/insomnia-2002|title=Insomnia review|journal=Rogerebert.com|date=24 May 2002|accessdate=18 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213010524/http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/insomnia-2002|archive-date=13 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Erik Skjoldbj\u00e6rg]], the director of the original film, was satisfied with Nolan's version, calling it a \"well crafted, smart film ... with a really good director handling it\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Paul Weedon|title=Erik Skjoldb\u00e6rg on 'Pioneer'|url=http://grolschfilmworks.com/ca/features/erik-skjoldbjaerg-on-pioneer|work=Grolsch Filmworks|accessdate=30 October 2013}}</ref> [[Richard Schickel]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' deemed ''Insomnia'' a \"worthy successor\" to ''Memento'', and \"a triumph of atmosphere over a none-too-mysterious mystery\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Schickel|first=Richard|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,238623,00.html|title=Sleepless in Alaska|journal=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=19 May 2002|accessdate=16 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113065714/http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,238623,00.html|archive-date=13 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter ''Insomnia'', Nolan planned a [[Howard Hughes]] biographical film starring [[Jim Carrey]]. He wrote a screenplay, which he said was \"the best script I've ever written\", but when he learned that [[Martin Scorsese]] was making a Hughes biopic (2004's ''[[The Aviator (2004 film)|The Aviator]]''), he reluctantly tabled his script and moved on to other projects.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2014/11/christopher-nolan-talks-howard-hughes-project-interstellar-more-in-interviews-plus-featurettes-new-pics-more-270480/|title=Christopher Nolan Talks Howard Hughes Project, 'Interstellar' & More In Interviews, Plus Featurettes, New Pics & More|work=Indiewire|date=10 November 2014|accessdate=7 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308045123/http://www.indiewire.com/2014/11/christopher-nolan-talks-howard-hughes-project-interstellar-more-in-interviews-plus-featurettes-new-pics-more-270480/|archive-date=8 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/christopher-nolan-says-his-howard-hughes-film-is-dead-but-hed-still-like-to-do-a-bond-film-at-some-point-20120604|title=Christopher Nolan Says His Howard Hughes Film Is Dead, But He'd Still Like To Do A Bond Film at Some Point|work=Indiewire|accessdate=9 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527153400/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/christopher-nolan-says-his-howard-hughes-film-is-dead-but-hed-still-like-to-do-a-bond-film-at-some-point-20120604|archive-date=27 May 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> After turning down an offer to direct the historical epic ''[[Troy (film)|Troy]]'' (2004),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/trivia-when-christopher-nolan-first-came-to-warner-bros-he-was-offered-troy-to-direct-20130621|title=Trivia: When Christopher Nolan First Came To Warner Bros., He Was Offered 'Troy' To Direct|publisher=The Playlist|accessdate=12 August 2014|first=Kevin|last=Jagernauth|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140813021758/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/trivia-when-christopher-nolan-first-came-to-warner-bros-he-was-offered-troy-to-direct-20130621|archive-date=13 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Nolan worked on adapting [[Ruth Rendell]]'s crime novel ''[[The Keys to the Street]]'' into a screenplay that he planned to direct for [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]], but eventually left the project, citing the similarities to his previous films.<ref name=\"blogspot\">[http://theplaylist.net/gemma-arterton-to-star-in-christopher-20100906/ Gemma Arterton to star in Christopher Nolan-penned thriller 'The Keys to the Street', Meeting with Ridley Scott for 'Alien' prequels'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160925015835/http://theplaylist.net/gemma-arterton-to-star-in-christopher-20100906/ |date=25 September 2016 }} ''The Playlist'', 9 June 2011.</ref> Nolan was also adapting a film version of ''[[The Prisoner]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Child|first=Ben|title=Nolan signs to take Inception from script to screen|work=The Guardian|date=12 February 2009|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/feb/12/christopher-nolan-inception|location=London}}</ref> but later dropped out of the project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/batman/news/nolan-drops-the-prisoner_1113280 |title=Nolan Drops The Prisoner |publisher=Contact Music |date = 13 August 2009|accessdate=5 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\n=== 2003\u20132013: Hollywood success ===\nIn early 2003, Nolan approached Warner Bros. with the idea of making a new [[Batman]] film.<ref name=\"bb-latimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2005-may-08-ca-batman8-story.html|title=Rescuing Batman|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref> Fascinated by the character and story, he wanted to make a film grounded in a \"relatable\" world more reminiscent of a classical drama than a comic-book fantasy.<ref name=\"bb\">{{cite web|url=http://filmcomment.com/article/cinematic-faith-christopher-nolan-scott-foundas|title=Christopher Nolan looks back over the Dark Knight trilogy in this extended interview|publisher=Filmcomment|accessdate=27 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820002832/https://www.filmcomment.com/article/cinematic-faith-christopher-nolan-scott-foundas/|archive-date=20 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Filming took place in 2004, and Nolan relied heavily on traditional [[stunt]]s and [[miniature effect]]s, with [[computer-generated imagery]] being used in a minimal capacity.<ref name=\"bb-latimes\"/> ''[[Batman Begins]]'', the biggest project Nolan had undertaken to that point,<ref name=\"bb\"/> premiered in June 2005 to critical acclaim and commercial success.<ref>{{cite web|title=Insomnia|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/batman_begins/|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115152611/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/batman_begins/|archive-date=15 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Starring [[Christian Bale]] in the [[Bruce Wayne (The Dark Knight trilogy)|title role]], along with [[Michael Caine]], [[Gary Oldman]], [[Morgan Freeman]], and [[Liam Neeson]], the film revived the franchise, heralding a trend towards darker films that [[reboot (fiction)|rebooted]] (or retold) backstories.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/06/the-complicated-legacy-of-batman-begins/395477/|title=The Complicated Legacy of Batman Begins|magazine=The Atlantic|accessdate=10 June 2015|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611041139/http://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/06/the-complicated-legacy-of-batman-begins/395477/|archive-date=11 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Shawn Adler|title=He-Man' Movie Will Go Realistic: 'We're Not Talking About Putting Nipples On The Trapjaw Suit|url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2008/08/14/he-man-movie-will-go-realistic-were-not-talking-about-putting-nipples-on-the-trapjaw-suit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080902155525/http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2008/08/14/he-man-movie-will-go-realistic-were-not-talking-about-putting-nipples-on-the-trapjaw-suit|archivedate=2 September 2008|date=14 August 2008|accessdate=8 April 2013}}</ref> Praised for its psychological depth and contemporary relevance,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/sites/bfi.org.uk/files/downloads/bfi-press-release-christopher-nolan-season-at-bfi-southbank-in-july-2012-06-06.pdf|title=Christopher Nolan Season at BFI Southbank in July 2012|publisher=British Film Institute|accessdate=31 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304093423/http://www.bfi.org.uk/sites/bfi.org.uk/files/downloads/bfi-press-release-christopher-nolan-season-at-bfi-southbank-in-july-2012-06-06.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Kyle Smith]] of ''[[The New York Post]]'' called it \"a wake-up call to the people who keep giving us cute capers about men in tights. It wipes the smirk off the face of the superhero movie.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Review: Batman Begins|url=http://kylesmithonline.com/?p=349|newspaper=The New York Post|accessdate=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201172556/http://kylesmithonline.com/?p=349|archive-date=1 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''Batman Begins'' was the eighth-highest-grossing film of 2005 in the United States and the year's ninth-highest-grossing film worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=batmanbegins.htm|title=Batman Begins (2005)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=19 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724205014/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=batmanbegins.htm|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography]] and three [[BAFTA]] awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0372784/awards|title=Batman Begins|publisher=IMDb|access-date=30 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180409044611/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0372784/awards|archive-date=9 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/awards-database.html?sq=batman+begins|title=Batman Begins|publisher=BAFTA-Awards Database|accessdate=23 October 2012}}</ref> On the film's 10th anniversary, ''[[Forbes]]'' published an article describing its lasting influence: \"Reboot became part of our modern vocabulary, and superhero origin stories became increasingly en{{nbsp}}vogue for the genre. The phrase \"dark and gritty\" likewise joined the cinematic lexicon, influencing our perception of different approaches to storytelling not only in the comic book film genre but in all sorts of other genres as well.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/markhughes/2015/07/30/exclusive-christopher-nolan-talks-batman-begins-10th-anniversary/#797eaf2329a0|title=Exclusive: Christopher Nolan Talks 'Batman Begins' 10th Anniversary|magazine=Forbes|accessdate=28 February 2016|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003225206/https://www.forbes.com/sites/markhughes/2015/07/30/exclusive-christopher-nolan-talks-batman-begins-10th-anniversary/#797eaf2329a0|archive-date=3 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBefore returning to the Batman franchise for a sequel, Nolan directed, co-wrote, and produced ''[[The Prestige (film)|The Prestige]]'' (2006), an adaptation of the [[Christopher Priest (novelist)|Christopher Priest]] [[The Prestige|novel]] about two rival 19th-century magicians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christopher-priest.co.uk/books/the-prestige/interview-abou-the-prestige|title=Interview about The Prestige|publisher=Christopher-priest.co.uk|accessdate=15 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120728180958/http://www.christopher-priest.co.uk/books/the-prestige/interview-abou-the-prestige/|archive-date=28 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The screenplay was the result of an intermittent, five-year collaboration between him and his brother Jonathan, who had begun writing it already in 2001.<ref>{{cite podcast|url=http://cdn2.libsyn.com/creativescreenwritingmag/ThePrestigeQandA.mp3?nvb=20090804012227&nva=20090805013227&t=0177c850fb5969f409276|title=The Prestige Q&A: Interview with Jonathan Nolan|website=Creative Screenwriting Magazine Podcast|publisher=Creative Screenwriting|host=Jeff Goldsmith|date=28 October 2006|accessdate=24 July 2007}}</ref> Nolan initially intended to make the film as early as 2003, but had postponed the project after agreeing to make ''Batman Begins''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2003/film/news/nolan-wants-prestige-1117884751|title=Nolan wants 'Prestige'|work=Variety|accessdate=9 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005094256/http://variety.com/2003/film/news/nolan-wants-prestige-1117884751/|archive-date=5 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Starring [[Hugh Jackman]] and Christian Bale in the lead roles, ''The Prestige'' received critical acclaim and earned over $109{{nbsp}}million worldwide.<ref>[http://www.bo/Volumes/Untitled/PSP/Photo/Photo10/xofficemojo.com/movies/?id=prestige.htm \"The Prestige (2006)\"], ''[[Box Office Mojo]]''; retrieved 10 April 2011.</ref><ref>Murray, Noel. (3 December 2009) [http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-best-films-of-the-00s,35931 The best films of the '00s|Best of the Decade] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527155440/http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-best-films-of-the-00s,35931/ |date=27 May 2013 }}. The A.V. Club; retrieved 26 January 2011.</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] described it as \"quite a movie{{snd}}atmospheric, obsessive, almost satanic\",<ref>{{cite web|title=The Prestige|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-prestige-2007|publisher=Roger Ebert|accessdate=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203004736/http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-prestige-2007|archive-date=3 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Kenneth Turan]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called it an \"ambitious, unnerving melodrama\".<ref>{{cite news|title=They've got something up their sleeves|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/oct/20/entertainment/et-prestige20|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=23 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814051743/http://articles.latimes.com/2006/oct/20/entertainment/et-prestige20|archive-date=14 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Philip French]] wrote in his review for ''[[The Guardian]]'': \"In addition to the intellectual or philosophical excitement it engenders, ''The Prestige'' is gripping, suspenseful, mysterious, moving and often darkly funny.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=The Prestige|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2006/nov/12/drama.sciencefictionandfantasy|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=27 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221084521/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2006/nov/12/drama.sciencefictionandfantasy|archive-date=21 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Prestige'' also received Academy Award nominations for [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]] and [[Academy Award for Best Art Direction|Best Art Direction]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2007/feb/26/awardsandprizes.oscars2007|title=The Prestige|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815183501/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2007/feb/26/awardsandprizes.oscars2007|archive-date=15 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n | align     = left\n | direction = vertical\n | width     =\n | image1    = The Dark Knight European Premier - Leicester square2.jpg\n | width1    = 220\n | caption1  = Nolan (left) with the cast and crew of ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'' at the 2008 European premiere in London.\n | image2    = InceptionCastPremiereJuly10.jpg\n | width2    = 220\n | caption2  = The cast of ''[[Inception]]'' at the premiere in July 2010.\n}}\n\nIn 2006, Nolan announced that the follow-up to ''Batman Begins'' would be called ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.darkhorizons.com/news06/060731n.php|title=It's Official: \"Batman 2\" Gets A Title|author=Garth Franklin|date=31 July 2006|publisher=DarkHorizons|accessdate=9 March 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070125200104/http://www.darkhorizons.com/news06/060731n.php|archive-date=25 January 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> Approaching the sequel, Nolan wanted to expand on the [[Film noir|noirish]] quality of the first film by broadening the canvas and taking on \"the dynamic of a story of the city, a large crime story{{nbsp}}... where you're looking at the police, the justice system, the vigilante, the poor people, the rich people, the criminals\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.empireonline.com/features/dark-knight|title=The Dark Knight: The Original Feature|magazine=Empire|accessdate=23 December 2013|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120713133553/http://www.empireonline.com/features/dark-knight|archive-date=13 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Released in July 2008 to great critical acclaim, ''The Dark Knight'' has been cited as one of the best films of the 2000s and one of the [[List of films considered the best#Comic book/superhero|best superhero films ever made]].<ref name=\"Metadecade\"/><ref name=\"Paste\">{{cite web|title=The 50 Best Movies of the Decade (2000\u20132009)|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2009/11/50-best-movies-of-the-decade-2000-2009.html?p=4|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|accessdate=14 December 2011|date=3 November 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017223108/https://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2009/11/50-best-movies-of-the-decade-2000-2009.html?p=4|archive-date=17 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Empiredecade\">{{cite web|title=Review of the Decade \u2013 Year-By-Year: Empire's Films Of The Decade|url=http://www.empireonline.com/features/reviewofthedecade/films-of-the-decade/9.asp|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|accessdate=4 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924063908/http://www.empireonline.com/features/reviewofthedecade/films-of-the-decade/9.asp|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>  [[Manohla Dargis]] of ''The New York Times'' found the film to be of higher artistic merit than many Hollywood blockbusters: \"Pitched at the divide between art and industry, poetry and entertainment, it goes darker and deeper than any Hollywood movie of its comic-book kind.\"<ref name=\"Dargis\">{{cite news|author=Manohla Dargis|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/18/movies/18knig.html|title=The Dark Knight-Showdown in Gotham Town|work=The New York Times|date=18 July 2008|accessdate=21 January 2014|author-link=Manohla Dargis|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810124137/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/18/movies/18knig.html|archive-date=10 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Ebert expressed a similar point of view, describing it as a \"haunted film that leaps beyond its origins and becomes an engrossing tragedy.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080716/REVIEWS/55996637|title=The Dark Knight|author=Roger Ebert|date=16 July 2008|newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=21 January 2014|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/64yviafso?url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?aid=%2F20080716%2Freviews%2F55996637|archive-date=26 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Dark Knight'' set a number of box-office records during its theatrical run,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/28/movies/28box.html|title=Dark Knight Wins Again at Box Office|author=Brooks Barnes|date=28 July 2008|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=21 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090411150617/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/28/movies/28box.html|archive-date=11 April 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> earning $534,858,444 in North America and $469,700,000 abroad, for a worldwide total of $1,004,558,444.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=darkknight.htm|title=The Dark Knight (2008)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=17 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221104243/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=darkknight.htm|archive-date=21 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[81st Academy Awards]], the film was nominated for eight Oscars, winning two: the [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing]] and a posthumous [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for [[Heath Ledger]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/oscars/7842438.stm \"The Oscars 2009\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221215438/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/oscars/7842438.stm |date=21 February 2009 }}. BBC News.</ref> Nolan received many [[List of accolades received by The Dark Knight|awards and nominations]] for his work on the film.<ref name=\"nytimesawards\"/> In 2018, [[Bilge Ebiri]] of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' wrote, \"Its politics have been discussed ad infinitum. Its stylistic influence has become ubiquitous, then pass\u00e9, then somehow aspirational ... ''The Dark Knight'' is perhaps the most powerful exploration of guilt the modern American blockbuster has given us.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2018/07/18/10-years-later-the-dark-knight-and-its-vision-of-guilt-still-resonate/|title=Ten Years Later, \"The Dark Knight\" and Its Vision of Guilt Still Resonate|accessdate=23 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823174256/https://www.villagevoice.com/2018/07/18/10-years-later-the-dark-knight-and-its-vision-of-guilt-still-resonate/|archive-date=23 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter ''The Dark Knight''{{'}}s success, Warner Bros. signed Nolan to direct ''[[Inception]]'' (2010). Nolan also wrote and co-produced the film, described as \"a contemporary sci-fi actioner set within the architecture of the mind\".<ref name=\"Tackles\">{{cite journal|last=Fleming|first=Michael|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117999988.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|title=Nolan tackles 'Inception' for WB|journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=11 February 2009|accessdate=2 April 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414183155/http://variety.com/article/VR1117999988.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|archive-date=14 April 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> Starring a large ensemble cast led by [[Leonardo DiCaprio]], the film became a critical and commercial success upon its release in July 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://collider.com/inception-oscar-featurette|title=Warner Bros. Keeping INCEPTION in Oscar-voters' Minds with \"New\" Behind-the-Scenes Featurette|year=2010|work=Collider.com|accessdate=15 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822054454/http://collider.com/inception-oscar-featurette/|archive-date=22 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' awarded the film a perfect score of \"A+\" and called it \"one of the best movies of the [21st] century\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richardroeper.com/reviews/inception.aspx|title=''Inception'' Review|last=Roeper|first=Richard|authorlink=Richard Roeper|work=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=21 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100718103707/http://www.richardroeper.com/reviews/inception.aspx|archive-date=18 July 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mark Kermode]] named it the best film of 2010, stating \"''Inception'' is proof that people are not stupid, that cinema is not trash, and that it is possible for blockbusters and art to be the same thing.\"<ref name=\"Kermode\">{{cite video|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/markkermode/2010/12/my_top_five_films_of_the_year.html|accessdate=21 January 2014|date=24 December 2010|first=Mark|last=Kermode|authorlink=Mark Kermode|title=Kermode Uncut: My Top Five Films of the Year|publisher=BBC|time=5:05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130106172155/http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/markkermode/2010/12/my_top_five_films_of_the_year.html|archive-date=6 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Schuker\">{{cite news|last=Schuker|first=Lauren|title=Studios Root for 'Inception'|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703722804575369390235794102|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=10 January 2013|date=16 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150514092432/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703722804575369390235794102|archive-date=14 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The film ended up grossing over $820{{nbsp}}million worldwide<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=inception.htm|title=Inception (2010)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=2 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030220255/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=inception.htm|archive-date=30 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> and was nominated for eight Academy Awards, including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] and [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]; it won the award for [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound|Best Sound Mixing]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Best Sound Editing]] and [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]].<ref name=\"Academy Awards 2010 (83rd)\">{{cite web |url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2011/I?qt-honorees=1#block-quicktabs-honorees |title=2011 Academy Awards Nominations and Winners |access-date=26 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802040831/http://oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2011/I?qt-honorees=1#block-quicktabs-honorees |archive-date=2 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Nolan was also nominated for [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]] and Golden Globe awards, [[List of accolades received by Inception|among other accolades]].<ref name=\"nytimesawards\"/>\n\nIn 2012, Nolan directed his third and final Batman film, ''[[The Dark Knight Rises]]'', with Christian Bale reprising the title role. Although Nolan was initially hesitant about returning to the series, he agreed to come back after developing a story with his brother and [[David S. Goyer]] that he felt would end the series on a high note.<ref name=\"Bettinger\">{{cite news|first=Brendan|last=Bettinger|title=Christopher Nolan Speaks! Updates on Dark Knight Sequel and Superman Man of Steel|website=Collider.com|date=10 March 2010|url=http://www.collider.com/2010/03/10/christopher-nolan-speaks-updates-on-dark-knight-sequel-and-superman-man-of-steel|accessdate=10 March 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100313061209/http://www.collider.com/2010/03/10/christopher-nolan-speaks-updates-on-dark-knight-sequel-and-superman-man-of-steel/|archive-date=13 March 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/2010/10/27/christopher-nolan-reveals-title-of-third-batman-film-and-that-it-wont-be-the-riddler|title=Christopher Nolan reveals title of third Batman film and that 'it won't be the Riddler'|last=Boucher|first=Geoff|date=27 October 2010|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=27 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101029042813/http://herocomplex.latimes.com/2010/10/27/christopher-nolan-reveals-title-of-third-batman-film-and-that-it-wont-be-the-riddler/|archive-date=29 October 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> The film was released in July 2012 to positive reviews; Andrew O'Hehir of ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'' called it \"arguably the biggest, darkest, most thrilling and disturbing and utterly balls-out spectacle ever created for the screen\", further describing the work as \"auteurist spectacle on a scale never before possible and never before attempted\".<ref name=\"Hehir\">{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/2012/07/18/the_dark_knight_rises_christopher_nolans_evil_masterpiece|title=\"The Dark Knight Rises\": Christopher Nolan's evil masterpiece|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|date=18 July 2012|accessdate=4 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602051223/http://www.salon.com/2012/07/18/the_dark_knight_rises_christopher_nolans_evil_masterpiece/|archive-date=2 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/filmandtv/news/the-dark-knight-rises-receives-overwhelmingly-positive/275513|title='The Dark Knight Rises' receives overwhelmingly positive early reviews|author=NME.com|work=NME.com}}</ref> [[Christy Lemire]] of ''[[The Associated Press]]'' wrote in her review that Nolan concluded his trilogy in a \"typically spectacular, ambitious fashion\", but disliked the \"overloaded\" story and excessive grimness.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/16/batman-review-dark-knight-rises-letdown_n_1677247.html|title=Batman Review: Is 'The Dark Knight Rises' An Epic Letdown?|last=Lemire|first=Christy|date=16 July 2012|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=16 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317011538/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/16/batman-review-dark-knight-rises-letdown_n_1677247.html|archive-date=17 March 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Like its predecessor, the film was a box office success, becoming the thirteenth film to reach the billion-dollar mark.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-milestone-dark-knight-rises-warner-bros-christopher-nolan-christian-bale-367476|title=Box Office Milestone: 'Dark Knight Rises' Crosses $1 Billion Worldwide|accessdate=17 November 2012|work=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|date=2 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109092114/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-milestone-dark-knight-rises-warner-bros-christopher-nolan-christian-bale-367476|archive-date=9 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> During a midnight showing of the film at the Century{{nbsp}}16 cinema in [[Aurora, Colorado]], [[2012 Aurora, Colorado shooting|a gunman opened fire inside the theatre]], killing 12 people and injuring 58 others.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_21124893/12-shot-dead-58-wounded-aurora-movie-theater|title=12 shot dead, 58 wounded in Aurora movie theater during Batman premier|accessdate=13 January 2012|work=Denver Post|first=Jennifer|last=Brown|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722234007/http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_21124893/12-shot-dead-58-wounded-aurora-movie-theater|archive-date=22 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Nolan released a statement to the press expressing his condolences for the victims of what he described as a senseless tragedy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2012/07/20/christopher-nolan-dark-knight-rises-shooting-statement|title=Christopher Nolan on Theater Shooting: 'I Would Like to Express Our Profound Sorrow'|accessdate=13 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120721130638/http://insidemovies.ew.com/2012/07/20/christopher-nolan-dark-knight-rises-shooting-statement/|archive-date=21 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Christopher Nolan, London, 2013 (crop).jpg|thumb|upright|Nolan at the 2013 premiere of ''[[Man of Steel (film)|Man of Steel]]'' in London.]]\n\nDuring story discussions for ''The Dark Knight Rises'' in 2010, Goyer told Nolan of his idea to present [[Superman]] in a modern context.<ref name=\"GoyStory\">{{cite news|url=http://www.superherohype.com/news/articles/102090-christopher-nolan-on-batman-and-superman|title=Christopher Nolan on Batman and Superman|publisher=[[Superhero Hype!]]|date=4 June 2010|accessdate=2 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110105182212/http://www.superherohype.com/news/articles/102090-christopher-nolan-on-batman-and-superman|archive-date=5 January 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Impressed with Goyer's [[First contact (science fiction)|first contact]] concept, Nolan pitched the idea for ''[[Man of Steel (film)|Man of Steel]]'' (2013) to Warner Bros, who hired Nolan to produce and [[Zack Snyder]] to direct.<ref>{{cite news|title=Alien, Yet Familiar|work=The New York Times|date=22 May 2013|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/26/movies/man-of-steel-aims-to-make-superman-relevant-again.html|accessdate=22 May 2013|first=Dave|last=Itzkoff|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523184437/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/26/movies/man-of-steel-aims-to-make-superman-relevant-again.html|archive-date=23 May 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"GoyStory\"/> Starring [[Henry Cavill]], [[Amy Adams]], [[Kevin Costner]], [[Russell Crowe]], and [[Michael Shannon]], ''Man of Steel'' grossed more than $660{{nbsp}}million at the worldwide box office, but received a divided critical reaction.<ref>{{cite web|title=Man of Steel Reviews \u2013 Metacritic|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/man-of-steel|work=Metacritic|accessdate=12 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140706192545/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/man-of-steel|archive-date=6 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite the mixed reviews, Nolan was thoroughly impressed by Snyder's work, saying that the director \"knocked it out of the park\", and that he believed the film would have the same potential to excite audiences as when he himself saw the [[Superman (1978 film)|Christopher Reeve version]] in 1978.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/videos/christopher-nolan-talks-producing-man-of-steel-39948/|title=Christopher Nolan talks producing Man of Steel \u2013 Access Hollywood|accessdate=22 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822174604/http://www.accesshollywood.com/videos/christopher-nolan-talks-producing-man-of-steel-39948/|archive-date=22 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== 2014\u2013present: Established blockbuster auteur ===\n[[File:Jonathan Nolan by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Nolan's younger brother, [[Jonathan Nolan|Jonathan]], co-wrote the screenplay for ''Interstellar''.]]\n\nNolan next directed, wrote, and produced the science-fiction film ''[[Interstellar (film)|Interstellar]]'' (2014). The first drafts of the script were written by Jonathan Nolan, and it was originally to be directed by [[Steven Spielberg]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/09/christopher-nolan-interstellar_n_2444314.html|title=Christopher Nolan's 'Interstellar': 'Dark Knight Rises' Director Lines Up Next Project|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=13 January 2013|date=9 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130113030432/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/09/christopher-nolan-interstellar_n_2444314.html|archive-date=13 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Based on the scientific theories of [[theoretical physicist]] [[Kip Thorne]], the film follows a group of [[astronaut]]s who travel through a [[wormhole]] in search of a new home for humanity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/christopher-nolans-merging-an-original-idea-with-jonah-nolans-old-screenplay-for-interstellar-20130110|title=Christopher Nolan's Merging An Original Idea With Jonah Nolan's Old Screenplay For 'Interstellar'|publisher=The Playlist|author=Jagernauth, Kevin|date=10 January 2013|accessdate=13 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112010928/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/christopher-nolans-merging-an-original-idea-with-jonah-nolans-old-screenplay-for-interstellar-20130110|archive-date=12 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''Interstellar'' starred [[Matthew McConaughey]], [[Anne Hathaway]], [[Jessica Chastain]], [[Bill Irwin]], [[Michael Caine]], and [[Ellen Burstyn]], and was Nolan's first collaboration with cinematographer [[Hoyte van Hoytema]]. ''Interstellar'' was released in November 2014 to largely positive reviews and strong box office results, grossing over $670{{nbsp}}million worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/03/christopher-nolans-interstellar-to-be-paramount-warner-bros-co-production-and-joint-distribution/ |title=Christopher Nolan's 'Interstellar' To Be Paramount\u2013Warner Bros Co-Production And Joint Distribution |access-date=8 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140624041858/http://www.deadline.com/2013/03/christopher-nolans-interstellar-to-be-paramount-warner-bros-co-production-and-joint-distribution/ |archive-date=24 June 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/interstellar|title=Interstellar Reviews|work=metacritic.com|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=13 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804225550/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/interstellar|archive-date=4 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=interstellar.htm|title=Interstellar (2014)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=12 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316082328/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=interstellar.htm|archive-date=16 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> [[A. O. Scott]] wrote, in his review for ''The New York Times'', \"''Interstellar'', full of visual dazzle, thematic ambition{{nbsp}}... is a sweeping, futuristic adventure driven by grief, dread and regret.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/05/movies/interstellar-christopher-nolans-search-for-a-new-planet.html | title=Off to the Stars, With Grief, Dread and Regret | newspaper=The New York Times | accessdate=16 July 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828121417/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/05/movies/interstellar-christopher-nolans-search-for-a-new-planet.html | archive-date=28 August 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Documentary filmmaker [[Toni Myers]] said of the film, \"I loved it because it tackled the most difficult part of human exploration, which is that it's a multi-generational journey. It was a real work of art.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cnet.com/news/space-station-film-school-how-astronauts-shot-this-glorious-imax-documentary/ | title=Space station film school: How astronauts shot this glorious IMAX movie | website=CNET | accessdate=27 January 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610145325/http://www.cnet.com/news/space-station-film-school-how-astronauts-shot-this-glorious-imax-documentary/ | archive-date=10 June 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''Interstellar'' was particularly praised for its scientific accuracy, which led to the publication of two [[scientific papers]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=James|first=Oliver|last2=Tunzelmann|first2=Eug\u00e9nie von|last3=Franklin|first3=Paul|last4=Thorne|first4=Kip S.|date=February 2015|title=Gravitational lensing by spinning black holes in astrophysics, and in the movieInterstellar|journal=Classical and Quantum Gravity|language=en|volume=32|issue=6|pages=065001|doi=10.1088/0264-9381/32/6/065001|issn=0264-9381|arxiv=1502.03808}}</ref> and the [[American Journal of Physics]] calling for it to be shown in school science lessons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-33173197|title=Interstellar 'should be shown in school lessons'|work=BBC|accessdate=23 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150624075813/http://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-33173197|archive-date=24 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Visualizing Interstellar's Wormhole|journal = American Journal of Physics|volume = 83|issue = 6|pages = 486\u2013499|last=James|first=Oliver|last2=von Tunzelmann|first2=Eug\u00e9nie|doi=10.1119/1.4916949|last3=Franklin|first3=Paul|last4=Thorne|first4=Kip S.|year = 2015|bibcode = 2015AmJPh..83..486J|arxiv = 1502.03809}}</ref> It was named one of the best films of the year by The [[American Film Institute]] (AFI).<ref>{{cite news|last=Kilday|first=Gregg|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/afi-list-top-10-films-754933|title=AFI List of Top 10 Films Expands to Include 11|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=9 December 2014|accessdate=22 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150112100116/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/afi-list-top-10-films-754933|archive-date=12 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> At the [[87th Academy Awards]], the film won [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]] and received four other nominations{{snd}}[[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound Mixing]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Best Sound Editing]] and [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/3668006/oscars-2015-nominations/|title=Oscars 2015: See the Full List of Nominees|magazine=Time|date=15 January 2015|accessdate=16 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115180510/http://time.com/3668006/oscars-2015-nominations/|archive-date=15 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2014, Nolan and Emma Thomas also served as [[executive producer]]s on ''[[Transcendence (2014 film)|Transcendence]]'' (2014), the directorial debut of Nolan's longtime cinematographer Wally Pfister.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/christopher-nolan-wally-pfister-dark-knight-rises-337015|title=Christopher Nolan to Exec Produce Wally Pfister's Directorial Debut|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=23 October 2012|first=Borys|last=Kit|date=13 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120922192453/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/christopher-nolan-wally-pfister-dark-knight-rises-337015|archive-date=22 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The film was released to mostly unfavorable reviews and disappointing box office results.<ref name=\"Transcendence14\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/apr/18/transcendence-johnny-depp-2014s-most-unexpected-turkey-film|title=The Johnny Depp Problem|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=18 April 2014|accessdate=3 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703162416/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/apr/18/transcendence-johnny-depp-2014s-most-unexpected-turkey-film|archive-date=3 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the mid-2010s, Nolan took part in several ventures for film preservation and distribution of the films of lesser-known filmmakers. His production company, Syncopy, formed a joint venture with [[Zeitgeist Films]] to release [[Blu-ray]] editions of Zeitgeist's prestige titles.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/christopher-nolans-syncopy-teaming-with-zeitgeist-on-blu-ray-releases-exclusive-1201437195/|title=Christopher Nolan's Syncopy Teaming With Zeitgeist on Blu-ray Releases (EXCLUSIVE)|magazine=Variety|author=McNary, Dave|date=19 February 2015|accessdate=23 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224023820/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/christopher-nolans-syncopy-teaming-with-zeitgeist-on-blu-ray-releases-exclusive-1201437195/|archive-date=24 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> As part of the Blu-ray release of the animation films of the [[Brothers Quay]], Nolan directed the documentary short ''[[Quay (film)|Quay]]'' (2015). He also initiated a theatrical tour, showcasing the Quays' ''[[In Absentia (film)|In Absentia]]'', ''The Comb'', and ''[[Street of Crocodiles]]''. The program and Nolan's short received critical acclaim, with ''[[Indiewire]]'' writing in their review that the brothers \"will undoubtedly have hundreds, if not thousands more fans because of Nolan, and for that ''The Quay Brothers in 35mm'' will always be one of latter's most important contributions to cinema\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/why-the-quay-brothers-in-35mm-is-one-of-christopher-nolans-greatest-accomplishments-20150820|title=Why 'The Quay Brothers in 35mm' is One of Christopher Nolan's Greatest Accomplishments|work=Indiewire|accessdate=21 August 2015|date=20 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150821010112/http://www.indiewire.com/article/why-the-quay-brothers-in-35mm-is-one-of-christopher-nolans-greatest-accomplishments-20150820|archive-date=21 August 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/07/27/christopher-nolan-short-film-quay?|title=Christopher Nolan's next movie is a documentary short|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=28 July 2015|date=27 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150729031620/http://www.ew.com/article/2015/07/27/christopher-nolan-short-film-quay|archive-date=29 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> An advocate for the survival of the analogue medium, Nolan and visual artist [[Tacita Dean]] invited representatives from leading American film archives, laboratories, and presenting institutions to participate in an informal summit entitled ''Reframing the Future of Film'' at the [[J. Paul Getty Museum|Getty Museum]] in March 2015.<ref name=\"filmvsdigital 2\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/columns/christopher-nolan-rallies-the-troops-to-save-celluloid-film-1201450536/ |title=Christopher Nolan Rallies the Troops to Save Celluloid Film |work=Variety |date=11 March 2015 |accessdate=12 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150313152211/http://variety.com/2015/film/columns/christopher-nolan-rallies-the-troops-to-save-celluloid-film-1201450536/ |archive-date=13 March 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jul/31/quentin-tarantino-christopher-nolan-kodak-film|title=Tarantino and Nolan share a Kodak moment as studios fund film processing|work=The Guardian|accessdate=27 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227150531/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jul/31/quentin-tarantino-christopher-nolan-kodak-film|archive-date=27 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Subsequent events were held at [[Tate Modern]] in London, [[Museo Rufino Tamayo, Mexico City|Museo Tamayo]] in [[Mexico City]], and [[Tata Theatre]] in [[Mumbai]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://filmheritagefoundation.co.in/reframing-future-film/|title=Reframing The Future Of Film|date=14 March 2018|accessdate=14 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315070645/http://filmheritagefoundation.co.in/reframing-future-film/|archive-date=15 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2015, Nolan also joined the board of directors of [[The Film Foundation]], a US-based non-profitable organisation dedicated to [[film preservation]],<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://deadline.com/2015/04/christopher-nolan-joins-film-foundation-board-1201414195/|title=Christopher Nolan Joins Film Foundation Board|magazine=Deadline|date=22 April 2015|accessdate=22 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424184303/http://deadline.com/2015/04/christopher-nolan-joins-film-foundation-board-1201414195/|archive-date=24 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and was appointed, along with [[Martin Scorsese]], by the [[Library of Congress]] to serve on the [[National Film Preservation Board]] (NFPB) as DGA representatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dga.org/News/PressReleases/2015/150507-DGA-Congratulates-Martin-Scorsese-and-Christopher-Nolan-for-NFPB-appointments.aspx|title=DGA Congratulates Martin Scorsese and Christopher Nolan on Appointments to National Film Preservation Board|publisher=The Directors Guild of America|date=7 May 2015|accessdate=19 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150521043452/http://www.dga.org/News/PressReleases/2015/150507-DGA-Congratulates-Martin-Scorsese-and-Christopher-Nolan-for-NFPB-appointments.aspx|archive-date=21 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter serving as an executive producer alongside Thomas on Zack Snyder's ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]'' (2016) and ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]'' (2017), the sequels to ''Man of Steel'',<ref name=\"BSExec\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ben-affleck-first-choice-batman-740292|title=Charles Roven: Ben Affleck \"Was the First Guy We Went to\" for Batman Role|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=13 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014094819/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ben-affleck-first-choice-batman-740292|archive-date=14 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://collider.com/christopher-nolan-ben-affleck-batman-v-superman/|title=Christopher Nolan Discusses Ben Affleck's Casting in Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice|last=Nemiroff|first=Perri|work=Collider|date=10 November 2014|accessdate=23 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314192011/http://collider.com/christopher-nolan-ben-affleck-batman-v-superman/|archive-date=14 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Nolan returned to directing with ''[[Dunkirk (2017 film)|Dunkirk]]'' (2017). Based on his own original screenplay and co-produced with Thomas, the story is set amid [[World War II]] and the [[Dunkirk evacuation|evacuation]] of [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] soldiers from the beaches of [[Dunkirk]], [[France]], in 1940. Describing the film as a survival tale with a [[triptych]] structure, Nolan wanted to make a \"sensory, almost experimental movie\" with minimal dialogue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.premiere.fr/Cinema/News-Cinema/EXCLU-Christopher-Nolan-et-ses-collaborateurs-revelent-7-infos-sur-Dunkerque|title=Christopher Nolan et ses collaborateurs r\u00e9v\u00e8lent 7 infos sur Dunkerque|work=Premi\u00e8re|accessdate=28 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228144316/http://www.premiere.fr/Cinema/News-Cinema/EXCLU-Christopher-Nolan-et-ses-collaborateurs-revelent-7-infos-sur-Dunkerque/|archive-date=28 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He said he waited to make ''Dunkirk'' until he had earned the trust of a major studio to let him make it as a British film, but with an American budget.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2017/07/08/spitfires-flotillas-boats-rough-seas-1000-extras-christopher/|title=Spitfires, flotillas of boats, rough seas and 1,000 extras: Christopher Nolan on the making of Dunkirk, his most challenging film to date|last=Nolan|first=Christopher|work=The Telegraph|date=8 July 2017|accessdate=8 July 2017|archive-url=https://archive.is/20170710035754/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2017/07/08/spitfires-flotillas-boats-rough-seas-1000-extras-christopher/|archive-date=10 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Before filming, Nolan sought advice from Spielberg, who later said in an interview with ''Variety'', \"knowing and respecting that Chris [Nolan] is one of the world's most imaginative filmmakers, my advice to him was to leave his imagination, as I did on [[Saving Private Ryan|''Ryan'']], in second position to the research he was doing to authentically acquit this historical drama.\"<ref name=\"LangVariety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/christopher-nolan-dunkirk-oscars-movies-tv-spielberg-1202607836/|title=Christopher Nolan Gets Candid on the State of Movies, Rise of TV and Spielberg's Influence|last=Lang|first=Brent|date=8 November 2017|work=Variety|accessdate=9 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108202018/http://variety.com/2017/film/news/christopher-nolan-dunkirk-oscars-movies-tv-spielberg-1202607836/|archive-date=8 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Starring [[Fionn Whitehead]], [[Jack Lowden]], [[Aneurin Barnard]], [[Harry Styles]], [[Tom Hardy]], [[Mark Rylance]], [[Cillian Murphy]], and [[Kenneth Branagh]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/harry-styles-one-direction-christopher-nolan-dunkirk-1201728153|title=Harry Styles, Fionn Whitehead to Star in Christopher Nolan WW2 Action-Thriller 'Dunkirk'|last=McNary|first=Dave|work=Variety|date=11 March 2016|accessdate=7 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504152927/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/harry-styles-one-direction-christopher-nolan-dunkirk-1201728153/|archive-date=4 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Dunkirk'' was released in theatres in July 2017 to widespread critical acclaim and strong box office results.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/dunkirk-review-roundup-what-critics-are-saying-1021889|title='Dunkirk': What the Critics Are Saying|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=17 July 2017|accessdate=19 July 2017|archive-url=https://archive.is/20170720161842/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/dunkirk-review-roundup-what-critics-are-saying-1021889|archive-date=20 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dunkirk Reviews \u2013 Metacritic|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/dunkirk/critic-reviews|accessdate=21 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170722182106/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/dunkirk/critic-reviews|archive-date=22 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/07/dunkirk-success-christopher-nolan|title=How Dunkirk, Summer's Boldest Box-Office Gamble, Paid Off|magazine=Vanity Fair|date=24 July 2017|accessdate=1 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727032810/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/07/dunkirk-success-christopher-nolan|archive-date=27 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It grossed over $525{{nbsp}}million worldwide, which made it the highest-grossing World War{{nbsp}}II film of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/dunkirk-highest-grossing-world-war-2-movie/|title=Dunkirk Becomes Highest Grossing WWII Film at Global Box Office|work=Screen Rant|date=15 September 2017|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref> In his review, [[Mick LaSalle]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' wrote: \"It's one of the best [[war film]]s ever made, distinct in its look, in its approach and in the effect it has on viewers. There are movies\u2014they are rare\u2014that lift you out of your present circumstances and immerse you so fully in another experience that you watch in a state of jaw-dropped awe. ''Dunkirk'' is that kind of movie.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Dunkirk-is-Christopher-Nolan-s-masterpiece-11297495.php | title=Not a victory, but a triumph in 'Dunkirk' | newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle | accessdate=28 May 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190528083008/https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Dunkirk-is-Christopher-Nolan-s-masterpiece-11297495.php | archive-date=28 May 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The film received [[List of accolades received by Dunkirk|many accolades]], including Nolan's first Oscar nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]].<ref name=\"Oscars-18\">{{cite web|url=http://oscar.go.com/nominees|title=Oscar Nominations 2018: The Complete List \u2013 90th Academy Awards|publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]|date=23 January 2018|accessdate=23 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219195852/http://oscar.go.com/nominees|archive-date=19 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cannes 2018 4.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Nolan (right) with [[Keir Dullea]], Katharina Kubrick, Ron Sanders and [[Jan Harlan]] at the [[2018 Cannes Film Festival]].]]\n\nIn the months following the 2017\u201318 [[Oscar season]], Nolan began supervising a new 70mm print of [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s ''2001: A Space Odyssey'' (1968), made from the [[original camera negative]]; he presented it at the [[2018 Cannes Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-ca-mn-christopher-nolan-2001-20180503-story.html|title=Christopher Nolan restores Kubrick sci-fi masterpiece '2001: A Space Odyssey' the old-fashioned way|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=3 May 2018|accessdate=3 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510210339/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-ca-mn-christopher-nolan-2001-20180503-story.html|archive-date=10 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/christopher-nolan-cannes-stanley-kubrick-space-odyssey-2001-1202354670/|title=Cannes: Christopher Nolan To Present 70mm Print Of Stanley Kubrick's '2001: A Space Odyssey'|magazine=Deadline|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=3 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180328172210/http://deadline.com/2018/03/christopher-nolan-cannes-stanley-kubrick-space-odyssey-2001-1202354670/|archive-date=28 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> While in Cannes, the director also held a two-hour masterclass at the [[Palais des Festivals et des Congr\u00e8s|Palais des Festivals]]. ''[[USA Today]]'' observed that he was greeted \"like a rock star\", and with a prolonged standing ovation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2018/05/13/cannes-festival-christopher-nolan-inspires-crazed-crowd-talks-batman/605699002/|title=Christopher Nolan inspires crazed Cannes crowd, talks 'Batman' trilogy|newspaper=USA Today|date=13 May 2018|accessdate=14 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180513200908/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2018/05/13/cannes-festival-christopher-nolan-inspires-crazed-crowd-talks-batman/605699002/|archive-date=13 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, Nolan served as executive producer on ''The Doll's Breath'', an animated short directed by the Quay brothers.<ref name=\"Quay-Doll\">{{cite web|url=https://www.illuminationsmedia.co.uk/the-dolls-breath/|title=The Doll's Breath|publisher=illuminationsmedia|accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Upcoming projects ====\nNolan's eleventh feature, ''[[Tenet (film)|Tenet]]'', is scheduled to be released by Warner Bros. on 17 July 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20190522005664/en/Filming-Underway-%E2%80%9CTenet%E2%80%9D-New-Film-Christopher-Nolan|title=Filming is Underway on \"Tenet,\" a New Film from Christopher Nolan|website=Business Wire|date=22 May 2019|accessdate=22 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190523184738/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20190522005664/en/Filming-Underway-%25E2%2580%259CTenet%25E2%2580%259D-New-Film-Christopher-Nolan|archive-date=23 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Nolan wrote the screenplay and is producing with Emma Thomas. The film stars [[John David Washington]], [[Robert Pattinson]], [[Elizabeth Debicki]], [[Aaron Taylor-Johnson]], [[Dimple Kapadia]], [[Cl\u00e9mence Po\u00e9sy]], Kenneth Branagh and Michael Caine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/christopher-nolan-casts-pattinson-debicki/|title=Christopher Nolan's Next Film Adds Twilight, Guardians of the Galaxy Stars|website=[[CBR.com]]|last=Zachary|first=Brandon|date=21 March 2019|accessdate=22 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322122238/https://www.cbr.com/christopher-nolan-casts-pattinson-debicki/|archive-date=22 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Filmmaking ==\n{{Main|Cinematic style of Christopher Nolan}}\n\nNolan's films are often grounded in [[Existentialism|existential]] and [[Epistemology|epistemological]] themes, exploring the concepts of time, memory, and identity.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.grin.com/en/e-book/205383/time-memory-identity-the-films-of-christopher-nolan|title=Time, Memory & Identity: The Films of Christopher Nolan|year=2009|work=Grin \u2013 Master's Thesis written by Stuart Joy|accessdate=17 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201194745/http://www.grin.com/en/e-book/205383/time-memory-identity-the-films-of-christopher-nolan|archive-date=1 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Parks\">{{cite web|url=http://widescreenjournal.org/index.php/journal/article/viewFile/96/146|title=Identity Construction and Ambiguity in Christopher Nolan's Films|last=Parks|first=Erin Hill|date=June 2011|work=Widescreenjournal|accessdate=11 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425051550/http://widescreenjournal.org/index.php/journal/article/viewFile/96/146|archive-date=25 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://utpress.utexas.edu/index.php/books/mcgfic|title=The Fictional Christopher Nolan|publisher=University of Texas Press|accessdate=5 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005200914/http://utpress.utexas.edu/index.php/books/mcgfic|archive-date=5 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> His work is characterised by unconventional [[nonlinear narrative|narrative structures]], richly textured [[imagery]], and evocative use of music and sound.<ref name=\"Shone2014\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/nov/17/interstellar-sound-christopher-nolan|title=Interstellar's sound 'right for an experimental film', says Nolan|work=The Guardian|accessdate=29 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141117151023/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/nov/17/interstellar-sound-christopher-nolan|archive-date=17 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Film theory|Film theorist]] [[David Bordwell]] opined that Nolan has been able to blend his \"experimental impulses\" with the demands of mainstream entertainment, further describing his oeuvre as, \"experiments with cinematic time by means of techniques of subjective viewpoint and crosscutting.\"<ref name=\"Bordwell2019\">{{cite web|url=http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2019/01/28/nolan-book-2-0-cerebral-blockbusters-meet-blunt-force-cinephilia/|title=Nolan book 2.0: Cerebral blockbusters meet blunt-force cinephilia|last=Bordwell|first=David|date=28 January 2019|work=Observations on film art|accessdate=11 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190909104313/http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2019/01/28/nolan-book-2-0-cerebral-blockbusters-meet-blunt-force-cinephilia/|archive-date=9 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Nolan's use of practical, in-camera effects, miniatures and models, as well as shooting on celluloid film, has been highly influential in early [[Hollywood cinema in 21st century|21st century cinema]].<ref name=\"IndieW-19\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/influencers-team-christopher-nolan-1202192592/|title=Influencers: Christopher Nolan's Team Is the Big-Budget, Practical-Filmmaking Alternative|publisher=Indiewire|accessdate=12 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191203181719/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/influencers-team-christopher-nolan-1202192592/|archive-date=3 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''IndieWire'' wrote in 2019 that the director \"kept a viable alternate model of big-budget filmmaking alive\" in an era where blockbuster filmmaking has become \"a largely computer-generated art form.\"<ref name=\"IndieW-19\"/>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Christopher Nolan and Emma Thomas.jpg|thumb|Nolan and his wife [[Emma Thomas]] in January 2011]]\nNolan is married to [[Emma Thomas]], whom he met at University College London when he was 19.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/><ref name=\"British Cinematographer pt2\"/> She has worked as a producer on all of his films, and together they founded the production company [[Syncopy Inc.]]<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.empireonline.com/features/a-z/christopher-nolan/7.asp|accessdate=18 January 2014|magazine=Empire|title=The Z To A Of Christopher Nolan|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924051944/http://www.empireonline.com/features/a-z/christopher-nolan/7.asp|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The couple have four children and reside in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Christopher Nolan biography |publisher=Entertainment Scene 360 |url=http://www.entertainmentscene360.com/index.php/christopher-nolan-biography-252/ |accessdate=18 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202143859/http://www.entertainmentscene360.com/index.php/christopher-nolan-biography-252/ |archivedate=2 February 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/christopher-nolan|title=Christopher Nolan profile|magazine=Forbes|accessdate=18 January 2014|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140120171246/http://www.forbes.com/profile/christopher-nolan/|archive-date=20 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Protective of his privacy, he rarely discusses his personal life in interviews.<ref name=\"Lewis-Kraus\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/02/magazine/the-exacting-expansive-mind-of-christopher-nolan.html|last=Lewis-Kraus|first=Gideon|title=The Exacting, Expansive Mind of Christopher Nolan|work=The New York Times|accessdate=6 March 2016|date=30 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516070132/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/02/magazine/the-exacting-expansive-mind-of-christopher-nolan.html|archive-date=16 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> However, he has publicly shared some of his sociopolitical concerns for the future, such as the current conditions of nuclear weapons and environmental issues that he says need to be addressed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/christopher-nolan-uncut-on-interstellar-ben-afflecks-batman-and-the-future-of-mankind|accessdate=15 August 2017|website=The Daily Beast|title=Christopher Nolan Uncut: On 'Interstellar,' Ben Affleck's Batman, and the Future of Mankind|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730050522/http://www.thedailybeast.com/christopher-nolan-uncut-on-interstellar-ben-afflecks-batman-and-the-future-of-mankind|archive-date=30 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He has also expressed an admiration for [[scientific objectivity]], wishing it were applied \"in every aspect of our civilization.\"<ref name=\"ThorneNolan\">{{cite web|title=Watch Christopher Nolan and Kip Thorne Discuss the Physics of Interstellar|url=http://time.com/3602525/christopher-nolan-physics-interstellar-kip-thorne/|work=Time|accessdate=15 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160214175028/http://time.com/3602525/christopher-nolan-physics-interstellar-kip-thorne/|archive-date=14 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He is [[Red-Green color blindness|red-green colour blind]].<ref name=\"BAFTA-Pictures\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bafta.org/media-centre/transcripts/christopher-nolan-a-life-in-pictures | title=A Life in Pictures: Christopher Nolan | work=BAFTA | date=2 December 2017 | accessdate=21 April 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421091746/http://www.bafta.org/media-centre/transcripts/christopher-nolan-a-life-in-pictures | archive-date=21 April 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nNolan prefers not to use a mobile phone or an email address,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/dark-knight-rises-christopher-nolan-batman-352120 | title='Dark Knight Rises' Director Christopher Nolan's Shocking Admission: No Cell Phone, Email Address | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=19 July 2012 | accessdate=20 May 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803201801/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/dark-knight-rises-christopher-nolan-batman-352120 | archive-date=3 August 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> saying, \"It's not that I'm a [[Luddite]] and don't like technology; I've just never been interested ... When I moved to Los Angeles in 1997, nobody really had cell phones, and I just never went down that path.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.backstage.com/news/christopher-nolan-embraces-film-tech-but-doesnt-own-a-cell-phone/ | title=Christopher Nolan Embraces Film Tech But Doesn't Own a Cell Phone | work=Backstage | date=18 July 2012 | accessdate=6 January 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306082838/http://www.backstage.com/news/christopher-nolan-embraces-film-tech-but-doesnt-own-a-cell-phone/ | archive-date=6 March 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> He also prohibits use of phones on set.<ref name=\"cell phones on set\">{{cite web | url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/list-directors-interviewed-sam-mendes/ | title=A-List Directors, interviewed by Sam Mendes | work=Empire | date=21 October 2015 | accessdate=29 January 2015 | last=Mendes | first=Sam | authorlink=Sam Mendes | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029225147/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/list-directors-interviewed-sam-mendes/ | archive-date=29 October 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Recognition ==\nHaving made some of the most influential and popular films of his time,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/06/30/a-man-and-his-dream-christopher-nolan-and-inception/?|title=A Man and His Dream: Christopher Nolan and Inception|date=30 June 2010|work=The New York Times|accessdate=20 December 2013|first=Dave|last=Itzkoff|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140105012419/http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/06/30/a-man-and-his-dream-christopher-nolan-and-inception/|archive-date=5 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/tv-movie-creatives-that-defined-the-2010s/christopher-nolan|title=The Creatives That Defined the 2010s|publisher=Complex|accessdate=23 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/christopher-nolan-was-the-most-influential-filmmaker-of-00s/|title=Why Christopher Nolan Was the Quintessential Filmmaker of the 2000s|date=28 July 2017|work=Slashfilm|accessdate=11 January 2020|first=Joshua|last=Meyer}}</ref> Nolan's work has been as \"intensely embraced, analyzed and debated by ordinary film fans as by critics and film academics\".<ref name=\"Lewis-Kraus\"/><ref name=\"Descriptions\">{{cite web|title=An Evening with Christopher Nolan |url=http://www.ifccenter.com/films/an-evening-with-christopher-nolan |publisher=The Film Society of Lincoln Center \u2013 descriptions courtesy of The Criterion Collection and Film Society of Lincoln Center |accessdate=6 July 2013 |date=27 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130724221708/http://www.ifccenter.com/films/an-evening-with-christopher-nolan/ |archivedate=24 July 2013 }}</ref> Several of his films have been regarded by critics as among the best of their respective decades,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critics-pick-the-best-movies-of-the-decade|title=Film Critics Pick the Best Movies of the Decade|website=Metacritic.com |date=3 January 2010|accessdate=23 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-movies-of-the-decade-2010s|title=Best Movies of the Decade (2010-19)|website=Metacritic.com |date=18 December 2019|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://film.avclub.com/the-best-films-of-the-00s-1798222348|title=The best films of the '00s|accessdate=27 November 2019|newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]]| date=3 December 2009 |first1=Keith |last1=Phipps |first2=Tasha |last2=Robinson |first3=Nathan |last3=Rabin |first4=Scott |last4=Tobias |first5=Noel |last5=Murray}}</ref> and according to ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', his \"ability to combine box-office success with artistic ambition has given him an extraordinary amount of clout in the industry.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://online.wsj.com/articles/why-hollywood-loves-interstellar-director-christopher-nolan-1414677657|title=Why Hollywood Loves 'Interstellar' Director Christopher Nolan|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=30 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102063958/http://online.wsj.com/articles/why-hollywood-loves-interstellar-director-christopher-nolan-1414677657|archive-date=2 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, ''Memento'', ''The Dark Knight'', and ''Inception'' appeared in [[BBC's 100 Greatest Films of the 21st Century]] list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20160819-the-21st-centurys-100-greatest-films |title=The 21st Century's 100 greatest films |publisher=BBC |date=23 August 2016 |accessdate=21 January 2017}}</ref> In the following year, five of his (then nine) films featured in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine's poll of \"The 100 Greatest Movies\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/best-movies/|title=The 100 Greatest Movies|website=Empireonline.com |date=23 June 2017|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' categorised Nolan as a \"brand-name director\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/23/business/media/in-blockbuster-era-no-room-at-the-box-office-for-the-middlebrow.html|title=In Blockbuster Era, No Room at the Box Office for the Middlebrow|date=23 November 2019|work=The New York Times|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> while ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' described him as \"a Hollywood franchise unto himself.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/thr-100-hollywood-reporters-powerful-people-entertainment-1142979/item/thr-100-2018-randy-freer-1143892|title=The Hollywood Reporter 100: The Most Powerful People in Entertainment 2018|date=20 September 2018|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Geoff Andrew]] of the [[British Film Institute]] and ''[[Sight & Sound]]'' magazine, called Nolan \"a persuasively inventive storyteller\", singling him out as one of the few contemporary filmmakers producing highly personal films within the Hollywood mainstream. He also pointed out that Nolan's films are as notable for their \"considerable technical virtuosity and visual flair\" as for their \"brilliant narrative ingenuity and their unusually adult interest in complex philosophical questions\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://whatson.bfi.org.uk/Online/default.asp?doWork::WScontent::loadArticle=Load&BOparam::WScontent::loadArticle::article_id=92EC9074-583B-4953-AAFA-52B5F705731C|title=Christopher Nolan|year=2012|work=British Film Institute|accessdate=17 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620180635/https://whatson.bfi.org.uk/Online/default.asp?doWork::WScontent::loadArticle=Load&BOparam::WScontent::loadArticle::article_id=92EC9074-583B-4953-AAFA-52B5F705731C|archive-date=20 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/arts-and-books/widescreen-hollywoods-big-ideas|title=Widescreen: Hollywood's big ideas|publisher=Prospect|accessdate=30 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816232932/http://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/arts-and-books/widescreen-hollywoods-big-ideas|archive-date=16 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> David Bordwell observed that Nolan is \"considered one of the most accomplished living filmmakers,\" citing his ability to turn genre movies into both art and event films, as well as his box office numbers, critical acclaim, and popularity among cinemagoers.<ref name=\"Bordwell2019\">{{cite web|url=http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2019/01/28/nolan-book-2-0-cerebral-blockbusters-meet-blunt-force-cinephilia/|title=Nolan book 2.0: Cerebral blockbusters meet blunt-force cinephilia|last=Bordwell|first=David|date=28 January 2019|work=Observations on film art|accessdate=11 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190909104313/http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2019/01/28/nolan-book-2-0-cerebral-blockbusters-meet-blunt-force-cinephilia/|archive-date=9 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BordwellDunkirk\">{{cite web|title=DUNKIRK Part 2: The art film as event movie|url=http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2017/08/09/dunkirk-part-2-the-art-film-as-event-movie/|work=Observations on film art|accessdate=10 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810170522/http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2017/08/09/dunkirk-part-2-the-art-film-as-event-movie/|archive-date=10 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2008, film critic [[Philip French]] deemed Nolan \"The first major talent to emerge this [21st] century\",<ref name=\"French-50\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/apr/13/features.culture2|title=The top 50|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=21 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227024901/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/apr/13/features.culture2|archive-date=27 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> while ''[[Forbes]]'' called him \"one of the most successful and acclaimed filmmakers of our time\" in 2015.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/markhughes/2015/09/11/why-akira-could-be-christopher-nolans-next-film/#5d198de21474|title=Why 'Akira' Could Be Christopher Nolan's Next Film|magazine=Forbes|accessdate=30 June 2019|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630115858/https://www.forbes.com/sites/markhughes/2015/09/11/why-akira-could-be-christopher-nolans-next-film/#5d198de21474|archive-date=30 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Film critic [[Mark Kermode]] complimented the director for bringing \"the discipline and ethics of art-house independent moviemaking\" to Hollywood blockbusters, calling him \"living proof that you don't have to appeal to the lowest common denominator to be profitable\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenational.ae/lifestyle/newsmaker-christopher-nolan-is-a-different-kind-of-storyteller#page2|title=Newsmaker: Christopher Nolan is a different kind of storyteller|date=14 June 2013|publisher=The National|accessdate=21 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223144206/http://www.thenational.ae/lifestyle/newsmaker-christopher-nolan-is-a-different-kind-of-storyteller#page2|archive-date=23 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Observer]]'' described Nolan as a \"skilful, stylish storyteller, capable of combining the spectacle of Spielberg with the intellectual intricacy of [[Nicolas Roeg]] or [[Alain Resnais]]\".<ref name=\"Observer17\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/jul/22/christopher-nolan-dunkirk-batman-observer-profile-profile|last=Gilbey|first=Ryan|title=Christopher Nolan: from superheroes to Dunkirk's small tales of heroism|accessdate=30 June 2019|date=23 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630131849/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/jul/22/christopher-nolan-dunkirk-batman-observer-profile-profile|archive-date=30 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mark Cousins (film critic)|Mark Cousins]] applauded the director for embracing big ideas, \"Hollywood filmmakers generally shy away from ideas \u2014 but not Christopher Nolan\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/magazine/widescreen-hollywoods-big-ideas|title=Widescreen: Hollywood's big ideas|publisher=Prospect Magazine|accessdate=5 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720171750/https://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/magazine/widescreen-hollywoods-big-ideas|archive-date=20 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Scott Foundas of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' declared Nolan \"the premier big-canvas storyteller of his generation\",<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/film-review-interstellar-1201338475/|title=Film Review: 'Interstellar'|magazine=Variety|accessdate=30 October 2014|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141029234605/http://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/film-review-interstellar-1201338475/|archive-date=29 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> while [[Justin Chang]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called him \"the great [[proceduralist]] of 21st century blockbuster filmmaking, a lover of nuts-and-bolts minutiae.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-ca-mn-dark-knight-10th-anniversary-20180822-story.html|title=Ten years after it changed Hollywood, 'The Dark Knight' is back in theaters. Accept no substitutes|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=23 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822230952/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-ca-mn-dark-knight-10th-anniversary-20180822-story.html|archive-date=22 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe filmmaker has been praised by many of his contemporaries, and some have cited his work as influencing their own.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2016/06/duncan-jones-warcraft-christopher-nolan-moon-mute-interview-1201682897/|title=Duncan Jones on How He Models His Career After Christopher Nolan \u2013 Q&A|date=2 June 2017|work=Indiewire|accessdate=11 April 2019|first=Kate|last=Erbland|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411124616/https://www.indiewire.com/2016/06/duncan-jones-warcraft-christopher-nolan-moon-mute-interview-1201682897/|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/sam-mendes-says-he-was-not-at-all-interested-in-bond-at-first-took-direct-inspiration-from-christopher-nolans-dark-knight-films-20121018|title=Sam Mendes Says He Was \"Not at All\" Interested in Bond at First, Took Direct Inspiration From Nolan's 'Dark Knight' Films|date=18 October 2012|publisher=The Playlist|accessdate=26 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130110082142/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/sam-mendes-says-he-was-not-at-all-interested-in-bond-at-first-took-direct-inspiration-from-christopher-nolans-dark-knight-films-20121018|archive-date=10 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.empireonline.com/features/the-dark-knight-effect|title=The Dark Knight Effect \u2013 How Hollywood fell for \u2013 and learned from \u2013 the greatest superhero sequel ever made|date=23 July 2012|magazine=Empire|accessdate=26 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113083236/http://www.empireonline.com/features/the-dark-knight-effect|archive-date=13 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Rupert Wyatt]] said in an interview that he thinks of Nolan as a \"trailblazer{{nbsp}}... he is to be hugely admired as a master filmmaker, but also someone who has given others behind him a stick to beat back the naysayers who never thought a modern mass audience would be willing to embrace story and character as much as spectacle\".<ref name=\"Harding\">{{cite web|url=http://whatculture.com/film/exclusive-interview-rupert-wyatt-on-birdsong-why-he-quit-planet-of-the-apes.php#|last=Harding|first=Oscar|title=Exclusive Interview: Rupert Wyatt On Birdsong & Why He Quit Planet Of The Apes|work=Whatculture!|accessdate=4 June 2013|date=15 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605074302/http://whatculture.com/film/exclusive-interview-rupert-wyatt-on-birdsong-why-he-quit-planet-of-the-apes.php|archive-date=5 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Kenneth Branagh called Nolan's approach to large-scale filmmaking \"unique in modern cinema\", adding \"regardless of how popular his movies become, he remains an artist and an [[auteur]]. I think for that reason he has become a heroic figure for both the audience and the people working behind the camera.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://roadshow.com.au/articles/2017/6/kenneth-branagh-on-dunkirk |title=Kenneth Branagh on Dunkirk and The Nolan Experience |publisher=Roadshow |date=29 June 2017 |accessdate=25 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180325232650/https://roadshow.com.au/articles/2017/6/kenneth-branagh-on-dunkirk |archive-date=25 March 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Michael Mann (director)|Michael Mann]] complimented Nolan for his \"singular vision\" and called him \"a complete auteur\".<ref name=ShoneBlogspot>{{cite web|first=Tom|last=Shone|url=http://tomshone.blogspot.no/2014/11/christopher-nolan-directors-cut.html|title=Christopher Nolan: The Director's Cut|publisher=These Violent Delights, Tom Shone|date=4 November 2014|accessdate=23 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105014410/http://tomshone.blogspot.no/2014/11/christopher-nolan-directors-cut.html|archive-date=5 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Nicolas Roeg said of Nolan, \"[His] films have a magic to them{{nbsp}}... People talk about 'commercial art' and the term is usually self-negating; Nolan works in the commercial arena and yet there's something very poetic about his work.\"<ref name=\"ShoneBlogspot\"/> Martin Scorsese identified Nolan as a filmmaker creating \"beautifully made films on a big scale\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://filmtalk.org/2015/10/26/martin-scorsese-theres-always-the-budget-but-i-am-more-concerned-about-the-creative-freedom/|title=Martin Scorsese: There's always the budget, but I am more concerned about the creative freedom|date=26 October 2015|publisher=Filmtalk|accessdate=13 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025044907/https://filmtalk.org/2015/10/26/martin-scorsese-theres-always-the-budget-but-i-am-more-concerned-about-the-creative-freedom/|archive-date=25 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\nand [[Luca Guadagnino]] called him \"one of the ultimate auteurs.\"<ref name=Guadagnino>{{cite news|url=http://the-talks.com/interview/luca-guadagnino|title=Luca Guadagnino: \"I Try To Surrender To My Evidences\"|author=Kaleem Aftab|date=21 March 2018|work=The Talks|accessdate=21 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723190031/https://the-talks.com/interview/luca-guadagnino/|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Damien Chazelle]] said of Nolan, \"This is a filmmaker who has managed, time and again, to make the most seemingly impersonal projects \u2014 superhero epics, deep-space mind-benders \u2014 feel deeply personal\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/gallery/directors-on-directors-get-out-lady-bird/#!2/dunkirk-13|title=Damien Chazelle on ''Dunkirk''|magazine=Variety|accessdate=6 December 2017|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206041800/http://variety.com/gallery/directors-on-directors-get-out-lady-bird/#!2/dunkirk-13|archive-date=6 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Olivier Assayas]] said he admired Nolan for \"making movies that are really unlike anything else. The way I see it, he has a really authentic voice.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://filmtalk.org/2016/10/13/olivier-assayas-kristens-stewart-approach-to-acting-is-very-honest-very-human-and-very-pure/|title=Olivier Assayas: Kristen Stewart's approach to acting is very honest, very human and very pure|publisher=Film Talk|accessdate=14 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116165102/https://filmtalk.org/2016/10/13/olivier-assayas-kristens-stewart-approach-to-acting-is-very-honest-very-human-and-very-pure/|archive-date=16 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Discussing the difference between [[art film]]s and big studio blockbusters, [[Steven Spielberg]] referred to Nolan's ''Dark Knight'' series as an example of both;<ref>{{cite web|url=//www.youtube.com/watch?v=r69N56plrDE|title=In conversation with Steven Spielberg and Stacey Snider on The Front Row|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=16 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130728072836/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r69N56plrDE|archive-date=28 July 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> he has described ''Memento'' and ''Inception'' as \"masterworks\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.azcentral.com/thingstodo/movies/articles/2011/12/09/20111209steven-spielbergs-interview-goodykoontz-tintin-warhorse.html|title=Interview: Steven Spielberg talks movies 'Tintin,' 'War Horse'|date=19 December 2011|publisher=AzCentral|accessdate=26 January 2013}}</ref> [[Denis Villeneuve]] said of Nolan, \"[He] is a very impressive filmmaker, because he is able to keep his identity and create his own universe in that large scope ... To bring intellectual concepts and to bring them in that scope to the screen right now \u2014 it's very rare. Every movie that he comes out with, I have more admiration for his work.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/12/denis-villenueve-influences-christopher-nolan-steven-spielberg-ingmar-bergman-1201904623/|title=Denis Villenueve Aspires to Be Like Christopher Nolan, and Why He Wants to Make 'Dune'|date=22 December 2017|work=Indiewire|accessdate=23 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223192347/https://www.indiewire.com/2017/12/denis-villenueve-influences-christopher-nolan-steven-spielberg-ingmar-bergman-1201904623/|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSome of his films have been referenced extensively in popular culture,<ref>Eberl, Dunn, p. 1.</ref> and in 2013 a survey of seventeen film academics showed that Nolan was among the most studied directors in Britain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a529084/quentin-tarantino-is-most-studied-director-in-the-uk.html|title=Quentin Tarantino is most-studied director in the UK|date=6 November 2013|website=Digital Spy|accessdate=6 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131108105528/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a529084/quentin-tarantino-is-most-studied-director-in-the-uk.html|archive-date=8 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Nolan appeared in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'s}} [[Time 100|100 most influential people in the world]] in 2015 and in the [[Forbes Celebrity 100|''Forbes'' Celebrity 100]] in 2011 and 2013.<ref>[http://time.com/3822892/christopher-nolan-2015-time-100 \"Christopher Nolan\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417010758/http://time.com/3822892/christopher-nolan-2015-time-100/ |date=17 April 2015 }}, ''Time'', 16 April 2015; retrieved 16 April 2015.</ref><ref name=\"forbes-2011\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2012/celebrities/celebrity-100_2011.html|title=The World's Most Powerful Celebrities|magazine=Forbes|accessdate=29 January 2018|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160905004028/http://www.forbes.com/lists/2012/celebrities/celebrity-100_2011.html|archive-date=5 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography and awards ==\n{{Main|Christopher Nolan filmography|List of awards and nominations received by Christopher Nolan|l2=awards and nominations}}\n[[File:Christopher Nolan TCL.jpg|thumb|right|Nolan's hand and shoeprints in front of the [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]] in Hollywood]]\n\nNolan was named an Honorary Fellow of UCL in 2006, and conferred an [[Honorary degree|honorary doctorate]] in literature (DLit) in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/about-ucl/who-we-are/honorary-fellows|title=Honorary Fellows of UCL|publisher=UCL|year=2006|accessdate=11 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923115521/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/about-ucl/who-we-are/honorary-fellows|archive-date=23 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/campaign/campaign-news/christopher_nolan_honorary_doctorate|title=Back to where it all began: Christopher Nolan awarded honorary doctorate at UCL|publisher=UCL|year=2017|accessdate=15 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170916074807/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/campaign/campaign-news/christopher_nolan_honorary_doctorate|archive-date=16 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2012, he became the youngest director to receive a hand-and-footprint ceremony at [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2012/07/07/christopher-nolan-hand-and-footprint-ceremony/ |title=Christopher Nolan Hand and Footprint Ceremony, EW Magazine |access-date=28 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120808193929/http://insidemovies.ew.com/2012/07/07/christopher-nolan-hand-and-footprint-ceremony/ |archive-date=8 August 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Nolan was appointed Commander of the [[Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the [[2019 New Year Honours]] for his services to film.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/767769/DSO_NY19_CH___BE_HMTQ.pdf|title=OFFICIAL SENSITIVE \u2013 HONOURS|date=29 December 2018|accessdate=29 December 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190114225012/https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/767769/DSO_NY19_CH___BE_HMTQ.pdf|archive-date=14 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n'''Directed features:'''\n* ''[[Following]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Memento (film)|Memento]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Insomnia (2002 film)|Insomnia]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Batman Begins]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Prestige (film)|The Prestige]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Inception]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[The Dark Knight Rises]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Interstellar (film)|Interstellar]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Dunkirk (2017 film)|Dunkirk]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Tenet (film)|Tenet]]'' (2020)\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-ua}}\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Gouda|first=Soman|title=Yogi in Suits:Christopher Nolan and Vedanta|url=https://g.co/kgs/VthdpH |date=24 March 2018|publisher=SomeKranthi|isbn=978-1-9806-1543-9}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Conard|first=Mark|title=The Philosophy of Neo-Noir|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6J5uLqU8y58C&pg=PA35|date=5 January 2007|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=978-0-8131-7230-9}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Kellner|first=Douglas M|title=Cinema Wars: Hollywood Film and Politics in the Bush-Cheney Era|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GrQnyVqWBzYC&pg=PA2011 |date=21 December 2009|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell; 1 edition|isbn=978-1405198240}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Duncan Jesser |first1=Jody |first2=Janine |last2=Pourroy |title=The Art and Making of The Dark Knight Trilogy |publisher=Abrams |year=2012 |isbn=978-1-4197-0369-0}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Fischer |first=Mark |title=The Lost Unconscious: Delusions and Dreams in Inception. |publisher=Film Quarterly, Volume 64 (3) University of California Press |year=2011}}\n* {{Cite book |last=McGowan |first=Todd |title=The Fictional Christopher Nolan |location=Texas |publisher=the University of Texas Press |year=2012 |isbn=978-0-292-73782-2 }}\n* {{Cite book |last=Mottram |first=James |title=The Making of Memento |location=New York |publisher=Faber |year=2002 |isbn=0-571-21488-6 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/makingofmemento00mott }}\n* {{Cite book |last1=deWaard |first1=Andrew |first2=R. Colin |last2=Tait |title=The Cinema of Steven Soderbergh: Indie Sex, Corporate Lies, and Digital Videotape |publisher=Columbia University Press |year=2013 |isbn=978-0-231-16551-8}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Rabiger |first1=Michael |first2=Mick |last2=Hurbis-Cherrier |title=Directing: Film Techniques and Aesthetics |publisher=CRC Press |year=2013 |isbn=978-1-135-09921-3}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=O'Sullivan |first1=Natalia |first2=Nicola |last2=Graydon |title=The Ancestral Continuum: Unlock the Secrets of Who You Really Are |publisher=Simon and Schuster |year=2013 |isbn=978-1-451-67454-5}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Furby |first1=Jacqueline |first2=Stuart |last2=Joy |title=The Cinema of Christopher Nolan: Imagining the Impossible |publisher=Columbia University Press |year=2015 |isbn=978-0-231-85076-6}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Eberl |first1=Jason T. |first2=George A. |last2=Dunn |title=The Philosophy of Christopher Nolan |publisher=Lexington Books |year=2017 |isbn=978-1-498-51352-4}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Abad |first=Jos\u00e9 |title=Christopher Nolan |location=Madrid |publisher=C\u00e1tedra |year=2018 |isbn=978-84-376-3772-3}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Mooney |first=Darren |title=Christopher Nolan: A Critical Study of the Films |publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc. |year=2018 |isbn=978-14-766-7480-3}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Cameron |first=James |title=James Cameron's Story of Science Fiction |publisher=Simon and Schuster |year=2018 |isbn=978-16-838-3590-5}}\n\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q25191|c=category:Christopher Nolan|b=no|v=no|voy=no|s=no|wikt=no|n=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no}}\n* {{IMDb name|634240}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes person|christopher_nolan|Christopher Nolan}}\n* {{Allmovie name|240025|Christopher Nolan}}\n* [http://www.tribute.ca/people/christopher-nolan/6453/35045/ Christopher Nolan Biography] at [http://www.tribute.ca Tribute.ca]\n* [http://www.indiefilmhustle.com/christopher-nolan/ Christopher Nolan \u2013 How to Direct Your First Feature Film]\n{{Christopher Nolan|state=expanded}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Christopher Nolan|Awards for Christopher Nolan]]\n|list  =\n{{AACTA International Award for Best Direction}}\n{{BAFTA Los Angeles Britannia Awards}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Screenplay}}\n{{Empire Award for Best Director}}\n{{IndependentAwardforBest